{"title_page": "Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski\n| other_name = Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski Commune\n| settlement_type = [[Gmina]]\n| image_flag =\n| image_shield = POL Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski COA.svg\n| image_map =Zielonogorski-nowogrod bobrzanski.gif\n|map_caption = Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski in Zielona G\u00f3ra County\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|48|N|15|14|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint = Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Lubusz Voivodeship|Lubusz]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Zielona G\u00f3ra]]\n| seat = [[Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski]]\n| total_type = Total\n| area_total_km2 = 259.41\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n| population_total = 9487\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_urban = 5165\n| population_rural = 4322\n| website = {{URL|http://www.nowogrodbobrz.pl}}\n}}\n__NOTOC__\n'''Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski''' is an urban-rural [[gmina]] (administrative district) in [[Zielona G\u00f3ra County]], [[Lubusz Voivodeship]], in western [[Poland]]. Its seat is the town of [[Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski]], which lies approximately {{convert|25|km|mi|0}} south-west of [[Zielona G\u00f3ra]].\n\nThe gmina covers an area of {{convert|259.41|km2|sqmi|2}}, and as of 2019 its total population is 9,487.\n\n==Villages==\nApart from the town of Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski, Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski contains the villages and settlements of [[Bia\u0142owice]], [[Bogacz\u00f3w, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Bogacz\u00f3w]], [[Ciesz\u00f3w, Lubusz Voivodeship|Ciesz\u00f3w]], [[Dobrosz\u00f3w Ma\u0142y]], [[Dobrosz\u00f3w Wielki]], [[Dr\u0105gowina, Lubusz Voivodeship|Dr\u0105gowina]], [[Kaczenice]], [[Kamionka, Lubusz Voivodeship|Kamionka]], [[Kl\u0119pina]], [[Kotowice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Kotowice]], [[Krzewiny, Lubusz Voivodeship|Krzewiny]], [[Krzywa, Lubusz Voivodeship|Krzywa]], [[Krzywaniec]], [[\u0141agoda]], [[Niwiska, Lubusz Voivodeship|Niwiska]], [[Paj\u0119czno, Lubusz Voivodeship|Paj\u0119czno]], [[Pielice, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Pielice]], [[Pierzwin]], [[Podg\u00f3rzyce, Lubusz Voivodeship|Podg\u00f3rzyce]], [[Popowice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Popowice]], [[Przybymierz]], [[Skibice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Skibice]], [[Sobolice, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Sobolice]], [[Sterk\u00f3w]], [[Tur\u00f3w, Lubusz Voivodeship|Tur\u00f3w]], [[Urzuty, Lubusz Voivodeship|Urzuty]] and [[Wysoka, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Wysoka]].\n\n==Neighbouring gminas==\nGmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski is bordered by the gminas of [[Gmina Bobrowice|Bobrowice]], [[Gmina Brze\u017anica, Lubusz Voivodeship|Brze\u017anica]], [[Gmina D\u0105bie, Lubusz Voivodeship|D\u0105bie]], [[Gmina Jasie\u0144|Jasie\u0144]], [[Gmina Ko\u017cuch\u00f3w|Ko\u017cuch\u00f3w]], [[Gmina Lubsko|Lubsko]], [[Gmina \u015awidnica, Lubusz Voivodeship|\u015awidnica]], [[Gmina \u017baga\u0144|\u017baga\u0144]], [[Gmina \u017bary|\u017bary]] and [[Gmina Zielona G\u00f3ra|Zielona G\u00f3ra]].\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Poland}}\nGmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski is [[Sister city|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Gminy partnerskie|url=https://nowogrodbobrz.pl/?page_id=1652|website=nowogrodbobrz.pl|publisher=Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski|language=pl|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|MDA}} [[Cimi\u0219lia]], Moldova\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[L\u00fcbbenau]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|NED}} [[Westerwolde (municipality)|Westerwolde]], Netherlands\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski}}\n{{Zielona G\u00f3ra County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gmina Nowogrod Bobrzanski}}\n[[Category:Gminas in Lubusz Voivodeship|Nowogrod Bobrzanski]]\n[[Category:Zielona G\u00f3ra County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski\n| other_name = Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski Commune\n| settlement_type = [[Gmina]]\n| image_flag =\n| image_shield = POL Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski COA.svg\n| image_map =Zielonogorski-nowogrod bobrzanski.gif\n|map_caption = Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski in Zielona G\u00f3ra County\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|48|N|15|14|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint = Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{POL}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Lubusz Voivodeship|Lubusz]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[Powiat|County]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Zielona G\u00f3ra]]\n| seat = [[Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski]]\n| total_type = Total\n| area_total_km2 = 259.41\n| population_as_of = 2019-06-30<ref>{{cite web |title=Population. Size and structure and vital statistics in Poland by territorial divison in 2019. As of 30th June|url=https://stat.gov.pl/en/topics/population/population/population-size-and-structure-and-vital-statistics-in-poland-by-territorial-divison-in-2019-as-of-30th-june,3,26.html|website=stat.gov.pl|publisher=Statistics Poland|date=2019-10-15|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n| population_total = 9487\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_urban = 5165\n| population_rural = 4322\n| website = {{URL|http://www.nowogrodbobrz.pl}}\n}}\n__NOTOC__\n'''Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski''' is an urban-rural [[gmina]] (administrative district) in [[Zielona G\u00f3ra County]], [[Lubusz Voivodeship]], in western [[Poland]]. Its seat is the town of [[Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski]], which lies approximately {{convert|25|km|mi|0}} south-west of [[Zielona G\u00f3ra]].\n\nThe gmina covers an area of {{convert|259.41|km2|sqmi|2}}, and as of 2019 its total population is 9,487.\n\n==Villages==\nApart from the town of Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski, Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski contains the villages and settlements of [[Bia\u0142owice]], [[Bogacz\u00f3w, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Bogacz\u00f3w]], [[Ciesz\u00f3w, Lubusz Voivodeship|Ciesz\u00f3w]], [[Dobrosz\u00f3w Ma\u0142y]], [[Dobrosz\u00f3w Wielki]], [[Dr\u0105gowina, Lubusz Voivodeship|Dr\u0105gowina]], [[Kaczenice]], [[Kamionka, Lubusz Voivodeship|Kamionka]], [[Kl\u0119pina]], [[Kotowice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Kotowice]], [[Krzewiny, Lubusz Voivodeship|Krzewiny]], [[Krzywa, Lubusz Voivodeship|Krzywa]], [[Krzywaniec]], [[\u0141agoda]], [[Niwiska, Lubusz Voivodeship|Niwiska]], [[Paj\u0119czno, Lubusz Voivodeship|Paj\u0119czno]], [[Pielice, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Pielice]], [[Pierzwin]], [[Podg\u00f3rzyce, Lubusz Voivodeship|Podg\u00f3rzyce]], [[Popowice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Popowice]], [[Przybymierz]], [[Skibice, Lubusz Voivodeship|Skibice]], [[Sobolice, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Sobolice]], [[Sterk\u00f3w]], [[Tur\u00f3w, Lubusz Voivodeship|Tur\u00f3w]], [[Urzuty, Lubusz Voivodeship|Urzuty]] and [[Wysoka, Zielona G\u00f3ra County|Wysoka]].\n\n==Neighbouring gminas==\nGmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski is bordered by the gminas of [[Gmina Bobrowice|Bobrowice]], [[Gmina Brze\u017anica, Lubusz Voivodeship|Brze\u017anica]], [[Gmina D\u0105bie, Lubusz Voivodeship|D\u0105bie]], [[Gmina Jasie\u0144|Jasie\u0144]], [[Gmina Ko\u017cuch\u00f3w|Ko\u017cuch\u00f3w]], [[Gmina Lubsko|Lubsko]], [[Gmina \u015awidnica, Lubusz Voivodeship|\u015awidnica]], [[Gmina \u017baga\u0144|\u017baga\u0144]], [[Gmina \u017bary|\u017bary]] and [[Gmina Zielona G\u00f3ra|Zielona G\u00f3ra]].\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Poland}}\nGmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski is [[Sister city|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Gminy partnerskie|url=https://nowogrodbobrz.pl/?page_id=1652|website=nowogrodbobrz.pl|publisher=Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski|language=pl|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n*{{flagdeco|MDA}} [[Cimi\u0219lia]], Moldova\n*{{flagdeco|GER}} [[L\u00fcbbenau]], Germany\n*{{flagdeco|NED}} [[Westerwolde (municipality)|Westerwolde]], Netherlands\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gmina Nowogr\u00f3d Bobrza\u0144ski}}\n{{Zielona G\u00f3ra County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gmina Nowogrod Bobrzanski}}\n[[Category:Gminas in Lubusz Voivodeship|Nowogrod Bobrzanski]]\n[[Category:Zielona G\u00f3ra County]]\n", "name_user": "FromCzech", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTwin towns \u2013 sister cities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gmina_Nowogr%C3%B3d_Bobrza%C5%84ski"}
{"title_page": "Barry Gardiner", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Barry Gardiner\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Barry Gardiner MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Gardiner in 2020\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start = 14 July 2016\n| term_end = 5 April 2020\n| predecessor = ''Position established''\n| successor = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n| office1 = [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 5 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = ''Position established''\n| successor1 = [[Matthew Pennycook]]\n| office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]\n| leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| successor2 = [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]] {{small|([[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]])}}\n| office3 = [[DEFRA|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Biodiversity, Landscape and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Jim Knight]]\n| successor3 = [[Jonathan Shaw (politician)|Jonathan Shaw]]\n| term_start3 = 5 May 2006\n| term_end3 = 28 June 2007\n| office4 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|for Delivery, Efficiency and Competitiveness]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor4 = ''Position established''\n| successor4 = ''Position abolished''\n| term_start4 = 10 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 5 May 2006\n| office5 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Northern Ireland Office|for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Jane Kennedy (politician)|Jane Kennedy]]\n| successor5 = [[Jeff Rooker]]\n| term_start5 = 2 April 2004\n| term_end5 = 10 May 2005\n| office6 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]]\n| term_start6 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = [[Rhodes Boyson]]\n| successor6 = \n| majority6 = 8,079 (15.6%)\n| birth_name = Barry Strachan Gardiner<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |supp= |page=11776 |date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Caroline Anne Smith\n| children = 4\n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]]<br />[[Harvard University]]<br />[[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n| website = {{url|barrygardiner.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Barry Strachan Gardiner''' (born 10 March 1957) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]].\n\nGardiner served under [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] as a junior minister in the [[Northern Ireland Office]], the [[Department for Productivity, Energy and Industry]], the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] and finally in the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\nGardiner served in [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]], [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]] and [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]] from 2016 until 2020.\n\nHe is the recipient of India's highly prestigious award [[Padma Shri]] 2020 for his work in the field of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Desk |first1=The Hindu Net |title=Full list of 2020 Padma awardees |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/full-list-of-2020-padma-awardees/article30656841.ece |work=The Hindu |date=26 January 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBarry Gardiner, the son of Olympic [[Association football|footballer]] [[John Gardiner (footballer, born 1911)|John Gardiner]],<ref name=barry>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrygardiner.com/index.php/meet-barry-gardiner|title=Barry Gardiner: Meet Barry Gardiner|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910163500/http://www.barrygardiner.com/index.php/meet-barry-gardiner|archivedate=10 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> was born in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.  His mother trained as a surgeon and was the first woman to win the gold medal for surgery at Glasgow University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrygardiner.com/about|title=About|publisher=|access-date=1 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409143943/http://www.barrygardiner.com/about/|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was educated at the [[High School of Glasgow]] (an [[Independent School]]), [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College]] and the [[University of St Andrews]] where he received an [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA]]. He then served for two years as full-time Scottish Regional Secretary of the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]]. As a young man, he planned to become an [[Episcopal priest]] and began identifying politically with [[Democratic socialism|democratic]] and [[Christian socialism]], identities he has maintained.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schofield |first1=Kevin |title=Barry Gardiner: On taking on the media, his cult status and Labour's future |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/house/87129/barry-gardiner-taking-media-his-cult-status-and-labours-future |accessdate=8 June 2019 |work=PoliticsHome |date=29 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608235102/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/house/87129/barry-gardiner-taking-media-his-cult-status-and-labours-future |archive-date=8 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Socialist labels for Barry Gardiner and Jeremy Corbyn |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-48268699/socialist-labels-for-barry-gardiner-and-jeremy-corbyn |accessdate=8 June 2019 |work=BBC News |date=14 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614021727/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-48268699/socialist-labels-for-barry-gardiner-and-jeremy-corbyn |archive-date=14 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he was awarded a [[Kennedy Memorial Trust]] scholarship to study Philosophy at [[Harvard University]]<ref name=barry /> under [[John Rawls]], returning to research at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]] for three years from 1984. He worked as a senior partner in [[shipping insurance]] and [[arbitration]] before his election to [[Palace of Westminster|parliament]].<ref name=barry />\n\nHe was elected as a councillor to [[Cambridge City Council]] in 1988 becoming the mayor of the city in 1992,<ref name=parl>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/barry-gardiner/25651 |title=Barry Gardiner: Brent North |publisher=Parliament.uk |accessdate=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826143934/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/barry-gardiner/25651 |archivedate=26 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> the youngest mayor in the city's 800-year history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Gardiner |url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Brent+North/Barry+Gardiner |accessdate=20 October 2011 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403073228/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Brent%2BNorth/Barry%2BGardiner |archivedate=3 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>  He left the council in 1994.<ref name=parl />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===In government===\nGardiner contested the [[Greater London]] constituency of [[Brent North]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], defeating the incumbent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Rhodes Boyson]] by 4,019 votes. Following his election, he moved from Cambridge to Hertfordshire. He made his [[maiden speech]] on 4 July 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=1997-06-20a.554.2|title=House of Commons debates ..Health Services (London), 20 June 1997|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125214106/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=1997-06-20a.554.2|archive-date=25 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe served on the [[Procedure Committee]], the Select Committee on Broadcasting, the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] and the Joint Committee on Consolidation of Bills.<ref name=parl />\nHe was Chair of the PLP Departmental Committee for Culture, Media and Sport and Vice-chair of the PLP Departmental Committee for the Treasury.<ref name=parl /> He was the Chairman of the Labour Friends of [[India]], and has lectured at the Academy of National Economy in [[Moscow]]. He is a former Vice-chair of [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and remains a member.\n\nHe became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Home Office]], [[Beverley Hughes]], in 2002.  In 2004 he was appointed the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]], moving to the same position at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. He moved to DEFRA at the May 2006 reshuffle and left the Government in June 2007, to once again serve as a PPS, this time to the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]].<ref name=\"twfy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/barry_gardiner/brent_north|publisher=Theyworkforyou.com|title=Barry Gardiner:Former Labour MP for Brent North|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601165335/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/barry_gardiner/brent_north|archive-date=1 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] appointed him as his special representative on forestry in July 2007.<ref name=barry /> He left this role \"by mutual consent\" on 13 September 2008 after joining other Labour MPs in declaring that an MP should stand against [[Gordon Brown]], accusing Brown of \"vacillation, loss of international credibility and timorous political manoeuvres that the public cannot understand\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2962377/Barry-Gardiner-latest-MP-to-be-sacked-for-plotting-against-Gordon-Brown.html |title=Barry Gardiner latest MP to be sacked for plotting against Gordon Brown |date=15 September 2008 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=2 May 2010 |first1=James |last1=Kirkup |first2=Andrew |last2=Porter |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124132018/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2962377/Barry-Gardiner-latest-MP-to-be-sacked-for-plotting-against-Gordon-Brown.html |archive-date=24 January 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGardiner was described in 2010 by [[Andrew Roth]] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"One of the best educated and most internationally experienced MPs\".<ref name=andy>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1868/barry-gardiner |title=Barry Gardiner: Electoral history and profile |work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100512065535/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/person/1868/barry-gardiner |archivedate=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nGardiner's expenses in 2008\u20132009 were ranked 129 out of 647 MPs whilst his 2007\u20132008 expenses were ranked 369.<ref name=twfy /> Gardiner claimed for a second home<ref name=twfy /> despite his constituency being near Westminster and his wife working for him as an Office Manager/Executive Secretary.<ref>{{cite web |author=House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/090506/p2memi02.htm |title=House of Commons - Register of Members' Interests |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822180015/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/090506/p2memi02.htm |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> New expenses rules published by the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] coming into force after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]] allow employment of one relative but replace funding for a second home with a London Allowance of \u00a33,760 for MPs with seats within 20 miles of Westminster.<ref name=BBCexp>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8587661.stm|title=MPs' expenses: Old rules v new rules |work=BBC News|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=25 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100401125805/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8587661.stm| archivedate= 1 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Those who keep their seats and already own a second home will have profits \"recouped\".<ref name=BBCexp /> The Legg Report requested that Gardiner repay \u00a3174.17 for mortgage interest overpaid in 2005\u201306 though he voluntarily repaid \u00a315,404.07 by April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|title=Review of past ACA payments|author=Sir Thomas Legg|date=2 February 2010|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100214183244/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|archive-date=14 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===In opposition===\n[[File:Barry Gardiner, 2016 Labour Party Conference 1.jpg|upright|thumb|Gardiner giving his speech at the 2016 [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party Conference]]]]\n\nGardiner nominated [[David Miliband]] in the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2010 Labour leadership election]], but did not nominate anyone in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015]] or [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016]] contests.\n\nGardiner served as [[Ed Miliband]]'s Special Envoy for Environment and Climate Change between 2011 and 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edie.net/news/6/Barry-Gardiner-appointed-shadow-minister-for-natural-environment/24912/|title=Barry Gardiner appointed shadow minister for natural environment|date=4 July 2013|website=www.edie.net|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925095144/http://www.edie.net/news/6/Barry-Gardiner-appointed-shadow-minister-for-natural-environment/24912/|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref> In June 2013, Gardiner and Conservative MP [[Tim Yeo]] jointly tabled an amendment to the [[Energy Act 2013|Energy Bill]] which proposed establishing by 2014 a [[low-carbon economy|decarbonisation]] target for the UK's electricity generating sector, to be achieved by 2030. The amendment was narrowly defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1185066/decarbonisation-amendment-defeated-commons|title=Decarbonisation amendment defeated in the Commons|date=15 June 2013|website=www.planningresource.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925115339/http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1185066/decarbonisation-amendment-defeated-commons|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nGardiner was appointed as Shadow Minister for the Natural Environment and Fisheries in July 2013. In this role, Gardiner criticised the lack of prosecutions of leading players ten months after [[David Cameron]] promised that everything possible would be done to deal with crime relating to the [[2013 meat adulteration scandal|horse meat scandal]]. \"The extraordinary thing is that because of its clout, industry has been able to commit what appears to be a criminal offence \u2013 selling the public horsemeat falsely labelled as beef \u2013 and just say they are sorry and didn't know\".<ref name=\"felicity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/22/horsemeat-scandal-guardian-investigation-public-secrecy|title=Where did the 29% horse in your Tesco burger come from?|work=The Guardian|location=London|date=22 October 2013|author=Lawrence, Felicity|accessdate=22 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022060152/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/22/horsemeat-scandal-guardian-investigation-public-secrecy|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Gardiner gave his support  to the first annual [[Hen Harrier Day]] demonstrations in [[Derbyshire]] to highlight the illegal persecution of UK [[Hen harrier|raptors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://markavery.info/2014/08/13/hen-harrier-day-thank-yous/|title=Hen Harrier Day \u2013 some 'thank you's|date=13 August 2014|website=www.markavery.info|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925112732/http://markavery.info/2014/08/13/hen-harrier-day-thank-yous/|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Gardiner admitted that the push by the previous Labour government to encourage car-buyers to opt for [[diesel engine|diesel]] vehicles in a bid to save the planet was \u201cwrong\u201d, identifying that a \u201cmassive problem for public health\u201d had been created.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/motoring-news/labours-drive-towards-diesel-cars-causing-massive-public-health-problem-admits-shadow-environment-10000843.html|title=Labour's drive towards diesel cars causing 'massive public health problem,' admits shadow Environment Minister|date=25 January 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=23 September 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925170728/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/motoring-news/labours-drive-towards-diesel-cars-causing-massive-public-health-problem-admits-shadow-environment-10000843.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|location=London}}</ref>\n\nGardiner was briefly [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]] from June to July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/146/career|title=Parliamentary career for Barry Gardiner|website=UK Parliament|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> He then became [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]] and [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/seasonal/election/general-election-2019-barry-gardiner-1-6423196|title=General Election 2019: Barry Gardiner holds on to Brent North|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|date=13 December 2019|website=Kilburn Times|access-date=20 February 2020|quote=Before the election he was shadow minister for international climate change as well as being the international trade chief before the election.}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the murder in 2018 of Saudi journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]], Gardiner said \"We must look very carefully again at the relationship we have with [[Saudi Arabia]]. What we would do certainly at the moment, and I think the government should do this, is to suspend all arms sales to the kingdom.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jamal-khashoggi-death-saudia-arabia-consulate-uk-government-arms-sales-sanctions-a8593306.html|title=Jamal Khashoggi: UK government considers 'next steps' as Saudi Arabia admits dissident journalist died in Istanbul consulate|date=20 October 2018|work=The Independent|access-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020151333/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jamal-khashoggi-death-saudia-arabia-consulate-uk-government-arms-sales-sanctions-a8593306.html|archive-date=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nGardiner endorsed [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BarryGardiner/status/1216701990786473984|title=Despite my plane back from the Climate Conference being 4 hours late \u2014 I have just managed to cast my nomination for @RLong_Bailey & @DawnButlerBrent \nI will be voting for @AngelaRayner  for Deputy but she kindly agreed I should help get our friend over the magic number of 22!pic.twitter.com/ceJkOaVzGJ|last=Gardiner|first=Barry|date=2020-01-13|website=@BarryGardiner|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Following [[Keir Starmer]]'s victory in the contest, Gardiner was stood down from the Shadow Cabinet in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/05/labour-reshuffle-begins-barry-gardiner-shadow-cabinet-12512370/|title=Labour reshuffle begins with Barry Gardiner out of shadow cabinet|date=2020-04-05|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nIn February 2017, ''[[The Times]]'' revealed that, since September 2015, Gardiner had received \u00a3182,284 in disclosed cash donations from [[Christine Lee & Co]], which acts as the chief legal adviser to the Chinese embassy. Before this, his constituency party received cash donations from Christine Lee & Co of \u00a322,500 between 2009 and 2015. The paper also revealed that part of this money was used to fund the employment of Daniel Wilkes (son of the firm's founder) in his parliamentary offices. [[Alistair Graham]], former chair of the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life]], called the situation \"bizarre\" and said \"there are clearly questions to be answered\".<ref name=\"Times-4Feb.1\">{{cite news|last1=Wright|first1=Oliver|last2=McGrath|first2=Hannah|title=China cash link to Labour MP|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/china-cash-link-to-top-labour-mp-65d3c92j8|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The Times|date=4 February 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204015029/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/china-cash-link-to-top-labour-mp-65d3c92j8|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGardiner has been a supporter of China in his shadow portfolios, in particular surrounding the development of [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]], rejecting criticism of Chinese involvement in the project despite military and intelligence figures warning ministers that such involvement posed a threat to national security. He urged [[Theresa May]] to tell China that Britain wanted strong investment in infrastructure projects and described her decision to halt the deal as \"politically stupid\" and tantamount to \"closing UK Plc down\".<ref name=\"Times-4Feb.1\" /> Gardiner later criticised May for negotiating a \"rip-off deal\" over its development.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardiner|first1=Barry|title=The Conservatives have realised too late that Hinkley Point is a rip-off|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-deal-rip-off-labour-theresa-may|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The Guardian|date=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191012/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-deal-rip-off-labour-theresa-may|archive-date=3 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Bombardier====\nIn October 2017, Gardiner became involved in the [[Boeing]] complaint to the [[US Department of Commerce]] which claimed that [[Bombardier Aerospace]] was 'dumping' aircraft in the US i.e. selling them below the cost of production, thanks to huge subsidies from Canadian governments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://leehamnews-5389.kxcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/BBD-Complaint-042717.pdf |title=Petitions For The Imposition Of Antidumping And Countervailing Duties On 100-To 150-Seat Large Civil Aircraft From Canada |date=27 April 2017 |access-date=12 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904154259/https://leehamnews-5389.kxcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/BBD-Complaint-042717.pdf |archive-date=4 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The US Department had suggested that the solution was a 300% tariff on the [[Bombardier CSeries]] being sold to [[Delta Air Lines]], which would adversely affect prospects for the sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/bombardier-s-cseries-hit-with-another-u-s-duty-1.3622391|title=Bombardier's CSeries hit with another U.S. duty|first=Ross|last=Marowits|date=6 October 2017|publisher=|access-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007222506/http://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/bombardier-s-cseries-hit-with-another-u-s-duty-1.3622391|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Bombardier is a major employer in [[Belfast]] and a punitive tariff would threaten more than 4,000 manufacturing jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/28/theresa-may-hints-at-boeing-boycott-in-bombardier-us-tariff-row|title=Theresa May hints at Boeing boycott in Bombardier US tariff row|first=Larry|last=Elliott|date=28 September 2017|newspaper=Guardian|accessdate=26 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127053008/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/28/theresa-may-hints-at-boeing-boycott-in-bombardier-us-tariff-row|archive-date=27 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn its complaint against Bombardier, Boeing had made no reference to the multibillion-dollar tax breaks it receives from [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/columnists/ct-hiltzik-boeing-washington-tax-break-20170504-story.html |title=Boeing got a record tax break from Washington state and cut jobs anyway. Now the state wants to strike back |first=Michael |last=Hiltzik |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=7 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929184036/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/columnists/ct-hiltzik-boeing-washington-tax-break-20170504-story.html |archive-date=29 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gardiner, \nas spokesman for the Labour Party, seized on this and accused Boeing of hypocrisy, insisting that all aircraft manufacturers require government subsidies; he labelled the company \"the king of corporate welfare\" and a \"subsidy junkie\", and suggested that Boeing was trying to \"crush a competitor\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/boeing-a-subsidy-junkie-u-k-s-labour-says-in-bombardier-spat |title=Boeing a 'Subsidy Junkie,' U.K.'s Labour Says in Bombardier Spat |date=11 October 2017 |first1=Alex |last1=Morales |first2=Francine |last2=Lacqua |publisher=Bloomberg Politics |accessdate=26 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217221446/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/boeing-a-subsidy-junkie-u-k-s-labour-says-in-bombardier-spat |archive-date=17 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Boeing replied that their illegal-subsidies complaint against Bombardier is about selling aircraft below the cost of production and not anti-competitive. The company said it merely wants \"fairness\" in \"following trade rules\" as Boeing already claims to be doing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/boeing-is-the-king-of-corporate-welfare-or-boeing-has-never-ever-received-subsidies-you-decide |title=Boeing is the \"king of corporate welfare\" or Boeing has never received subsidies \u2013 you decide |first=David |last=Pugliese |date=11 October 2017 |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |accessdate=26 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210023225/http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/boeing-is-the-king-of-corporate-welfare-or-boeing-has-never-ever-received-subsidies-you-decide |archive-date=10 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHis son, [[Jacob Gardiner-Smith]], is a footballer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/features/25921/jacob-gardiner-smith-is-back-from-russia-with-much-love/|title=Jacob Gardiner-Smith is back from Russia with much love|date=21 February 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019|publisher=The Non-League Football Paper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819144416/https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/features/25921/jacob-gardiner-smith-is-back-from-russia-with-much-love/|archive-date=19 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.barrygardiner.com Barry Gardiner] official site\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = barry-gardiner/146 | hansardcurr = 3379 | hansard = mr-barry-gardiner | publicwhip = Barry_Gardiner | theywork = barry_gardiner | bbc = 25651.stm}}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-1868,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Barry Gardiner MP]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100423153147/http://mpsallowances.parliament.uk/mpslordsandoffices/hocallowances/allowances-by-mp/barry-gardiner/Barry_Gardiner_0405_ACA.pdf Barry Gardiner Allowances]\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rhodes Boyson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lisa Nandy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]|years=2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]]|as=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardiner, Barry}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:British Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the High School of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury and Imperial Service College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Kennedy scholars]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Office junior ministers]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in public affairs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Barry Gardiner\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Barry Gardiner MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Gardiner in 2020\n| office = [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]\n| leader = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start = 14 July 2016\n| term_end = 5 April 2020\n| predecessor = ''Position established''\n| successor = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n| office1 = [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]]\n| leader1 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start1 = 14 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 5 April 2020\n| predecessor1 = ''Position established''\n| successor1 = [[Matthew Pennycook]]\n| office2 = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]\n| leader2 = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2 = 27 June 2016\n| term_end2 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Lisa Nandy]]\n| successor2 = [[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]] {{small|([[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]])}}\n| office3 = [[DEFRA|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Biodiversity, Landscape and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor3 = [[Jim Knight]]\n| successor3 = [[Jonathan Shaw (politician)|Jonathan Shaw]]\n| term_start3 = 5 May 2006\n| term_end3 = 28 June 2007\n| office4 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|for Delivery, Efficiency and Competitiveness]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor4 = ''Position established''\n| successor4 = ''Position abolished''\n| term_start4 = 10 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 5 May 2006\n| office5 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] [[Northern Ireland Office|for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Jane Kennedy (politician)|Jane Kennedy]]\n| successor5 = [[Jeff Rooker]]\n| term_start5 = 2 April 2004\n| term_end5 = 10 May 2005\n| office6 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]]\n| term_start6 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = [[Rhodes Boyson]]\n| successor6 = \n| majority6 = 8,079 (15.6%)\n| birth_name = Barry Strachan Gardiner<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61961 |supp= |page=11776 |date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = Caroline Anne Smith\n| children = 4\n| alma_mater = [[University of St Andrews]]<br />[[Harvard University]]<br />[[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n| website = {{url|barrygardiner.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Barry Strachan Gardiner''' (born 10 March 1957) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]].\n\nGardiner served under [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]] as a junior minister in the [[Northern Ireland Office]], the [[Department for Productivity, Energy and Industry]], the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] and finally in the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]].\n\nGardiner served in [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s [[Shadow Cabinet]] as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]], [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]] and [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]] from 2016 until 2020.\n\nHe is the recipient of India's highly prestigious award [[Padma Shri]] 2020 for his work in the field of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Desk |first1=The Hindu Net |title=Full list of 2020 Padma awardees |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/full-list-of-2020-padma-awardees/article30656841.ece |work=The Hindu |date=26 January 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBarry Gardiner, the son of Olympic [[Association football|footballer]] [[John Gardiner (footballer, born 1911)|John Gardiner]],<ref name=barry>{{cite web|url=http://www.barrygardiner.com/index.php/meet-barry-gardiner|title=Barry Gardiner: Meet Barry Gardiner|accessdate=8 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910163500/http://www.barrygardiner.com/index.php/meet-barry-gardiner|archivedate=10 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> was born in [[Glasgow]], Scotland.  His mother trained as a surgeon and was the first woman to win the gold medal for surgery at Glasgow University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.barrygardiner.com/about|title=About|publisher=|access-date=1 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190409143943/http://www.barrygardiner.com/about/|archive-date=9 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was educated at the [[High School of Glasgow]] (an [[Independent School]]), [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College]] and the [[University of St Andrews]] where he received an [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA]]. He then served for two years as full-time Scottish Regional Secretary of the [[Student Christian Movement of Great Britain|Student Christian Movement]]. As a young man, he planned to become an [[Episcopal priest]] and began identifying politically with [[Democratic socialism|democratic]] and [[Christian socialism]], identities he has maintained.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schofield |first1=Kevin |title=Barry Gardiner: On taking on the media, his cult status and Labour's future |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/house/87129/barry-gardiner-taking-media-his-cult-status-and-labours-future |accessdate=8 June 2019 |work=PoliticsHome |date=29 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608235102/https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/house/87129/barry-gardiner-taking-media-his-cult-status-and-labours-future |archive-date=8 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Socialist labels for Barry Gardiner and Jeremy Corbyn |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-48268699/socialist-labels-for-barry-gardiner-and-jeremy-corbyn |accessdate=8 June 2019 |work=BBC News |date=14 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614021727/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-48268699/socialist-labels-for-barry-gardiner-and-jeremy-corbyn |archive-date=14 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he was awarded a [[Kennedy Memorial Trust]] scholarship to study Philosophy at [[Harvard University]]<ref name=barry /> under [[John Rawls]], returning to research at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]] for three years from 1984. He worked as a senior partner in [[shipping insurance]] and [[arbitration]] before his election to [[Palace of Westminster|parliament]].<ref name=barry />\n\nHe was elected as a councillor to [[Cambridge City Council]] in 1988 becoming the mayor of the city in 1992,<ref name=parl>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/barry-gardiner/25651 |title=Barry Gardiner: Brent North |publisher=Parliament.uk |accessdate=8 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826143934/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/barry-gardiner/25651 |archivedate=26 August 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> the youngest mayor in the city's 800-year history.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Gardiner |url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Brent+North/Barry+Gardiner |accessdate=20 October 2011 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403073228/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Brent%2BNorth/Barry%2BGardiner |archivedate=3 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>  He left the council in 1994.<ref name=parl />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n===In government===\nGardiner contested the [[Greater London]] constituency of [[Brent North]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], defeating the incumbent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP [[Rhodes Boyson]] by 4,019 votes. Following his election, he moved from Cambridge to Hertfordshire. He made his [[maiden speech]] on 4 July 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=1997-06-20a.554.2|title=House of Commons debates ..Health Services (London), 20 June 1997|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125214106/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/debate/?id=1997-06-20a.554.2|archive-date=25 January 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe served on the [[Procedure Committee]], the Select Committee on Broadcasting, the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] and the Joint Committee on Consolidation of Bills.<ref name=parl />\nHe was Chair of the PLP Departmental Committee for Culture, Media and Sport and Vice-chair of the PLP Departmental Committee for the Treasury.<ref name=parl /> He was the Chairman of the Labour Friends of [[India]], and has lectured at the Academy of National Economy in [[Moscow]]. He is a former Vice-chair of [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and remains a member.\n\nHe became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Home Office]], [[Beverley Hughes]], in 2002.  In 2004 he was appointed the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]], moving to the same position at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]]. He moved to DEFRA at the May 2006 reshuffle and left the Government in June 2007, to once again serve as a PPS, this time to the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]]<ref name=\"twfy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/barry_gardiner/brent_north|publisher=Theyworkforyou.com|title=Barry Gardiner:Former Labour MP for Brent North|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601165335/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/barry_gardiner/brent_north|archive-date=1 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe new [[Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] appointed him as his special representative on forestry in July 2007.<ref name=barry /> He left this role \"by mutual consent\" on 13 September 2008 after joining other Labour MPs in declaring that an MP should stand against [[Gordon Brown]], accusing Brown of \"vacillation, loss of international credibility and timorous political manoeuvres that the public cannot understand\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2962377/Barry-Gardiner-latest-MP-to-be-sacked-for-plotting-against-Gordon-Brown.html |title=Barry Gardiner latest MP to be sacked for plotting against Gordon Brown |date=15 September 2008 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=2 May 2010 |first1=James |last1=Kirkup |first2=Andrew |last2=Porter |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124132018/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/2962377/Barry-Gardiner-latest-MP-to-be-sacked-for-plotting-against-Gordon-Brown.html |archive-date=24 January 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nGardiner was described in 2010 by [[Andrew Roth]] in ''[[The Guardian]]'' as \"One of the best educated and most internationally experienced MPs\".<ref name=andy>{{Cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/person/1868/barry-gardiner |title=Barry Gardiner: Electoral history and profile |work=The Guardian|accessdate=25 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100512065535/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/person/1868/barry-gardiner |archivedate=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nGardiner's expenses in 2008\u20132009 were ranked 129 out of 647 MPs whilst his 2007\u20132008 expenses were ranked 369.<ref name=twfy /> Gardiner claimed for a second home<ref name=twfy /> despite his constituency being near Westminster and his wife working for him as an Office Manager/Executive Secretary.<ref>{{cite web |author=House of Commons |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/090506/p2memi02.htm |title=House of Commons - Register of Members' Interests |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822180015/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmregmem/090506/p2memi02.htm |archive-date=22 August 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> New expenses rules published by the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] coming into force after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]] allow employment of one relative but replace funding for a second home with a London Allowance of \u00a33,760 for MPs with seats within 20 miles of Westminster.<ref name=BBCexp>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8587661.stm|title=MPs' expenses: Old rules v new rules |work=BBC News|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=25 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100401125805/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8587661.stm| archivedate= 1 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  Those who keep their seats and already own a second home will have profits \"recouped\".<ref name=BBCexp /> The Legg Report requested that Gardiner repay \u00a3174.17 for mortgage interest overpaid in 2005\u201306 though he voluntarily repaid \u00a315,404.07 by April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|title=Review of past ACA payments|author=Sir Thomas Legg|date=2 February 2010|accessdate=25 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100214183244/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|archive-date=14 February 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===In opposition===\n[[File:Barry Gardiner, 2016 Labour Party Conference 1.jpg|upright|thumb|Gardiner giving his speech at the 2016 [[Labour Party (UK) Conference|Labour Party Conference]]]]\n\nGardiner nominated [[David Miliband]] in the [[2010 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2010 Labour leadership election]], but did not nominate anyone in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015]] or [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016]] contests.\n\nGardiner served as [[Ed Miliband]]'s Special Envoy for Environment and Climate Change between 2011 and 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edie.net/news/6/Barry-Gardiner-appointed-shadow-minister-for-natural-environment/24912/|title=Barry Gardiner appointed shadow minister for natural environment|date=4 July 2013|website=www.edie.net|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925095144/http://www.edie.net/news/6/Barry-Gardiner-appointed-shadow-minister-for-natural-environment/24912/|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref> In June 2013, Gardiner and Conservative MP [[Tim Yeo]] jointly tabled an amendment to the [[Energy Act 2013|Energy Bill]] which proposed establishing by 2014 a [[low-carbon economy|decarbonisation]] target for the UK's electricity generating sector, to be achieved by 2030. The amendment was narrowly defeated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1185066/decarbonisation-amendment-defeated-commons|title=Decarbonisation amendment defeated in the Commons|date=15 June 2013|website=www.planningresource.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925115339/http://www.planningresource.co.uk/article/1185066/decarbonisation-amendment-defeated-commons|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nGardiner was appointed as Shadow Minister for the Natural Environment and Fisheries in July 2013. In this role, Gardiner criticised the lack of prosecutions of leading players ten months after [[David Cameron]] promised that everything possible would be done to deal with crime relating to the [[2013 meat adulteration scandal|horse meat scandal]]. \"The extraordinary thing is that because of its clout, industry has been able to commit what appears to be a criminal offence \u2013 selling the public horsemeat falsely labelled as beef \u2013 and just say they are sorry and didn't know\".<ref name=\"felicity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/22/horsemeat-scandal-guardian-investigation-public-secrecy|title=Where did the 29% horse in your Tesco burger come from?|work=The Guardian|location=London|date=22 October 2013|author=Lawrence, Felicity|accessdate=22 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022060152/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/22/horsemeat-scandal-guardian-investigation-public-secrecy|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Gardiner gave his support  to the first annual [[Hen Harrier Day]] demonstrations in [[Derbyshire]] to highlight the illegal persecution of UK [[Hen harrier|raptors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://markavery.info/2014/08/13/hen-harrier-day-thank-yous/|title=Hen Harrier Day \u2013 some 'thank you's|date=13 August 2014|website=www.markavery.info|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925112732/http://markavery.info/2014/08/13/hen-harrier-day-thank-yous/|archive-date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Gardiner admitted that the push by the previous Labour government to encourage car-buyers to opt for [[diesel engine|diesel]] vehicles in a bid to save the planet was \u201cwrong\u201d, identifying that a \u201cmassive problem for public health\u201d had been created.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/motoring-news/labours-drive-towards-diesel-cars-causing-massive-public-health-problem-admits-shadow-environment-10000843.html|title=Labour's drive towards diesel cars causing 'massive public health problem,' admits shadow Environment Minister|date=25 January 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=23 September 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925170728/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/motoring/motoring-news/labours-drive-towards-diesel-cars-causing-massive-public-health-problem-admits-shadow-environment-10000843.html|archive-date=25 September 2015|location=London}}</ref>\n\nGardiner was briefly [[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]] from June to July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/146/career|title=Parliamentary career for Barry Gardiner|website=UK Parliament|access-date=20 February 2020}}</ref> He then became [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]] and [[Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Shadow Minister for International Climate Change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kilburntimes.co.uk/seasonal/election/general-election-2019-barry-gardiner-1-6423196|title=General Election 2019: Barry Gardiner holds on to Brent North|last=Raffray|first=Nathalie|date=13 December 2019|website=Kilburn Times|access-date=20 February 2020|quote=Before the election he was shadow minister for international climate change as well as being the international trade chief before the election.}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the murder in 2018 of Saudi journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]], Gardiner said \"We must look very carefully again at the relationship we have with [[Saudi Arabia]]. What we would do certainly at the moment, and I think the government should do this, is to suspend all arms sales to the kingdom.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jamal-khashoggi-death-saudia-arabia-consulate-uk-government-arms-sales-sanctions-a8593306.html|title=Jamal Khashoggi: UK government considers 'next steps' as Saudi Arabia admits dissident journalist died in Istanbul consulate|date=20 October 2018|work=The Independent|access-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020151333/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jamal-khashoggi-death-saudia-arabia-consulate-uk-government-arms-sales-sanctions-a8593306.html|archive-date=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nGardiner endorsed [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BarryGardiner/status/1216701990786473984|title=Despite my plane back from the Climate Conference being 4 hours late \u2014 I have just managed to cast my nomination for @RLong_Bailey & @DawnButlerBrent \nI will be voting for @AngelaRayner  for Deputy but she kindly agreed I should help get our friend over the magic number of 22!pic.twitter.com/ceJkOaVzGJ|last=Gardiner|first=Barry|date=2020-01-13|website=@BarryGardiner|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Following [[Keir Starmer]]'s victory in the contest, Gardiner was stood down from the Shadow Cabinet in April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/05/labour-reshuffle-begins-barry-gardiner-shadow-cabinet-12512370/|title=Labour reshuffle begins with Barry Gardiner out of shadow cabinet|date=2020-04-05|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nIn February 2017, ''[[The Times]]'' revealed that, since September 2015, Gardiner had received \u00a3182,284 in disclosed cash donations from [[Christine Lee & Co]], which acts as the chief legal adviser to the Chinese embassy. Before this, his constituency party received cash donations from Christine Lee & Co of \u00a322,500 between 2009 and 2015. The paper also revealed that part of this money was used to fund the employment of Daniel Wilkes (son of the firm's founder) in his parliamentary offices. [[Alistair Graham]], former chair of the [[Committee on Standards in Public Life]], called the situation \"bizarre\" and said \"there are clearly questions to be answered\".<ref name=\"Times-4Feb.1\">{{cite news|last1=Wright|first1=Oliver|last2=McGrath|first2=Hannah|title=China cash link to Labour MP|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/china-cash-link-to-top-labour-mp-65d3c92j8|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The Times|date=4 February 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204015029/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/china-cash-link-to-top-labour-mp-65d3c92j8|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGardiner has been a supporter of China in his shadow portfolios, in particular surrounding the development of [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]], rejecting criticism of Chinese involvement in the project despite military and intelligence figures warning ministers that such involvement posed a threat to national security. He urged [[Theresa May]] to tell China that Britain wanted strong investment in infrastructure projects and described her decision to halt the deal as \"politically stupid\" and tantamount to \"closing UK Plc down\".<ref name=\"Times-4Feb.1\" /> Gardiner later criticised May for negotiating a \"rip-off deal\" over its development.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardiner|first1=Barry|title=The Conservatives have realised too late that Hinkley Point is a rip-off|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-deal-rip-off-labour-theresa-may|accessdate=4 February 2017|work=The Guardian|date=29 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203191012/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-deal-rip-off-labour-theresa-may|archive-date=3 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Bombardier====\nIn October 2017, Gardiner became involved in the [[Boeing]] complaint to the [[US Department of Commerce]] which claimed that [[Bombardier Aerospace]] was 'dumping' aircraft in the US i.e. selling them below the cost of production, thanks to huge subsidies from Canadian governments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://leehamnews-5389.kxcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/BBD-Complaint-042717.pdf |title=Petitions For The Imposition Of Antidumping And Countervailing Duties On 100-To 150-Seat Large Civil Aircraft From Canada |date=27 April 2017 |access-date=12 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904154259/https://leehamnews-5389.kxcdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/BBD-Complaint-042717.pdf |archive-date=4 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The US Department had suggested that the solution was a 300% tariff on the [[Bombardier CSeries]] being sold to [[Delta Air Lines]], which would adversely affect prospects for the sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/bombardier-s-cseries-hit-with-another-u-s-duty-1.3622391|title=Bombardier's CSeries hit with another U.S. duty|first=Ross|last=Marowits|date=6 October 2017|publisher=|access-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007222506/http://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/business/bombardier-s-cseries-hit-with-another-u-s-duty-1.3622391|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Bombardier is a major employer in [[Belfast]] and a punitive tariff would threaten more than 4,000 manufacturing jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/28/theresa-may-hints-at-boeing-boycott-in-bombardier-us-tariff-row|title=Theresa May hints at Boeing boycott in Bombardier US tariff row|first=Larry|last=Elliott|date=28 September 2017|newspaper=Guardian|accessdate=26 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127053008/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/sep/28/theresa-may-hints-at-boeing-boycott-in-bombardier-us-tariff-row|archive-date=27 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn its complaint against Bombardier, Boeing had made no reference to the multibillion-dollar tax breaks it receives from [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/columnists/ct-hiltzik-boeing-washington-tax-break-20170504-story.html |title=Boeing got a record tax break from Washington state and cut jobs anyway. Now the state wants to strike back |first=Michael |last=Hiltzik |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=7 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929184036/http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/columnists/ct-hiltzik-boeing-washington-tax-break-20170504-story.html |archive-date=29 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gardiner, \nas spokesman for the Labour Party, seized on this and accused Boeing of hypocrisy, insisting that all aircraft manufacturers require government subsidies; he labelled the company \"the king of corporate welfare\" and a \"subsidy junkie\", and suggested that Boeing was trying to \"crush a competitor\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/boeing-a-subsidy-junkie-u-k-s-labour-says-in-bombardier-spat |title=Boeing a 'Subsidy Junkie,' U.K.'s Labour Says in Bombardier Spat |date=11 October 2017 |first1=Alex |last1=Morales |first2=Francine |last2=Lacqua |publisher=Bloomberg Politics |accessdate=26 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180217221446/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/boeing-a-subsidy-junkie-u-k-s-labour-says-in-bombardier-spat |archive-date=17 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Boeing replied that their illegal-subsidies complaint against Bombardier is about selling aircraft below the cost of production and not anti-competitive. The company said it merely wants \"fairness\" in \"following trade rules\" as Boeing already claims to be doing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/boeing-is-the-king-of-corporate-welfare-or-boeing-has-never-ever-received-subsidies-you-decide |title=Boeing is the \"king of corporate welfare\" or Boeing has never received subsidies \u2013 you decide |first=David |last=Pugliese |date=11 October 2017 |newspaper=Ottawa Citizen |accessdate=26 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210023225/http://ottawacitizen.com/news/national/defence-watch/boeing-is-the-king-of-corporate-welfare-or-boeing-has-never-ever-received-subsidies-you-decide |archive-date=10 February 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHis son, [[Jacob Gardiner-Smith]], is a footballer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/features/25921/jacob-gardiner-smith-is-back-from-russia-with-much-love/|title=Jacob Gardiner-Smith is back from Russia with much love|date=21 February 2019|accessdate=19 August 2019|publisher=The Non-League Football Paper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819144416/https://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/features/25921/jacob-gardiner-smith-is-back-from-russia-with-much-love/|archive-date=19 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.barrygardiner.com Barry Gardiner] official site\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = barry-gardiner/146 | hansardcurr = 3379 | hansard = mr-barry-gardiner | publicwhip = Barry_Gardiner | theywork = barry_gardiner | bbc = 25651.stm}}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-1868,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Barry Gardiner MP]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100423153147/http://mpsallowances.parliament.uk/mpslordsandoffices/hocallowances/allowances-by-mp/barry-gardiner/Barry_Gardiner_0405_ACA.pdf Barry Gardiner Allowances]\n*{{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rhodes Boyson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lisa Nandy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]]|years=2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Clive Lewis (politician)|Clive Lewis]]|as=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for International Trade]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gardiner, Barry}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:British Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at the High School of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury and Imperial Service College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Kennedy scholars]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Cambridgeshire]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Office junior ministers]]\n[[Category:Politics of the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in public affairs]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn government", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Gardiner"}
{"title_page": "Creation Evidence Museum", "text_new": "{{coord|32.23028|-97.80533|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=title}}\n[[Image:Creation Evidence Museum Original.jpg|right|thumb|Temporary museum building]]\n[[Image:Creation Evidence Museum.jpg|right|thumb|New museum building]]\n[[Image:Hyperbaric Biosphere.jpg|right|thumb|The first hyperbaric biosphere]]\nThe '''Creation Evidence Museum of Texas''', originally '''Creation Evidences Museum''',<ref name=\"Observer\">[http://www.dallasobserver.com/1996-12-12/news/footprints-of-fantasy/ \"Footprints of Fantasy\"], by Kaylois Henry, ''[[Dallas Observer]]'', December 12, 1996. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> is a [[creationist museum]] in [[Glen Rose, Texas|Glen Rose]] in [[Somervell County, Texas|Somervell County]] in central [[Texas]], [[United States|USA]]. Founded in 1984 by [[Carl Baugh]] for the purpose of researching and displaying exhibits that support [[creationism]], it portrays the Earth as six thousand years old and humans coexisting with [[dinosaurs]],<ref name=\"Chronicle\"/> [[Level of support for evolution#Scientific support|disputing]] that the [[Age of the Earth|Earth]] is approximately 4.5 billion years old and dinosaurs [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|became extinct]] 65.5 million years before [[human evolution|human beings arose]].<ref name=nihrecord>[http://nihrecord.od.nih.gov/newsletters/2006/07_28_2006/story03.htm ''Finding the Evolution in Medicine''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122022815/http://nihrecord.od.nih.gov/newsletters/2006/07_28_2006/story03.htm |date=2008-11-22 }}, Cynthia Delgado, [[National Institutes of Health|NIH]] Record, July 28, 2006.</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek_1987_Martz_McDaniel\">Larry Martz & Ann McDaniel, ''[[Newsweek]]'' CIX(26): 23-24, June 29, 1987, ISSN 0028-9604</ref><ref name=iapstatement>{{cite web |url=http://www.interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/6/150/Evolution%20statement.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060705140010/http://www.interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/6/150/Evolution%20statement.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-07-05 |title=IAP STATEMENT ON THE TEACHING OF EVOLUTION |access-date=2007-10-02 |format=PDF |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History and projects==\nThe Creation Evidence Museum was founded by Carl Baugh, a [[Young Earth creationism|young Earth creationist]], after he came to Glen Rose in 1982 to research claims of [[fossilized]] human footprints alongside [[dinosaur]] footprints in the [[limestone]] banks of the [[Paluxy River]], near [[Dinosaur Valley State Park]]. He claims to have excavated 475 dinosaur footprints and 86 human footprints,<ref name=\"Roadside America\">[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/8196 \"Creation Evidence Museum, Glen Rose, Texas\"], [[Roadside America]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> which form the basis of the Creation Evidence Museum as well as other exhibits.<ref name=\"Chronicle\">[http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid%3A283058 \"Creationism Alive and Kicking in Glen Rose\"], by Greg Beets, August 5, 2005, ''[[Austin Chronicle]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Democrat\"/>  Baugh remains the director and main speaker for CEM.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/credentials.html | title=Some Questionable Creationist Credentials | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|date= May 31, 2002 | first=Brett | last=Vickers | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe Creation Evidence Museum sponsors continuing [[paleontological]] and [[archaeological]] excavations among other research projects, including a hunt for living [[pterodactyls]] in [[Papua New Guinea]],<ref name=\"Observer\"/><ref name=\"LATimes\">[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/27/local/me-dinosaurs27 \"Adam, Eve and T. Rex\"], by Ashley Powers, August 27, 2005, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved August 14, 2008.</ref> and expeditions to [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Cleburne Times Review\">[http://www.cleburnetimesreview.com/archivesearch/local_story_036154557.html \"Bronstein, head of Israeli Department of Antiquities, lectures in Glen Rose\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130119084132/http://www.cleburnetimesreview.com/archivesearch/local_story_036154557.html |date=2013-01-19 }}, John Watson, ''[[Cleburne Times-Review]]'', February 05, 2006.</ref> Materials from the museum have been recommended by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]],<ref name=\"Time\">[http://www.time.com//time/printout/0,8816,1601845,00.html \"The Case for Teaching The Bible\"], by David Van Biema, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, March 22, 2007.</ref> but the NCBCPS curriculum has been deemed \"unfit for use in public school classrooms.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Amanda Colleen|date=Winter 2007|title=Losing My Religion: The Controversy over Bible Classes in Public Schools|url=http://www.bibleliteracy.org/site/News/bibl_newsBaylorLawReview071010.htm|url-status=dead|journal=Baylor Law Review|volume=59|pages=193\u2013240|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820115248/http://www.bibleliteracy.org/site/News/bibl_newsBaylorLawReview071010.htm|archive-date=August 20, 2008|via=}}</ref>\n\nOne of the museum's projects is a \"[[hyperbaric chamber|hyperbaric]] [[biosphere]]\", a chamber which the museum hopes will reproduce the atmospheric conditions that these creationists postulate for Earth before the [[Flood myth|Great Flood]], and enable them to grow dinosaurs. Baugh says that these conditions made creatures [[Maximum life span|live longer]], and get [[Square-cube law#Biometrics|larger]], smarter and nicer.<ref name=\"Roadside America\"/> He claims that tests under these conditions have tripled the lifespan of fruit-flies, and detoxified copperhead snakes. A much larger version is under construction in the new building.<ref name=\"Chronicle\"/>\n== Exhibits ==\nAll of the creationist exhibits have been strongly criticized as incorrectly identified dinosaur prints, other fossils, or outright forgeries.<ref name=\"AIC\"/><ref name=\"Kuban\"/><ref name=\"Armstrong\">[http://www.asa3.org/ASA/PSCF/1989/PSCF3-89Armstrong.html \"Seeking Ancient Paths\"], John R. Armstrong, PSCF 41 (March 1989): 33&ndash;35, [[American Scientific Affiliation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"Hastings\">[http://www.asa3.org/ASA/PSCF/1988/PSCF9-88Hastings.html \"The Rise and Fall of the Paluxy Mantracks\"], by Ronnie J. Hastings, PSCF 40 (September 1988): 144&ndash;154. [[American Scientific Affiliation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> The second floor balcony of the museum features prominently a {{convert|12|ft|m}} high statue of [[Dallas Cowboys]] football coach [[Tom Landry]].<ref name=\"ncse back to Glen Rose\">{{Cite web  | last = Moore | first = Randy | title = Going Back to Glen Rose | url = http://ncse.com/rncse/29/6/going-back-to-glen-rose | publisher = Reports of the [[National Center for Science Education]] | year = 2009 | accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nDisplays in the Creation Evidence Museum include:\n* The \"London Artifact\", also known as the \"[[London Hammer]]\", an [[out-of-place artifact]] found in 1934 in [[London, Texas]]. This is a hammer \"of recent American historical style\" (18th or 19th century) found in a [[limestone]] concretion that has been claimed to be [[Ordovician|Ordovician period]] or [[Cretaceous]] rock.<ref name=\"NCSE-Hammer\">{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/cej/5/1/if-i-had-hammer | title=If I Had a Hammer | publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] |date= Winter 1985|issue=Issue 15 (Volume 5, Number 1) | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> It was examined by scientists who concluded that the stone has not necessarily been part of the surrounding rock formation but can have formed around the hammer relatively recently: \"The stone is real, and it looks impressive to someone unfamiliar with geological processes... Minerals in solution can harden around an intrusive object dropped in a crack or simply left on the ground if the source rock (in this case, reportedly Ordovician) is chemically soluble.\"<ref name=\"Hammer-London\">{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/hammer.htm | title=The London Hammer: An Alleged Out-of-Place Artifact  | publisher=The Paluxy Dinosaur/\"Man Track\" Controversy |date=14 July 2006 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> \n* The \"Burdick Track\", a human footprint in Cretaceous rock. Glen J. Kuban and geologist Gregg Wilkerson described anatomical errors in the \"footprint\", and remains of algae which indicate that it was [[stone carving|carve]]d into the bottom of a limestone slab, similar to other tracks that were carved in the [[Dinosaur Valley State Park]] area.<ref name=\"Sum Paluxy\">{{Cite web | first=Glen | last=Kuban  | title = Summary of Paluxy \"Man Track\" claims | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/paluxy/mantrack.html | publisher = [[TalkOrigins Archive]] | date =  1992\u20132010| accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/wilker6.htm | title=The \"Burdick Print\"  | publisher=The Paluxy Dinosaur/\"Man Track\" Controversy |year= 2008  | first=Glen | last=Kuban | accessdate = 2008-08-19}}</ref>\n* The \"Fossilized Human Finger\", a finger where tissues appear to have been [[Fossilized#Replacement and recrystallization|replaced]] by Cretaceous stone. The stone was not found in situ and according to Mark Isaak \"looks remarkably similar in size and shape to the cylindrical sandstone infillings of Ophiomoipha or Thalassmoides shrimp burrows commonly found in Cretaceous rocks. Although its general shape is fingerlike, it has none of the fine structure one would expect from a finger.\"<ref name=\"Isaak\">{{cite book|last1=Isaak|first1=Mark|title=The Counter-creationism Handbook|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520249264|page=112|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dGFJXLEWogEC&pg=PA112&dq=%22Fossilized+Human+Finger%22,&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYp-bs1r3MAhXLpx4KHRxOA-8Q6AEIITAB#v=onepage&q=%22Fossilized%20Human%20Finger%22%2C&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* The \"[[Meister Print]]\", two [[trilobites]] in [[slate]] that appear to be crushed in a [[sandal]] print. The print is \"questionable on several accounts\" such as the shallowness of the print, [[spall]] patterns, striding sequence, and similarities to the [[Wheeler formation]].<ref>Conrad, Ernest C. 1981. \"Tripping Over a Trilobite,\" ''Creation/Evolution'' Issue VI, pp. 30-33. [http://ncse.com/cej/2/4/tripping-over-trilobite-study-meister-tracks]</ref><ref>Stokes, William Lee. 1986. \"Alleged Human Footprint from the Middle Cambrian Strata, Millard County, Utah.\" ''Journal of Geologic Education'' Vol. 34, pp. 187-90.</ref><ref>Strahler, Arthur N. 1987. ''Science and Earth History'' Buffalo, New York: Prometheus Books. pp. 459-461. {{ISBN|1-57392-717-1}}</ref> \"In short, the trilobites in the specimen are real enough, but the 'print' itself appears to be due solely to inorganic, geologic phenomena,\" according to Kuban.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/paluxy/meister.html | title=The \"Meister Print\"  | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|year= 1998 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref>\n* The \"Hand Print in Stone\", allegedly a hand print in Cretaceous rock.<ref name=\"CEM Displays\">[http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9&Itemid=11 \"Creation Evidence Museum Online &mdash; Museum Displays\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813085507/http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9&Itemid=11 |date=2008-08-13 }}, official site. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> Baugh has provided no evidence it was [[in situ]] in any Cretaceous bed, nor allowed experts to inspect it.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/hand.htm | title=Alleged Human Hand Print in Cretaceous Rock | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|year= 2006 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref> Creationists have been critical of it too.<ref name=\"AIC\">[http://www.answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm \"Creation Science Rebuttals &mdash; Creation Evidence Museum Lacks Evidence!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905065319/http://answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm |date=2008-09-05 }}, by Greg Neyman, [[Answers in Creation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref>\n* The \"Alvis Delk Cretaceous Footprint\", allegedly a human footprint partially overlapped by an [[Acrocanthosaurus]] dinosaur footprint, found when a slab supposedly taken from Glen Rose was later cleaned up.<ref name=\"Democrat\">[http://www.weatherforddemocrat.com/archivesearch/local_story_210103057.html \"Rock solid proof?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20090417052416/http://www.weatherforddemocrat.com/archivesearch/local_story_210103057.html |date=2009-04-17 }}, by David May, ''[[Weatherford Democrat]]'', July 28, 2008. Also printed as [http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/homepage/local_story_210093256.html \"Rock-solid proof?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://swap.stanford.edu/20100417032541/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/homepage/local_story_210093256.html |date=2010-04-17 }}, in ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]'', July 28, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"CEM Delk\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080603055755/http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=24 \"Creation Evidence Museum Online &ndash; Alvis Delk Cretaceous Footprint\"], official site. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"MWI Aug 11 2008\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080928220610/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_224120721.html \"One step at a time\"], by David May, August 11, 2008, ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]''. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"MWI Aug 12 2008\">[http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_225091209.html \"Rock's finders discovering celebrity not always pleasant\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20100111120546/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_225091209.html |date=2010-01-11 }}, by David May, August 12, 2008, ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]''. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> The footprint is presented as representing ''Homo bauanthropus'', a species name coined by Baugh but not recognised by anyone else.<ref name=\"ncse back to Glen Rose\" /> Biologist [[PZ Myers]] described it as a blatant fake. The \"human print has toes like tubes and a weirdly dug-in big toe\", while \"the dino print is even worse \u2014 it\u2019s basically a three-pronged flat plate\" with no resemblance to a real dinosaur footprint.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2008/07/28/transparent-fakery/ | title=Transparent fakery | publisher=[[Pharyngula (blog)]] |date=July 28, 2008 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> Kuban described anatomical problems in detail. He notes that the slab was not documented in situ, and there are significant issues with [[CT scan]]s claimed to authenticate the slab. Other creationists have not supported the claims, and one of those originally promoting the slab has removed the information from his website.<ref name=\"Sum Paluxy\"/><ref>{{Cite web  | last = Kuban | first = Glen J. | title = The Delk Print | url = http://paleo.cc/paluxy/delk.htm | publisher =  | date =  | accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1982&ndash;1984, several scientists, including J.R. Cole, L.R. Godfrey, R.J. Hastings, and [[Steven Schafersman]], examined Baugh's purported \"mantracks\" as well as others provided by creationists in Glen Rose. In the course of the examination \"Baugh contradicted his own earlier reports of the locations of key discoveries\" and many of the supposed prints \"lacked characteristics of human footprints.\" After a three-year investigation of the tracks and Baugh's specimens, the scientists concluded there was no evidence for any of Baugh's claims or any \"dinosaur-man tracks\".<ref name=\"NCSE-Examine\">{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/cej/5/1/introduction | title=Creation/Evolution | publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] |date=Winter 1985|issue=Issue 15 (Volume 5, Number 1) | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism from creationists ==\nYoung Earth creationist organizations such as [[Answers in Genesis]] and [[Creation Ministries International]] have criticized Baugh's claims saying he \"muddied the water for many Christians ... People are being misled.\"<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Don Batten, of [[Creation Ministries International]] wrote: \"Some Christians will try to use Baugh's 'evidences' in witnessing and get 'shot down' by someone who is scientifically literate. The ones witnessed to will thereafter be wary of all creation evidences and even more inclined to dismiss Christians as [[wiktionary:nutcase#English|nut cases]] not worth listening to.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/whatbau.htm  | title=What About Carl Baugh?| publisher=[[Creation Ministries International]] |year= 1998 | first= | last=  | accessdate =2007-05-17}}</ref> Answers in Genesis lists the \"Paluxy tracks\" as arguments \"we think creationists should NOT use\" [emphasis in original].<ref name=\"AIGCriticism\">{{cite news | url=http://creation.com/arguments-we-think-creationists-should-not-use | title=Arguments we think creationists should NOT use | publisher=[[Answers In Genesis]] |year= 2008 | first= | last=  | accessdate =2007-05-17}}</ref> The old Earth creationist organization [[Answers In Creation]] also reviewed Baugh's museum and concluded \"the main artifacts they claim show a young earth reveal that they are deceptions, and in many cases, not even clever ones.\"<ref name=\"AICReview\">{{cite news | url=http://www.answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm | title=Review of Carl Baugh's Museum | publisher=[[Answers In Creation]] | year=2008 | first= | last= | accessdate=2007-05-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905065319/http://answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm | archive-date=2008-09-05 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe \"Burdick track\" and \"fossilized finger\" were featured on the controversial [[NBC]] program ''[[The Mysterious Origins of Man]]'', aired in 1996 and hosted by [[Charlton Heston]].<ref name=\"Kuban\">[http://paleo.cc/paluxy/nbc.htm \"A Review of NBC's 'The Mysterious Origins of Man'\"], 1996, Glen J. Kuban. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> Creationist [[Ken Ham]] criticized the production in the February 1996 [[Answers in Genesis]] newsletter in a review titled \"Hollywood's 'Moses' Undermines [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]].\"<ref name=\"SkepticalOrigins\"/> Ham attacked Baugh's claims, saying, \"According to leading creationist researchers, this evidence is open to much debate and needs much more intensive research. One wonders how much of the information in the program can really be trusted!\"<ref name=\"SkepticalOrigins\">{{cite news|url=http://www.csicop.org/sb/9603/origins.html |title=NBC's Origins Show |publisher=[[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] |date=March 1996 |first=Dave |last=Thomas |access-date=2007-02-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203134301/http://www.csicop.org/sb/9603/origins.html |archive-date=2007-02-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Creation Evidence Museum}}\n*[[Creation Museum]], museum in Northern [[Kentucky]]\n*[[Kent Hovind#Dinosaur Adventure Land|Dinosaur Adventure Land]], bankrupt theme park in Pensacola, Florida by Kent Hovind\n*[[Dinosaur Valley State Park#Controversy|Glen Rose dinosaur-human hoax]]\n*[[List of museums in North Texas]]\n*[[List of museums in Texas]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.creationevidence.org/ Creation Evidence Museum Online] &mdash; official site.\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Museums in Somervell County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Creationist museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Religious museums in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|32.23028|-97.80533|type:landmark_region:US-TX|display=title}}\n[[Image:Creation Evidence Museum Original.jpg|right|thumb|Temporary museum building]]\n[[Image:Creation Evidence Museum.jpg|right|thumb|New museum building]]\n[[Image:Hyperbaric Biosphere.jpg|right|thumb|The first hyperbaric biosphere]]\nThe '''Creation Evidence Museum of Texas''', originally '''Creation Evidences Museum''',<ref name=\"Observer\">[http://www.dallasobserver.com/1996-12-12/news/footprints-of-fantasy/ \"Footprints of Fantasy\"], by Kaylois Henry, ''[[Dallas Observer]]'', December 12, 1996. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> is a [[creationist museum]] in [[Glen Rose, Texas|Glen Rose]] in [[Somervell County, Texas|Somervell County]] in central [[Texas]], [[United States|USA]]. Founded in 1984 by [[Carl Baugh]] for the purpose of researching and displaying exhibits that support [[creationism]], it portrays the Earth as six thousand years old and humans coexisting with [[dinosaurs]],<ref name=\"Chronicle\"/> [[Level of support for evolution#Scientific support|disputing]] that the [[Age of the Earth|Earth]] is approximately 4.5 billion years old and dinosaurs [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|became extinct]] 65.5 million years before [[human evolution|human beings arose]].<ref name=nihrecord>[http://nihrecord.od.nih.gov/newsletters/2006/07_28_2006/story03.htm ''Finding the Evolution in Medicine''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122022815/http://nihrecord.od.nih.gov/newsletters/2006/07_28_2006/story03.htm |date=2008-11-22 }}, Cynthia Delgado, [[National Institutes of Health|NIH]] Record, July 28, 2006.</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek_1987_Martz_McDaniel\">Larry Martz & Ann McDaniel, ''[[Newsweek]]'' CIX(26): 23-24, June 29, 1987, ISSN 0028-9604</ref><ref name=iapstatement>{{cite web |url=http://www.interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/6/150/Evolution%20statement.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060705140010/http://www.interacademies.net/Object.File/Master/6/150/Evolution%20statement.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-07-05 |title=IAP STATEMENT ON THE TEACHING OF EVOLUTION |access-date=2007-10-02 |format=PDF |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History and projects==\nThe Creation Evidence Museum was founded by Carl Baugh, a [[Young Earth creationism|young Earth creationist]], after he came to Glen Rose in 1982 to research claims of [[fossilized]] human footprints alongside [[dinosaur]] footprints in the [[limestone]] banks of the [[Paluxy River]], near [[Dinosaur Valley State Park]]. He claims to have excavated 475 dinosaur footprints and 86 human footprints,<ref name=\"Roadside America\">[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/8196 \"Creation Evidence Museum, Glen Rose, Texas\"], [[Roadside America]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> which form the basis of the Creation Evidence Museum as well as other exhibits.<ref name=\"Chronicle\">[http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid%3A283058 \"Creationism Alive and Kicking in Glen Rose\"], by Greg Beets, August 5, 2005, ''[[Austin Chronicle]]''.</ref><ref name=\"Democrat\"/>  Baugh, who does not have an [[accredited]] degree, remains the director and main speaker for CEM.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/credentials.html | title=Some Questionable Creationist Credentials | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|date= May 31, 2002 | first=Brett | last=Vickers | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 Baugh and Creation Evidence Museum were featured on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' where Baugh likened human history to ''[[The Flintstones]]'' and the show poked fun at his claims about the  hyperbaric biosphere, pterodactyl expeditions, and dinosaurs.<ref name=\"DailyShow\">{{cite news | url=http://www.thedailyshow.com/video/index.jhtml?videoId=105921&title=Tyrannosaurus-Redux | title=Tyrannosaurus Redux | publisher=[[The Daily Show]] |date=November 14, 2001 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe Creation Evidence Museum sponsors continuing [[paleontological]] and [[archaeological]] excavations among other research projects, including a hunt for living [[pterodactyls]] in [[Papua New Guinea]],<ref name=\"Observer\"/><ref name=\"LATimes\">[http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/27/local/me-dinosaurs27 \"Adam, Eve and T. Rex\"], by Ashley Powers, August 27, 2005, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved August 14, 2008.</ref> and expeditions to [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Cleburne Times Review\">[http://www.cleburnetimesreview.com/archivesearch/local_story_036154557.html \"Bronstein, head of Israeli Department of Antiquities, lectures in Glen Rose\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130119084132/http://www.cleburnetimesreview.com/archivesearch/local_story_036154557.html |date=2013-01-19 }}, John Watson, ''[[Cleburne Times-Review]]'', February 05, 2006.</ref> Materials from the museum have been recommended by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]],<ref name=\"Time\">[http://www.time.com//time/printout/0,8816,1601845,00.html \"The Case for Teaching The Bible\"], by David Van Biema, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine, March 22, 2007.</ref> but the NCBCPS curriculum has been deemed \"unfit for use in public school classrooms.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Amanda Colleen|date=Winter 2007|title=Losing My Religion: The Controversy over Bible Classes in Public Schools|url=http://www.bibleliteracy.org/site/News/bibl_newsBaylorLawReview071010.htm|url-status=dead|journal=Baylor Law Review|volume=59|pages=193\u2013240|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820115248/http://www.bibleliteracy.org/site/News/bibl_newsBaylorLawReview071010.htm|archive-date=August 20, 2008|via=}}</ref>\n\nOne of the museum's projects is a \"[[hyperbaric chamber|hyperbaric]] [[biosphere]]\", a chamber which the museum hopes will reproduce the atmospheric conditions that these creationists postulate for Earth before the [[Flood myth|Great Flood]], and enable them to grow dinosaurs. Baugh says that these conditions made creatures [[Maximum life span|live longer]], and get [[Square-cube law#Biometrics|larger]], smarter and nicer.<ref name=\"Roadside America\"/> He claims that tests under these conditions have tripled the lifespan of fruit-flies, and detoxified copperhead snakes. A much larger version is under construction in the new building.<ref name=\"Chronicle\"/>\n\nIn 2008, a descendant of a family that provided many original Paluxy River dinosaur tracks in the 1930s claimed that her grandfather had faked many of them, including the [[Alvis Delk Cretaceous Footprint]].<ref name=\"tracks\">{{cite news | title=Human footprints beside dinosaur tracks? Let's talk| publisher=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |date=August 10, 2008 | first=Bud | last=Kennedy |page = B02}}</ref> Zana Douglas, the granddaughter of George Adams, explained that during the 1930s depression her grandfather and other residents of Glen Rose made money by making [[moonshine]] and selling \"dinosaur fossils\".<ref name=\"tracks\"/> The faux fossils brought $15 to $30 and when the supply ran low, they \"just carved more, some with human footprints thrown in.\"<ref name=\"tracks\"/>\n\n== Exhibits ==\nAll of the creationist exhibits have been strongly criticized as incorrectly identified dinosaur prints, other fossils, or outright forgeries.<ref name=\"AIC\"/><ref name=\"Kuban\"/><ref name=\"Armstrong\">[http://www.asa3.org/ASA/PSCF/1989/PSCF3-89Armstrong.html \"Seeking Ancient Paths\"], John R. Armstrong, PSCF 41 (March 1989): 33&ndash;35, [[American Scientific Affiliation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"Hastings\">[http://www.asa3.org/ASA/PSCF/1988/PSCF9-88Hastings.html \"The Rise and Fall of the Paluxy Mantracks\"], by Ronnie J. Hastings, PSCF 40 (September 1988): 144&ndash;154. [[American Scientific Affiliation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> The second floor balcony of the museum features prominently a {{convert|12|ft|m}} high statue of [[Dallas Cowboys]] football coach [[Tom Landry]].<ref name=\"ncse back to Glen Rose\">{{Cite web  | last = Moore | first = Randy | title = Going Back to Glen Rose | url = http://ncse.com/rncse/29/6/going-back-to-glen-rose | publisher = Reports of the [[National Center for Science Education]] | year = 2009 | accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nDisplays in the Creation Evidence Museum include:\n* The \"London Artifact\", also known as the \"[[London Hammer]]\", an [[out-of-place artifact]] found in 1934 in [[London, Texas]]. This is a hammer \"of recent American historical style\" (18th or 19th century) found in a [[limestone]] concretion that has been claimed to be [[Ordovician|Ordovician period]] or [[Cretaceous]] rock.<ref name=\"NCSE-Hammer\">{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/cej/5/1/if-i-had-hammer | title=If I Had a Hammer | publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] |date= Winter 1985|issue=Issue 15 (Volume 5, Number 1) | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> It was examined by scientists who concluded that the stone has not necessarily been part of the surrounding rock formation but can have formed around the hammer relatively recently: \"The stone is real, and it looks impressive to someone unfamiliar with geological processes... Minerals in solution can harden around an intrusive object dropped in a crack or simply left on the ground if the source rock (in this case, reportedly Ordovician) is chemically soluble.\"<ref name=\"Hammer-London\">{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/hammer.htm | title=The London Hammer: An Alleged Out-of-Place Artifact  | publisher=The Paluxy Dinosaur/\"Man Track\" Controversy |date=14 July 2006 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> \n* The \"Burdick Track\", a human footprint in Cretaceous rock. Glen J. Kuban and geologist Gregg Wilkerson described anatomical errors in the \"footprint\", and remains of algae which indicate that it was [[stone carving|carve]]d into the bottom of a limestone slab, similar to other tracks that were carved in the [[Dinosaur Valley State Park]] area.<ref name=\"Sum Paluxy\">{{Cite web | first=Glen | last=Kuban  | title = Summary of Paluxy \"Man Track\" claims | url = http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/paluxy/mantrack.html | publisher = [[TalkOrigins Archive]] | date =  1992\u20132010| accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/wilker6.htm | title=The \"Burdick Print\"  | publisher=The Paluxy Dinosaur/\"Man Track\" Controversy |year= 2008  | first=Glen | last=Kuban | accessdate = 2008-08-19}}</ref>\n* The \"Fossilized Human Finger\", a finger where tissues appear to have been [[Fossilized#Replacement and recrystallization|replaced]] by Cretaceous stone. The stone was not found in situ and according to Mark Isaak \"looks remarkably similar in size and shape to the cylindrical sandstone infillings of Ophiomoipha or Thalassmoides shrimp burrows commonly found in Cretaceous rocks. Although its general shape is fingerlike, it has none of the fine structure one would expect from a finger.\"<ref name=\"Isaak\">{{cite book|last1=Isaak|first1=Mark|title=The Counter-creationism Handbook|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520249264|page=112|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dGFJXLEWogEC&pg=PA112&dq=%22Fossilized+Human+Finger%22,&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYp-bs1r3MAhXLpx4KHRxOA-8Q6AEIITAB#v=onepage&q=%22Fossilized%20Human%20Finger%22%2C&f=false|language=en}}</ref>\n* The \"[[Meister Print]]\", two [[trilobites]] in [[slate]] that appear to be crushed in a [[sandal]] print. The print is \"questionable on several accounts\" such as the shallowness of the print, [[spall]] patterns, striding sequence, and similarities to the [[Wheeler formation]].<ref>Conrad, Ernest C. 1981. \"Tripping Over a Trilobite,\" ''Creation/Evolution'' Issue VI, pp. 30-33. [http://ncse.com/cej/2/4/tripping-over-trilobite-study-meister-tracks]</ref><ref>Stokes, William Lee. 1986. \"Alleged Human Footprint from the Middle Cambrian Strata, Millard County, Utah.\" ''Journal of Geologic Education'' Vol. 34, pp. 187-90.</ref><ref>Strahler, Arthur N. 1987. ''Science and Earth History'' Buffalo, New York: Prometheus Books. pp. 459-461. {{ISBN|1-57392-717-1}}</ref> \"In short, the trilobites in the specimen are real enough, but the 'print' itself appears to be due solely to inorganic, geologic phenomena,\" according to Kuban.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/paluxy/meister.html | title=The \"Meister Print\"  | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|year= 1998 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref>\n* The \"Hand Print in Stone\", allegedly a hand print in Cretaceous rock.<ref name=\"CEM Displays\">[http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9&Itemid=11 \"Creation Evidence Museum Online &mdash; Museum Displays\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813085507/http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9&Itemid=11 |date=2008-08-13 }}, official site. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> Baugh has provided no evidence it was [[in situ]] in any Cretaceous bed, nor allowed experts to inspect it.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/hand.htm | title=Alleged Human Hand Print in Cretaceous Rock | publisher=[[talk.origins]]|year= 2006 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2008-02-19}}</ref> Creationists have been critical of it too.<ref name=\"AIC\">[http://www.answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm \"Creation Science Rebuttals &mdash; Creation Evidence Museum Lacks Evidence!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905065319/http://answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm |date=2008-09-05 }}, by Greg Neyman, [[Answers in Creation]]. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref>\n* The \"Alvis Delk Cretaceous Footprint\", allegedly a human footprint partially overlapped by an [[Acrocanthosaurus]] dinosaur footprint, found when a slab supposedly taken from Glen Rose was later cleaned up.<ref name=\"Democrat\">[http://www.weatherforddemocrat.com/archivesearch/local_story_210103057.html \"Rock solid proof?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20090417052416/http://www.weatherforddemocrat.com/archivesearch/local_story_210103057.html |date=2009-04-17 }}, by David May, ''[[Weatherford Democrat]]'', July 28, 2008. Also printed as [http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/homepage/local_story_210093256.html \"Rock-solid proof?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://swap.stanford.edu/20100417032541/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/homepage/local_story_210093256.html |date=2010-04-17 }}, in ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]'', July 28, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"CEM Delk\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080603055755/http://75.125.60.6/~creatio1/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=48&Itemid=24 \"Creation Evidence Museum Online &ndash; Alvis Delk Cretaceous Footprint\"], official site. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"MWI Aug 11 2008\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20080928220610/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_224120721.html \"One step at a time\"], by David May, August 11, 2008, ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]''. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"MWI Aug 12 2008\">[http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_225091209.html \"Rock's finders discovering celebrity not always pleasant\"] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20100111120546/http://www.mineralwellsindex.com/local/local_story_225091209.html |date=2010-01-11 }}, by David May, August 12, 2008, ''[[Mineral Wells Index]]''. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> The footprint is presented as representing ''Homo bauanthropus'', a species name coined by Baugh but not recognised by anyone else.<ref name=\"ncse back to Glen Rose\" /> Biologist [[PZ Myers]] described it as a blatant fake. The \"human print has toes like tubes and a weirdly dug-in big toe\", while \"the dino print is even worse \u2014 it\u2019s basically a three-pronged flat plate\" with no resemblance to a real dinosaur footprint.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://scienceblogs.com/pharyngula/2008/07/28/transparent-fakery/ | title=Transparent fakery | publisher=[[Pharyngula (blog)]] |date=July 28, 2008 | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref> Kuban described anatomical problems in detail. He notes that the slab was not documented in situ, and there are significant issues with [[CT scan]]s claimed to authenticate the slab. Other creationists have not supported the claims, and one of those originally promoting the slab has removed the information from his website.<ref name=\"Sum Paluxy\"/><ref>{{Cite web  | last = Kuban | first = Glen J. | title = The Delk Print | url = http://paleo.cc/paluxy/delk.htm | publisher =  | date =  | accessdate = 30 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1982&ndash;1984, several scientists, including J.R. Cole, L.R. Godfrey, R.J. Hastings, and [[Steven Schafersman]], examined Baugh's purported \"mantracks\" as well as others provided by creationists in Glen Rose. In the course of the examination \"Baugh contradicted his own earlier reports of the locations of key discoveries\" and many of the supposed prints \"lacked characteristics of human footprints.\" After a three-year investigation of the tracks and Baugh's specimens, the scientists concluded there was no evidence for any of Baugh's claims or any \"dinosaur-man tracks\".<ref name=\"NCSE-Examine\">{{cite news | url=http://ncse.com/cej/5/1/introduction | title=Creation/Evolution | publisher=[[National Center for Science Education]] |date=Winter 1985|issue=Issue 15 (Volume 5, Number 1) | first= | last= | accessdate = 2007-02-19}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism from creationists ==\nYoung Earth creationist organizations such as [[Answers in Genesis]] and [[Creation Ministries International]] have criticized Baugh's claims saying he \"muddied the water for many Christians ... People are being misled.\"<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Don Batten, of [[Creation Ministries International]] wrote: \"Some Christians will try to use Baugh's 'evidences' in witnessing and get 'shot down' by someone who is scientifically literate. The ones witnessed to will thereafter be wary of all creation evidences and even more inclined to dismiss Christians as [[wiktionary:nutcase#English|nut cases]] not worth listening to.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://paleo.cc/paluxy/whatbau.htm  | title=What About Carl Baugh?| publisher=[[Creation Ministries International]] |year= 1998 | first= | last=  | accessdate =2007-05-17}}</ref> Answers in Genesis lists the \"Paluxy tracks\" as arguments \"we think creationists should NOT use\" [emphasis in original].<ref name=\"AIGCriticism\">{{cite news | url=http://creation.com/arguments-we-think-creationists-should-not-use | title=Arguments we think creationists should NOT use | publisher=[[Answers In Genesis]] |year= 2008 | first= | last=  | accessdate =2007-05-17}}</ref> The old Earth creationist organization [[Answers In Creation]] also reviewed Baugh's museum and concluded \"the main artifacts they claim show a young earth reveal that they are deceptions, and in many cases, not even clever ones.\"<ref name=\"AICReview\">{{cite news | url=http://www.answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm | title=Review of Carl Baugh's Museum | publisher=[[Answers In Creation]] | year=2008 | first= | last= | accessdate=2007-05-17 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905065319/http://answersincreation.org/rebuttal/cem/cem.htm | archive-date=2008-09-05 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe \"Burdick track\" and \"fossilized finger\" were featured on the controversial [[NBC]] program ''[[The Mysterious Origins of Man]]'', aired in 1996 and hosted by [[Charlton Heston]].<ref name=\"Kuban\">[http://paleo.cc/paluxy/nbc.htm \"A Review of NBC's 'The Mysterious Origins of Man'\"], 1996, Glen J. Kuban. Retrieved August 15, 2008.</ref> Creationist [[Ken Ham]] criticized the production in the February 1996 [[Answers in Genesis]] newsletter in a review titled \"Hollywood's 'Moses' Undermines [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]].\"<ref name=\"SkepticalOrigins\"/> Ham attacked Baugh's claims, saying, \"According to leading creationist researchers, this evidence is open to much debate and needs much more intensive research. One wonders how much of the information in the program can really be trusted!\"<ref name=\"SkepticalOrigins\">{{cite news|url=http://www.csicop.org/sb/9603/origins.html |title=NBC's Origins Show |publisher=[[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] |date=March 1996 |first=Dave |last=Thomas |access-date=2007-02-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070203134301/http://www.csicop.org/sb/9603/origins.html |archive-date=2007-02-03 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Creation Evidence Museum}}\n*[[Creation Museum]], museum in Northern [[Kentucky]]\n*[[Kent Hovind#Dinosaur Adventure Land|Dinosaur Adventure Land]], bankrupt theme park in Pensacola, Florida by Kent Hovind\n*[[Dinosaur Valley State Park#Controversy|Glen Rose dinosaur-human hoax]]\n*[[List of museums in North Texas]]\n*[[List of museums in Texas]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.creationevidence.org/ Creation Evidence Museum Online] &mdash; official site.\n\n[[Category:Museums established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Museums in Somervell County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscience]]\n[[Category:Creationist museums in the United States]]\n[[Category:Religious museums in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "47.219.108.168", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Omitted unnecessary biased and negative comments as well as hearsay.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creation_Evidence_Museum"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Hastie (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015 }}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Hastie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n| image            = Andrew Hastie Orignal.jpg\n| caption          = Hastie in 2018\n| constituency_MP  = [[Division of Canning|Canning]]\n| parliament       = Australian\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = [[Don Randall]]\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 19 September 2015\n| term_end         = \n| office1          = Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]]\n| deputy1          = [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]]\n| term_start1      = 15 February 2017\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Michael Sukkar]]\n| successor1       = \n| birthname        = Andrew William Hastie\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|9|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Wangaratta, Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Ruth Hastie\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| relations        = \n| children         = 2\n| residence        = [[Mandurah, Western Australia]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of New South Wales|UNSW]], [[Australian Defence Force Academy|ADFA]], [[Royal Military College, Duntroon|Duntroon]], [[George Washington University|GWU]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|www.andrewhastie.com.au}}\n| footnotes        = \n| allegiance       = Australia\n| branch           = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears     = 2001\u20132015\n| rank             = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n| unit             = [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]] (2007\u20132009)<br />[[Special Air Service Regiment]] (2010\u20132015)\n| battles          = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew William Hastie''' (born 30 September 1982) is an Australian politician who serves as Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] and as the Federal MP for [[Division of Canning|Canning]], [[Western Australia|WA]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]]. He was first elected in the [[2015 Canning by-election]] and re-elected in 2016 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|website=www.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> A controversial figure, his public statements for Australia to \"preserve our sovereignty\"<ref name=\"Hastie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> in defiance of an \"expansionist\"<ref name=\"Grattan\">{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/politics-with-michelle-grattan-andrew-hastie-on-foreign-influence-security-and-veteran-mental-health-128545|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Andrew Hastie on foreign influence, security and veteran mental health|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> [[Communist Party of China]] have been condemned as \"totally intemperate\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Richard|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/kerry-stokes-says-andrew-hastie-did-more-harm-than-good-with-china-remarks/news-story/bc218d8b7cbffd3f1cc3ec6cb6db8ee8|title=Kerry Stokes says Andrew Hastie did more harm than good with China remarks|date=9 February 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"inflammatory\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/western-australia/wa-premier-slams-andrew-hastie-s-china-concerns-as-extreme-and-inflammatory-20190808-p52f7m.html|title=WA Premier slams Andrew Hastie's China concerns as 'extreme and inflammatory'|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2019-08-08|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> by Australian corporate leaders, then praised as a matter of \"strong public interest\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/pm/strong-public-interest-in-chinese-influence-claims/9792976|title=\"Strong public interest\" in Chinese influence claims|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC Radio|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and \"necessary, and important\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2019/08/17/how-the-china-question-split-australian-politics/15659640008614|title=How the China question split Australian politics|last=Seccombe|first=Mike|date=2019-08-17|website=The Saturday Paper|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> by security analysts [[Clive Hamilton|Professor Clive Hamilton]] and Professor Rory Medcalf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/in-defence-of-andrew-hastie-20190811-p52fyw|title=In defence of Andrew Hastie|date=2019-08-11|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> His stance led to the [[Government of China]] refusing him and his colleague [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] from visiting China on a study tour, demanding that they \"repent\" from their views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/outspoken-liberal-politicians-must-repent-and-redress-says-china|title='Outspoken' Liberal politicians must 'repent and redress', says China|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nHastie's mother Sue was a primary school teacher, particularly to children with special needs. [[File:Andrew Hastie with his father Peter Hastie back yard Wangaratta Victoria circa 1983.jpg|alt=Andrew Hastie, age 1, with his father Peter, around 1983|thumb|Andrew Hastie with his father Peter, in the backyard of their home in Wangaratta, Victoria, circa 1983]] Her mother Rose \u2014 to whom, Hastie says in his first speech, he was \"very close\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Australian Parliament House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\u2014 was a nurse throughout her life, caring for Hastie's grandfather, Reginald a war veteran, through to his death.\n\nSimilarly, his paternal grandfather served as an officer with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was severely wounded by gunfire when covering the air-sea rescue of two downed Australian airmen during the [[Pacific War]] for which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|title=First Speech|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|website=www.andrewhastie.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> His son (Hastie's father) Peter has served as a pastor in church communities, early on in rural [[Wangaratta]], Victoria; and later in the inner urban suburb of [[Ashfield, New South Wales|Ashfield,]] where he launched a Mandarin speaking congregation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWhen the family moved to the inner west of Sydney, Hastie began his primary education at Ashbury Public School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=May 4, 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> From year 5 he attended [[The Scots College]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2015|title=Old Boy News|url=https://www.tsc.nsw.edu.au/hubfs/Lion_and_Lang_Syne_Summer_2015.pdf|journal=The Lion & Lang Syne|volume=26|pages=49|via=}}</ref> in [[Sydney]], completing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|Higher School Certificate]] in 2000. Intending to become a journalist, Hastie began a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in History, Politics and Philosophy at the Kensington Campus of [[University of New South Wales]] in 2001, and also joined the [[University of New South Wales Regiment]] as a part-time reservist. At a tutorial near the end of first year, following [[September 11 attacks|September 11 terror attacks]] Hastie says he listened to other students argue that the [[United States]] had \u201cdeserved\u201d the attack, which he says he found \u201cbizarre\",<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/australia/war-has-its-limits-hastie-tells-mps-ng-ya-130555|title=War has its limits, new MP Andrew Hastie tells Parliament|date=2015-10-14|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> the event would \"shape the next decade of my life.\"<ref name=\"Hastie\"/><blockquote>I was planning on being a foreign correspondent. 9/11 happened and the daughter of my year 2/3 teacher at Ashbury Public School, she died in one of the towers, I think she was 90 floors up. And so that event, apart from the obvious impact it had on Australia, it came very close to me and my life and I had a tradition of service in my family and thought, you know what, this is a big, historical shift, I want to be part of this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=unforgiving60|website=unforgiving60|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie with book.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Andrew Hastie at the rear of his ASLAV Type 1, holding a copy of ''Empire'' by Scottish historian [[Niall Ferguson]].]]\nHastie decided to join the [[Australian Army]] full-time, but completed his second year at the Kensington Campus in 2002 before transferring to the [[University of New South Wales]] at [[Australian Defence Force Academy]] in Canberra in 2003. He completed his bachelor's degree in 2004 before being invited to do an honours year in 2005, his final thesis examined [[Charles Bean]]'s official history of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. Hastie still regards himself as a student of history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourlocalexaminer.com.au/andrew-hastie-maiden-speech/|title=Hastie sworn in, vows to put Canning people first|last=Hastie|first=Hamish|date=2015-10-14|website=Your Local Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and recently wrote the forward to ''Destined for War''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.scribd.com/book/350699416/Destined-for-War-can-America-and-China-escape-Thucydides-Trap|title=Destined for War by Graham Allison and Andrew Hastie - Book - Read Online|language=en}}</ref> an historical survey of global conflicts, beginning with the [[Peloponnesian War]] by [[Graham T. Allison]].\n\nHastie went on to officer training at [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In 2007, Hastie completed the [[George Washington University]] [[Elliott School of International Affairs]]'s U.S. Foreign Policy Summer Program in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Military service (2001\u20132015)==\nHastie initially intended to serve purely in the [[Australian Army Reserve]], participating in their officer training in 2001 and 2002 with the University of New South Wales Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=September 11 Australian Stories|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426162732/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2011/09/08/september-11-australian-stories|website=www.sbs.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> The events of [[9/11]] prompted him towards full-time army service beginning 2003. Having graduated from ADFA and Duntroon, he received his commission as a Lieutenant at the end of 2006 and began his chosen career in Royal Australian Armoured Corps in 2007. He first served in [[2nd Armoured Division (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]], beginning his command of a cavalry troop in 2008. The regiment is the second most senior regiment in the [[Royal Australian Armoured Corps]], which was attached to the 1st Brigade, based in Darwin, Northern Territory.<ref>{{cite web|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment|url=https://www.army.gov.au/our-people/units/forces-command/1st-brigade/2nd-cavalry-regiment|website=www.army.gov.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan, 2009-2010 ===\n[[File:Charmestan valley afghanistan.jpg|thumb|MRTF-2 Commanding Officer's Tactical Party, on the edge of the Charmestan Valley, Urozgan Province, Afghanistan.]]\n[[File:Hastie overlooking Chora Valley.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie overlooking the Chora Valley from his Type I ASLAV.]]\n\n Hastie first deployed to Afghanistan with the Mentoring and Reconstruction Task Force Two, a 750-strong Australian combined arms battle group. He commanded a troop of [[ASLAV|Australian Light Armoured Vehicle]]s on patrols in [[Uruzgan province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf |publisher=The Australian Army |title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009 |date=1 July 2010 |accessdate=2 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923174042/http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref> Operations began at the very start of the fighting season in May 2009, concluding in February 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nautilus.org/publications/books/australian-forces-abroad/afghanistan/mentoring-task-force/|title=Mentoring Task Force|date=2011-12-19|website=Nautilus Institute for Security and Sustainability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> aiming \u201cto dominate the threat\u201d using \u201cclose combat to destroy the enemy with precision.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|last=Connolly|first=Peter|publisher=Land Warfare Studies Centre|year=2011|isbn=|location=Canberra|pages=}}</ref> For Hastie, the wider goal of Western forces was an attempt to reshape Afghanistan: <blockquote>Our job pretty much was the stick. The carrot was the mentoring piece, the aid that was delivered through DFAT, also there at the time and other NGOs. And we were the stick that kept the bad guys back.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>The responsibilities of Hastie's own troop were convoy escort and force overwatch - for which it was attacked by the enemy intermittently, mostly by [[improvised explosive device]]s. In interview, he explained, \"We had four strikes in my troop alone.\u201d<ref name=\"Development\">{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Special Air Service Regiment, 2010-2012 ===\n[[File:Insigne du Special Air Service Regiment (SASR).svg|thumb|Insignia of the Special Air Service Regiment (SASR)]]Hastie successfully applied for entry to the [[Special Air Service Regiment]]\u00a0Selection Course (known simply as \"Selection\"). The process is designed to identify soldiers with diverse backgrounds and strong character as they are able to \u201cgenerate unconventional answers to strategic and tactical problems\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cios.org/EJCPUBLIC/010/1/01013.html|title=Article from ejc/rec|website=www.cios.org|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> as needed for a Tier 1 [[Special forces]] unit. His cohort featured in the SBS documentary ''The Search for Warriors''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/video/11757123841/SAS-The-Search-For-Warriors-S1-Ep1|title=SAS - The Search For Warriors S1 Ep1|website=SBS PopAsia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> where Hastie has been identified as candidate 10. With the other candidates, Hastie was subjected to extreme exercises, a deliberate system in which, according to the Lieutenant Colonel who had oversight of Hastie's Selection, \u201cwe will break an individual down.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackfootstudios.com/forums/index.php?/forums/topic/5012-australian-sas-selection-documentary/|title=Australian SAS Selection Documentary|website=BlackFoot Studios|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Exercises included \u201cLucky Dip\u201d, five days working with teams to move heavy equipment by hand through the bush, with only one meal in that time; and a 150&nbsp;km five-day solo trek across mountainous terrain, which Hastie recalled in interview:<blockquote>\u201cI remember on Selection being up on one of the mountains in the Stirling ranges, being asked, \u201cWhy do you want to be here?\u201d I said, \u201cBecause last time I was in Afghanistan I was driving around getting blown up and I actually want to go after these guys.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> </blockquote>Hastie's Selection experience concluded with a three-day extreme interrogation session, involving constant sleep deprivation and starvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/documentary-reveals-gruelling-sas-selection-process/news-story/4488a528d9e0bffd2bc98c43cc2a9350|title=SAS: We will break an individual down|date=2010-12-06|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>  Men in the group lost between 10 and 15 kilograms from exertion and malnutrition. From Hastie's initial cohort of 131, only 26 completed the course.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/national/2015/08/21/can-pass-sas-test/|title=The most gruelling tests of the SAS|date=2015-08-21|website=The New Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> From there Hastie commenced the 18-month Reinforcement Cycle before receiving qualification with the Regiment, based at [[Campbell Barracks]]. He was given his \u201csandy beret\u201d in May 2012 and was assigned to 1 SAS Squadron. His first overseas deployment was in Port Moresby to support the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] as they provide security and stability for the General Election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2012/s3523650.htm|title=Australia provides help for PNG elections|date=2012-06-12|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Commanding special forces troop in Afghanistan, 2013  ===\n[[File:Australia\u2019s Special Operations Task Group mentors Provincial Response Company \u2013 Uruzgan 130427-A-FS372-213.jpg|thumb|Australia's Special Operations Task Group was partnered with the local Provincial Police Ready Reaction Auxiliary Force which involved training, support and some joint operations.]]\n\nIn January 2013, Hastie returned to Afghanistan as an SASR officer with Special Operations Task Group Rotation XIX. Hastie led his troop in operations against hostile [[Taliban]] leadership in southern Afghanistan, commanding B Troop. The wider mission was to provide force protection as the ADF mentored the nascent [[Afghan National Security Force]]. Hastie directed counter-leadership operations:<blockquote>This meant targeting and taking out the Taliban leadership, helping to support the building of institutions such as schools, and trying to carve out some space for the new Afghan Government to govern.<ref name=\"Whinnett\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>At points, operations were also protective. Hastie and his troops were a part the successful removal of enemy combatants who fired rockets at the Allied base and prevented a truck bomb from coming through the front gates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The Untold Story of SAS mission|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> As part of Task Force 66 (Special Operations Task Groups IV-XX) Hastie's unit was awarded a [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] for \"outstanding service on operations against an unrelenting, cunning and ruthless enemy, in an unforgiving environment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-day-honours-list-2015|title=Australia Day honours list 2015|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Deaths of Toor Jan and Odood ====\nIn February 2013, Hastie led a team of men to support a remote outpost of Afghan National Police. While there, he received communication intercepts indicating two Taliban fighters, seen at a distance of 1,200 metres, were planning a rocket attack on the post.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hastie had authority to neutralise the threat, communicated the coordinates for the combatants and called in a strike by a US Army Apache helicopter. However, the attack went badly wrong:<blockquote>I remember looking at the target, and then hearing the guns fire and then the rounds splashing 600m away and thinking, \u2018what the heck, that is not at all, that is not the target.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\"/></blockquote>Two boys, Toor Jan, age 7 and his brother Odood, who were collecting firewood had been mistakenly targeted for the two Taliban figures. An ADF inquiry later cleared the Australian forces of any breakdown in procedure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fdefence%2Fandrew-hastie-in-clear-on-second-afghan-incident%2Fnews-story%2Fb91a2ab20fa8ccfe4fb7f1a546b5e7cd&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=9daa57764cfab982111b15402df38b47-1576880157|title=Andrew Hastie in clear on second afghan incident|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> For Hastie, the death of the boys was both personally affecting and a turning point in his political outlook:<blockquote>I just felt sick. My stomach just dropped away.... It was arrogant to think we could build a mirror image of ourselves in foreign lands. [The boys\u2019 deaths] underscored the gap between our aims and reality. The two boys who perished were bystanders in this larger struggle. I was humbled and chastened by this experience. War is a miserable enterprise. I remember saying to my boss: \u2018I didn\u2019t come here to kill kids\u2019.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>\n\n==== Inquiry into severed hands ====\nOne engagement with the Taliban became the subject of a major investigation. On April 28 2013, a major operation began against the senior insurgent commander, Abdul Hai.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Masters|first=Chris|title=No Front Line: Australian special forces at war in Afghanistan|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=515}}</ref> Led by Hastie's SASR B Troop, several combatants were killed in the ensuing battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> On searching the dead men, one corporal severed the right hands of two \"Enemy Killed in Action\" using a scalpel. On attempting to do the same to a third EKIA the soldier was stopped by a sergeant who said, \u201cWhat the f*** are you doing?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> On arriving at this part of battle environment, Hastie gave the order to cease the practice and the next day the incident was reported to the CO, triggering a major ADF inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> The inquiry heard that there had recently been training on how to collect biometric samples, particularly in managing the aftermath of a suicide bomb event,<ref>{{Cite book|title=No Front Line|last=Masters|first=Chris|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2017|isbn=9781760111144|location=Australia|pages=518}}</ref> Hastie later commented that \u201cthe guy giving instructions conflated site exploitation of a suicide bomber with that of biometric testing.\" The SASR corporal who severed the hands later conceded he had made an error of judgement in not first checking with his patrol commander.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> The inquiry made it clear that the practice, and the fact that some appeared to accept it at the time, \"demonstrated a drift in values, or at least a degree of desensitisation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Jordan and Afghanistan, 2014-2015 ===\nHastie deployed in late-2014 and 2015 to an intelligence role<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> in the Middle East-based role countering [[ISIL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-21/hastie-liberal-candidate-keogh-alp-canning-byelection/6713986|title=Andrew Hastie to run for Liberals, Matt Keogh for ALP in Canning by-election|date=20 August 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> as an Operations Officer for Operation Gallant Phoenix,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> a classified defence operation based in Jordan. The operation is said to be collecting intelligence \"from commando raids in Syria and Iraq and funnelling it to law enforcement agencies in Europe and Southeast Asia to help stop future attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/24/us/politics/us-isis-fight.html|title=Its Territory May Be Gone, but the U.S. Fight Against ISIS Is Far From Over|date=2019-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|last2=Gibbons-Neff|first2=Thomas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cooper|first3=Helene|last4=Rubin|first4=Alissa J.}}</ref> Hastie resigned his commission from the ADF in August 2015 after announcing his candidature to run as the Member for Canning in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/andrew-hastie-liberal-byelection-candidate-led-troop-probed-for-chopping-hands-off-taliban-20150821-gj52lj.html|title=Andrew Hastie, Liberal byelection candidate, was in charge of troop probed for chopping hands off Taliban|date=22 August 2015|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n==Political career (2015\u2013present)==\n\n=== Election and first Turnbull Government ===\nThe seat of [[Division of Canning|Canning]] became vacant by the death in office of the Liberal member, [[Don Randall]], triggering the [[2015 Canning by-election]]. Hastie began a launched his campaign with strong support from [[Mathias Cormann]] and [[Julie Bishop]], however he was quickly inundated with media criticism about the \"severed hands\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/08/australia-election-dictate-pm-fate-150830103706951.html|title=Australia by-election could dictate PM's fate|last=Kurmelovs|first=Royce|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> incident and was further \"rattled\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=2015-09-11|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> by strong questioning of his family's religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=2015-09-11|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Within days Hastie would give a speech in which he strongly defended the soldiers under his command and his own military service:<blockquote>I have not lived my life behind a desk pushing paper and talking about the concepts of freedom and democracy. I have acted. I have put my life on the line for this country and for that freedom.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>On Saturday 19 September 2015, after a four-week campaign that centred on solving the [[methamphetamine]] epidemic, Hastie won 55.26% of votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party-preferred]] system, making him the 10th Federal Member for Canning, defeating Labor candidate [[Matt Keogh]]. He joined the government of [[Malcolm Turnbull]] who had himself become [[Prime Minister of Australia]] a week before the by-election. Hastie gave his first speech on 13 October 2015, which centred on his priorities for healthy democracy, stronger community institutions and for defending Australia's sovereignty, \"To safeguard our freedom I believe that the first duty of the Australian federal government is to secure our nation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=ParlInfo - BUSINESS : Rearrangement|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In the first months, when headlines were dominated by the [[2015 Parramatta shooting|Parramatta shooting]] and the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attack]] and the aftermath of the [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|Sydney hostage crisis]], it seemed that Hastie's parliamentary career would be marked by his concern<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/asio-chief-called-just-two-coalition-mps-about-islam-debate-malcolm-turnbull-20151218-glr0js.html|title=ASIO chief called just two Coalition MPs about Islam debate: Malcolm Turnbull|last=Kenny|first=David Wroe and Mark|date=2015-12-18|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> about \"radical islamist ideology\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Alberici|first=Emma|title=Interview: Andrew Hastie, Liberal MP|date=2017-05-31|url=https://www.abc.net.au/lateline/interview:-andrew-hastie,-liberal-mp/8577672|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> arguing in interviews<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2gb.com/podcast/alan-jones-andrew-hastie/|title=Alan Jones \u2013 Andrew Hastie|date=1448967022|website=2GB|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and op eds that: <blockquote>I have read the Koran in its entirety. In my previous job with the Australian Defence Force, I studied Islamic State propaganda including many of its violent videos and images in an effort to understand their objectives, aims and rationale. I was disturbed by what I saw, but not cowed into inaction.... we should be free to question the roots of Islamic terrorism, especially the brand pushed by Islamic State. It is troubling that we have had young Australians sympathising with the theology and ideology of Islamic State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=AAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.adelaidenow.com.au%2Fnews%2Fopinion%2Fwe-should-be-free-to-question-the-roots-of-islamic-terrorism-especially-the-brand-pushed-by-islamic-state-writes-andrew-hastie%2Fnews-story%2F81bc06145842d58af1c980edb20d0b42&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=3290dea7434c4d3e6d98e6f90da327e0-1586142284|title=Adelaidenow.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Advertiser for exclusive stories|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Re-election and second Turnbull Government ===\nHastie stood again for the division of Canning for the [[2016 Australian federal election]], on Saturday 2 July. He won 56.79% of the votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote]] against Labor opposition candidate Barry Winmar, moving his seat from being \"marginal\" to \"fairly safe\" according to the [[Australian Electoral Commission]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} He was appointed to the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] [[File:Andrew Hastie MP, Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with Deputy Chair Anthony Byrne MP in February 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Anthony Byrne, a Labor MP and Deputy Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with its Chair, Andrew Hastie MP. ]]in September 2016, and invited to chair the committee from February 2017.<ref>http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F9de5f081-9ccf-4f72-a05a-02462c1f3a0c%2F0136%22 Retrieved 15 June 2017</ref> It's known the committee receives briefings from [[Inspector-General of Intelligence and Security (Australia)]], [[Australian Signals Directorate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/plans-to-boost-electronic-spy-agency-meet-with-extreme-caution-20190615-p51y1o.html|title=Plans to boost electronic spy agency meet with extreme caution|last=Ireland|first=David Wroe, Judith|date=2019-06-15|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> and [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/four-hour-top-secret-briefing-used-to-press-encryption-law-need-516084|title=Four hour 'top secret' briefing used to press encryption law need|website=iTnews|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> As such, Hastie and fellow members of the [[bi-partisan]] committee are \"privy to a lot of information and intelligence briefings that other members of parliament aren't.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6070077627001|title='We can't deny there are problems with China's behaviour': Dutton|website=Sky News Australia|language=|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> Through his work with the PJCIS Hastie came to conclude that Australia is \"facing an unprecedented threat from espionage and foreign interference, and that current laws are not adequate to deal with this threat.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/foreign-interference-laws-needed-before-super-saturday-vote-christian-porter-says-20180607-h113o9|title=Foreign interference laws needed before super Saturday vote, Christian Porter says|date=2018-06-07|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> At this point the source of the foreign interference was unnamed. Following its deliberations, the committee reviewed and amended the [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018C00506 Espionage and Foreign Interference Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defence.gov.au/dsvs/industry/DISP-foreign-espionage.asp|title=Foreign Espionage & Interference Act 2018 : Industry Security Program : Department of Defence|last=|website=www.defence.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018A00029 Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/about-us/our-portfolios/national-security/security-coordination/security-of-critical-infrastructure-act-2018|title=Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018|website=www.homeaffairs.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== First Morrison Government ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie and daughter (KN).jpg|thumb|In Parliamentary offices, Andrew Hastie plays with his daughter. ]]\nIn August 2018, Malcolm Turnbull called for two [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|leadership spills]], in which Hastie is known to have supported the call for a new leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-24/the-liberal-mps-that-sparked-the-spill/10161660|title=The 43 Liberal MPs that brought down Malcolm Turnbull|date=2018-08-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> [[Scott Morrison]] was elected leader of the Liberal Party, becoming [[Prime Minister of Australia]]. Hastie maintained his chairmanship of the PJCIS as it took an increasingly serious tone on foreign threats. The committee carried the Assistance and Access Bill 2018 through to legislation enabling security agencies to access otherwise encrypted communications by people who intend harm to Australians. Prompted by the sale of the Port of [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] to interests connected to the Communist Party of China, the Committee made recommendations for the Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018 (Cth) (Act)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corrs.com.au/insights/critical-infrastructure-reporting-starts-now|title=Critical infrastructure: reporting starts now|website=Corrs Chambers Westgarth|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \u2014 placing a national security test to any foreign investment into energy or water assets and, notably, ports. The committee also contributed amendments to the Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme Act 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/Integrity/foreign-influence-transparency-scheme/Pages/default.aspx|title=Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme|last=Department|first=Attorney-Generals's|website=www.ag.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nIn his constituency work, Hastie surprised some by giving public support to striking [[Alcoa Australia]] workers, organised by the [[Australian Workers' Union]]. Hastie said, he supported the strikers because, \"energy production in Australia is too expensive and it is hurting industry, workers, seniors and families. We have to put Australians first. Otherwise, more jobs will go offshore to other countries. Our smelters and refineries will close down. Energy security is job security.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/andrew-hastie-utility-bills-are-crippling-workingclass-families/news-story/d2890e742284107f09917bfcbfd78a08|title=Utility bills are crippling working-class families|date=November 23, 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Re-election and second Morrison Government ===\n[[File:AH and PM at Mandurah War Memorial (KN).jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Scott Morrison and Andrew Hastie MP stand by ANZAC wreaths at a memorial in Mandurah.]]\nIn the [[2019 Australian federal election]], held on May 18, Hastie ran for re-election and won 61.83% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]] against the Australian Labor Party's candidate Mellisa Teede. On entering the [[46th Parliament of Australia]] Hastie, in which [[Scott Morrison]] was returned as Prime Minister, Hastie become increasingly involved in lawmaking around matters of national security. He spoke in 45 debates in 2019, above average according to Open Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/mp/andrew_hastie/canning|title=Andrew Hastie MP, Canning (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> the bulk of them surrounding matters of security or sovereignty.  [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] pushed forward the Temporary Exclusion Orders Bill designed to prevent dual-national terrorists from returning to Australia. [[File:Andrew Hastie MP with flag gifted to him by SASR operators January 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie in his electoral office in Mandurah, with an Australian flag given to him by a friend in the ADF, it had once flown at a army forward operating base]]However, the Identity-matching Services Bill 2019 and the Australian Passports Amendment (Identity-matching Services) Bill 2019 were reviewed by the committee and sent back for redrafting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/facial-recognition-bill-knocked-back-20191024-p533s6|title=Facial recognition bill knocked back|date=2019-10-23|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> By 2020, Hastie was able to review the suite of legislative changes security as being all of one piece, to strengthen Australia's position in the region and the world:<blockquote>What we\u2019ve done in Australia over the last three or four years, I call it our pivot... taking action to preserve our digital sovereignty by excluding high-risk vendors from our future 5G network, passing the Espionage and Foreign Interference Laws, stopping the extradition treaty to China, those things were part of the pivot and ultimately, they\u2019re expressions of our sovereignty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\u00a0 </blockquote>\n\n==== \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\" ====\n[[File:Joint media release Hastie Paterson November 15 2019.jpg|alt=A media release from Andrew Hastie MP and Senator James Paterson.|thumb|Hastie and James Paterson confirm they have been blocked from visiting China following their public comments about the [[Communist Party of China]]]]\nIn August 2019 Hastie wrote an [[Op-ed]] column, \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> for [[The Sydney Morning Herald|''The Sydney Morning Herald'']] and [[The Age|''The Age'']] newspapers<ref name=\"Hastie\"/>, where he admitted that Communist China \u2014 rather than [[Islamic terrorism]], which he worked to defeat in his military career \u2014 would be the real security concern of the 21st Century. Moreover, a rising, revisionist, expansionist China would frame \"almost every strategic and economic question facing Australia in the coming decades.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>  What brought more attention was his strong criticism of Western democracies and their mistaken belief \"that economic liberalisation would naturally lead to democratisation in China\" much as the French had believed the [[Maginot Line]] would guard them against the German advance in 1940. Hastie wrote, \"Like the French, Australia has failed to see how mobile our authoritarian neighbour has become.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last1=Hastie|first1=Andrew|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The piece caused \"a firestorm\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> with the [[Embassy of China, Canberra|Chinese Embassy in Australia]] denouncing the remarks as reflecting a \"[[Cold war (general term)|Cold War]] mentality\",<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Liberal MP Andrew Hastie condemned by China after comparing Beijing's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last1=Laschon|first1=Eliza|date=8 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> while Western Australian Premier [[Mark McGowan]], whose state is heavily reliant on China for trade,<ref name=\"abcaunazi\">{{cite news|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-09/wa-particularly-vulnerable-in-a-china-us-trade-war/11395926|title=Western Australia's huge reliance on China leaves it particularly vulnerable in a trade war|last1=O'Flaherty|first1=Alisha|date=10 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> accusing Hastie of \"threatening WA jobs with extreme and inflammatory language.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> An academic at UWA opined that the Western Australian government's contemporaneous relationship with China may not be sustainable in the future, saying \"But there may come a time where this relationship is not possible to be run purely on commercial lines, and I have to say most of the reason for that is the changing behaviour of the Chinese Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> Conversely, Hastie received support from his colleagues [[Dave Sharma]]<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-wins-support-for-his-china-warning-from-former-diplomat-sharma-20190810-p52fup.html|title=Hastie wins support for his China warning from former diplomat Sharma|last1=Wright|first1=Shane|date=10 August 2019|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Peter Dutton]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/no-point-pretending-there-s-nothing-to-see-here-peter-dutton-warns-on-china-20190809-p52fgz.html|title='No point pretending there's nothing to see here': Peter Dutton warns on China|last1=Shields|first1=Bevan|date=9 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Hastie had been invited on a study trip with several colleagues to China with the independent think tank China Matters. However the Chinese embassy announced \u201cthat at this time Mr Hastie and Senator Paterson are not welcome\" unless they \"genuinely repent and redress their mistakes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/15/china-denies-entry-to-liberal-mps-andrew-hastie-and-james-paterson|title=China denies entry to Liberal MPs Andrew Hastie and James Paterson|last=editor|first=Katharine Murphy Political|date=2019-11-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This snub had the effect of making [[Communist Party of China]] attempts to control the behaviour and speech of people in sovereign nations an even bigger concern. Hastie's warnings about Chinese abuses of human rights and interference with sovereign nations appeared to be vindicated when newspapers released 400 pages of Chinese documents<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=2019-11-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-18|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> on the workings of internment camps in [[Xinjiang]], shortly followed by the apparent defection of a young Chinese spy with information in connection with a Chinese Australian, Nick Zhao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-25/chinese-spy-parliament-foreign-interference-in-hong-kong-taiwan/11735176|title=A man is dead. Another fears being killed. Here's a breakdown of the claims about Chinese espionage|last=Conifer|first=Dan|date=2019-11-25|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> who was funded by Chinese interests to run for parliament, and was later found dead in a hotel room. By raising concerns about foreign interference, the opinion piece has been seen as a \"threshold\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>, with other commentators predicting that Hastie's concerns \"will dominate the political agenda\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/ellen-whinnett-china-crisis-looms-large-in-canberra/news-story/66c19d19acafcbaa2a914fabe17b23d5|title=China crisis looms large in Canberra|date=December 4, 2019|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, having been discussed in the pages of global newspapers such as ''[[Haaretz]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|last=Melman|first=Yossi|date=December 6, 2019|website=haaretz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>  [[The Times|''The Times'']]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/beijing-denies-australian-mps-right-to-visit-china-bldtfvl2j|title=Beijing denies Australian MPs right to visit China|last=Times|first=Bernard Lagan, Sydney {{!}} The|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/28/world/australia/china-spying-wang-liqiang-nick-zhao.html|title=Suddenly, the Chinese Threat to Australia Seems Very Real|last=Cave|first=Damien|date=2019-11-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-18|last2=Tarabay|first2=Jamie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHastie has been described as a \"conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/ruthless-hardline-and-focused-the-mp-who-stunned-parliament-20180525-p4zhgy.html|title='Ruthless, hardline and focused': The MP who stunned Parliament|last=Wright|first=Tony|date=2018-05-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>, a \"social conservative\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/08/canning-byelection-the-complete-and-completely-unofficial-guide-to-the-candidates|title=Canning byelection: the complete (and completely unofficial) guide to the candidates|date=2015-09-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and, at least by the official Chinese government media as \"an arch-conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/21/c_137406904.htm|title=News Analysis: Aussie gov't set for period of upheaval following leadership challenge to PM - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>. Critics see his foreign policy outlook as being \"jingoistic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1161600.shtml|title=Australia need not follow US script on its relationship with China - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> and the MP himself as \"a notorious hawk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/08/andrew-hasties-nazi-germany-warning-on-china-labelled-extreme-and-unwelcome|title=China denounces Liberal MP Andrew Hastie's Nazi Germany analogy|date=2019-08-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Hastie himself has said, \"I am not a libertarian, but I am a Liberal, which is to say that I am committed to freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/blogs/andrew-bolt/andrew-hastie-shames-the-free-speech-quislings/news-story/1f81333ae068f76e98ca8b311effcc1d|title=Andrew Hastie Shames the Free Speech Quislings|last=Bolt|first=Andrew|date=March 3, 2017|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 30 2020}}</ref> This would appear to be confirmed by his decision to join the [[Atlantic Council]] \u2014 a [[Classical liberalism|Classical liberal]] bi-partisan think tank formed for \"defending democratic values.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/cbd-melbourne-hockey-ready-to-ride-post-virus-bondi-wave-20200325-p54dw1.html|title=CBD Melbourne: Hockey ready to ride post-virus Bondi wave|last=Loussikian|first=Samantha Hutchinson, Kylar|date=2020-03-25|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The invitation<ref name=\":5\" /> came via US Congressman [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]], a conservative [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Tom Tugendhat]], a British MP who describes himself as a \"community conservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smf.co.uk/tom-tugendhat-speech-2018/|title=Tom Tugendhat MP's speech for the SMF|date=2018-11-08|website=Social Market Foundation|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> [[File:Soldiers cross a foot bridge in the Mirabad Valley.jpg|thumb|A footbridge in the Mirabad Valley, in [[Urozgan Province]], built by [[Australian Defence Force|ADF]] engineers, being patrolled by a member of the [[Afghan National Army]], followed by an Australian soldier from the [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force]] in February 2010. ]] His outlook, unsurprisingly, has been shaped by his experience of war:<blockquote>I take my time in Afghanistan, especially in my first deployment, particularly my time with [[Mentoring Task Force One|MRTF2]] with the [[1st Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|1RAR]] battle group, as being very formative for me, doing [[Nation Building - Afghanistan|Nation Building]] and realising the limitations of government to change people and their culture. We built bridges, we built a bazaar where we expected people to trade, we built schools and hospitals, we built all sorts of things, but fundamentally, we didn\u2019t change the way the Afghan people lived. Respecting people\u2019s sovereignty, and people\u2019s freedom to live as they choose is something that I learned over there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref></blockquote>[[File:Hastie giving crayons to children op takht.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Hastie distributing crayons to Afghan children in Oruzghan]]This experience seems to have made Hastie sceptical of [[Neoliberalism]], saying, \"I am now far more circumspect about the ability of military power to change people and societies, and far more aware of how resilient culture can be.\"<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\" /> By the same measure, Hastie is diffident towards [[Neoconservatism]], especially in its [[Laissez-faire]] tendencies, which he finds unacceptable because, \"despite the benefits of globalisation, there are always losers in the transfer of labour and capital offshore. Loss of identity through vocational irrelevance is a real anxiety in communities that prize skilled labour.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political Class Ignored the People and Paid the Price|date=November 23, 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hastie's high view of  sovereignty and his desire to protect local people and their industries from global forces<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/26/andrew-hasties-contribution-to-our-china-effort-curious-and-curiouser|title=Andrew Hastie's contribution to our China effort? Curious and curiouser {{!}} Katharine Murphy|last=Murphy|first=Katharine|date=2018-05-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> would places him in the tradition of [[National liberalism]]. Recently Ben Pronk and Tim Curtis (both former SAS officers, Pronk had been Hastie's commanding officer) asked Hastie for his vision for Australia. His off the cuff answer was: <blockquote>I hope to see a country where families are strong. Where we've incentivised families through the policies that we've legislated. I hope to see a strong defence force so that we can weather the challenges that will inevitably come. If you take history as a guide we will face inevitable security challenges. I hope that we are aware of our history, that we haven't cut the mooring that is our civilisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref></blockquote>This statement contains three threads that are seen in almost all of Hastie's writing and remarks. First, a passion \"to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greg|first=Brown|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/rivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy/news-story/455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811|title=Rivals unite for the sake of democracy|date=July 13, 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. Second, a believe that \"Sovereignty, where compromised, must be recovered and protected.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Third, that community or local institutions \"should define the character and activity of our nation from the ground up.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0200;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0049%22|title=ParlInfo - ADJOURNMENT : 45th Parliament|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Democracy ===\nOne [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] profile on Hastie found that \"the heart of his worldview is the belief that everyone is equal and has dignity\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382?pfmredir=sm&sf75079731=1&smid=Page:+ABC+News-Facebook_Organic&WT.tsrc=Facebook_Organic|title=Keeping the faith: Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and from here his convictions about democracy emanate. The belief in the inherent value of the individual means the individual must be free when it comes to \"thought, worship, speech, association and choice\" as Hastie said in his first speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Parliament of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> These freedoms allow our communities to naturally form and \"are the fullest expression of self-government.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie recently collaborated with the [[Australian Labor Party]]'s [[Kimberley Kitching]] to form the \"Parliamentary Friends of Democracy.\" It comes out of a concern that democratic institutions are \"under increasing pressure around the globe.\" They believe, \"Australian parliamentarians have a duty to rise above party to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms that make Australia a special place to live.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Frivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy%2Fnews-story%2F455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e77fa5e4fbb81da52eba770ee8c0a8a7-1576685699|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> This view expands on concerns that Hastie has expressed elsewhere, that \"our greatest vulnerability lies not in our infrastructure, but in our thinking. That intellectual failure makes us institutionally weak. If we don't understand the challenge ahead for our civil society, in our parliaments, in our universities, in our private enterprises, in our charities \u2014 our little platoons \u2014 then choices will be made for us. Our sovereignty, our freedoms, will be diminished.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Embassy condemns MP Hastie for comparing China's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last=Laschon|first=political reporter Eliza|date=2019-08-08|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In February 2020 it was announced that Hastie had been invited to serve on a panel of western leaders who are concerned for the state of global democracy, the Commission on Advancing a Free World, in association with [[Atlantic Council|The Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/news/press-releases/free-world-commission-of-legislators-from-leading-democracies-launched-at-munich-security-conference/|title=Free World Commission of legislators from leading democracies launched at Munich Security Conference|date=2020-02-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Their ''Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/declaration/|title=Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> articulates seven statements for protecting democracy across the world, beginning with \"the right of all people to live in free and just societies, where fundamental rights are protected under the rule of law.\"\n\n==== Freedom of thought - on marriage ====\nHastie saw the 2016 [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage debate in Australia]] as a conscience issue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/marriage-is-peoples-institution-so-they-should-decide-its-future/news-story/a6ace55c388f0f5e3c7484f8738aefe6|title=Marriage is people's institution, so they should decide its future|date=September 20, 2016|work=|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  He supported the postal survey because he believed that the institution of marriage, since it existed before the parliament, was an institution that \"belongs to the people\" so it was right for the people themselves to vote on it.<ref name=\":4\" /> When the \"yes vote\" was strongly returned, Hastie ensured passage of the bill, but could not vote for it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-11-15/wa-politicians-to-ignore-same-sex-marriage-result/9154656|title=Prominent No campaigner to abstain from same-sex marriage vote|date=2017-11-15|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He explained, \"We went to the election with it, I was on television saying I would abstain, I've been in dialogue with constituents for the last 18 months and whenever I've talked to them about the issue, I've said I would abstain. My intention is to abstain because to vote yes would go against my conscience, but I want to uphold both the vote in Canning and the national result and abstention is the best way to do that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/5058727/hastie-to-abstain-on-yes-vote/|title=Hastie to abstain on 'yes' vote|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2017-11-15|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Most of Hastie's statements through the public debate centred not on marriage, but on how to have the debate. When right wing commentators such as Larry Pickering used homophobic language towards [[LGBT]] persons, Hastie immediately condemned the statement, expressing his \"dismay\" at the degrading language, and pleaded for \"higher personal and civic standards\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/pickering-comments-despicable-hastie|title=Pickering comments despicable: Hastie|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of conscience - on military abuses ====\nRecent reports by Chris Masters and others of prisoner abuse, and even killings, by the Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] in Afghanistan have seen Hastie come forward as a strong advocate for transparency, though it may hurt the prestige of his former unit. He has \"emerged as a champion of the Brereton Inquiry.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/he-thought-i-was-going-to-shoot-him-how-david-s-little-voice-saved-him-in-war-20190913-p52qy6.html|title='He thought I was going to shoot him': How David's 'little voice' saved him in war|last=Masters|first=Nick McKenzie, Chris|date=2019-09-20|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> He strongly supports whistleblowers when it comes to abuse, telling ABC Radio the truth tellers should be respected: \"I don't want to go into any specific allegations, but they should be taken seriously and, as I said, we want a free media reporting on all issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/secretive-and-elite-sas-soldiers-grilled-about-alleged-war-crimes-20180608-p4zkau.html|title=Secretive and elite SAS soldiers grilled about alleged war crimes|last=Wroe|first=Nick McKenzie, David|date=2018-06-08|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of expression ====\nIn one of Hastie's first electoral campaigns, he had a large outdoor poster vandalised. Rather than condemn the culprit, he wrote a Facebook message, \"Will Mandurah's Van Gogh please come forward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/3985723/hasties-spray-mp-responds-to-graffiti-attack/|title=Hastie's spray: MP responds to graffiti attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2016-06-22|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> then had a local graffiti artist add even more colour to the piece. However, when a campaign bus was torched, Hastie drew a firm line, calling them, \"cowards using Taliban tactics in the dead of night\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/federal-election-2019/andrew-hastie-s-campaign-bus-survives-dead-of-night-arson-attack-20190420-p51fr4.html|title=Andrew Hastie's campaign bus survives 'dead of night' arson attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2019-04-19|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie encourages debate and dissension, especially in classroom settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4488661/students-get-political-during-hastie-visit/|title=Students get political during Hastie visit|last=Cockerill|first=Jess|date=2017-02-23|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of press ====\nHastie is currently having difficulty balancing freedoms when it comes to the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/today/paddy-manning/2019/23/2019/1563861108/joint-pain|title=Joint pain|last=paddym@schwartzmedia.com.au1516749970|date=2019-07-23|website=The Monthly|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He has actively stood up for journalists at the ABC and [[Sydney morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]], using Parliamentary privilege to name Chau Chak Wing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> as a man who co-conspired to bribe a UN official, a man who took the media outlets to court for defamation as they had published the accusations. Hastie explained his actions by saying \"...democracy works only if we have a free press that can publish information that serves the public interest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> However, current laws have allowed for the Australian Federal Police to raid journalists from the ABC and News Corp Australia for reasons of security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-15/abc-raids-australian-federal-police-press-freedom/11309810|title=AFP wanted fingerprints of journalists behind ABC special forces investigation|last=Lyons|first=the ABC's head of investigative journalism John|date=2019-07-15|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> This places a tension between freedom and sovereignty.\n\n==== Freedom of religion ====\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Huyghur delegates and Sen James Paterson 30 November 2019 photographed by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Delegates from Australia's Uyghur community, Sadam and Almas, meeting with Andrew Hastie MP (on left) and Senator James Paterson (right) at Parliament House, Canberra, in November 2019.]]\nWhile an observant Christian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Hastie holds to the view that if the law allows him to practice his faith, it must allow all to express their faith, or lack of it. That means, in Australia, that while he personally finds the burka \"repugnant\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> as it \"defaces the personhood of women\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> he would be very reluctant to have the state controlling it, as it's an expression of religious belief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie advocates strongly for freedom of religion as a basic human right across the globe, including the right of [[Uyghurs]] to practice their faith in China's Xingjian Province, saying \"it's our duty to stand up for them, and argue the point, and ask for their freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=2019-11-17|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> After [[The New York Times]] published the [[Xinjiang papers]] Hastie expressed deep empathy for those with personal ties to Uighurs facing \"systemic persecution and internment\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/liberal-mp-and-outspoken-china-critic-vows-uighur-loved-ones-will-not-be-forgotten|title=Liberal MP and outspoken China critic vows Uighur \u2018loved ones\u2019 will not be forgotten|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  The documents showed how China views their the muslim people of that region as being \"infected, as they say, with unhealthy thoughts\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=2019-11-17|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> forcing millions into the communist government's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|Xinjiang re-education program]]. Hastie urged Uyghur people in Australia, and in China, not to give up hope.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n\n=== Sovereignty ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Mayor Rhys Williams at March 2020 Citizenship Ceremony in Mandurah photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|The Mayor of Mandurah, Rhys Williams, with Andrew Hastie MP, hosting an Australian Citizenship ceremony in March 2020]]\nHastie argues that Australia's representatives must be the ones making decisions that affect Australia's future, and so \"upholding our political system is the first thing that we must do because that at least preserves our political leadership and their ability to make decisions, un-influence by greater powers.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> As such he strongly resists foreign influence on the working of the Australian economy, culture or political system. \"My bottom line is Australian sovereignty \u2013 I want to protect our way of life, our freedom of action and our political institutions. That's my job as a member of the Commonwealth Parliament. I make no apologies for it.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|date=2019-12-06|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic sovereignty ====\nInterestingly, Hastie locates the energy debates as sovereignty issue, and in 2018 said, \"I have a problem legislating the Paris target because it undermines Australia's 'economic sovereignty'\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelly|first=Joe|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/andrew-hastie-confirms-we-cannot-support-neg-in-current-form/news-story/48af53948ad288198550fdb68617f947|title=Andrew Hastie confirms he cannot support NEG in current form|date=August 16, 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which meant he could not support the [[National Energy Guarantee]]. The next month he made a speech in the Federation Chamber, saying, \"Australian industry and Australian workers must come first. When it comes to energy, we must put the Australian people before Paris.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0350;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0329%22|title=ParlInfo - Federation Chamber : PRIVATE MEMBERS' BUSINESS : Alcoa|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==== Sovereignty and political warfare ====\nThis has been the main legislative focus for Hastie in recent times. In an interview with the Israeli newspaper ''Haaretz'', Hastie explained that, \"Democratic countries must take domestic measures to protect against these threats. Australia has led the way in this regard. Authoritarian states use all instruments of state power to pursue their strategic objectives. Seemingly innocent activities like diplomacy, foreign-investment flows into strategic industries and infrastructure acquisitions like the purchase of ports are not so innocuous. Democracies who don't pay attention to these activities \u2013 and take measures to guard against them \u2013 risk becoming tethered to hyper-modern authoritarian states and losing their sovereignty in the process.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/>\n\n==== Digital sovereignty ====\nHastie frames questions to do with the provision of information networks as a matter of sovereignty, which must be defended. Given that companies such as Huawei would be legally required to pass on information carried on their networks to the Chinese government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/05/huawei-would-have-to-give-data-to-china-government-if-asked-experts.html|title=Huawei says it would never hand data to China's government. Experts say it wouldn't have a choice|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=2019-03-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> Hastie was a strong supporter of the Turnbull Government's decision to prevent that company from providing 5G services in Australia. Along with other parliamentarians from the Liberal Party, including [[Tim Wilson (Australian politician)|Tim Wilson]] and [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] and [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Kimberley Kitching]] and [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]], he has been active in applying pressure to Australia's partners in the [[Five Eyes]] security alliance to do the same. In a public statement he explained how important that security arrangement is, \"In a time of growing strategic uncertainty, Australia values that membership more than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/four-australian-mps-urge-britain-to-ban-huawei-20200124-p53u9x.html|title=Four Australian MPs urge Britain to ban Huawei|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=2020-01-23|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> In private settings, it is known that he has supported Byrne, the Deputy Chair of the committee Hastie leads, who used forceful language with the UK leadership, asking \u201cHow would you feel if the Russians laid down infrastructure in your own networks? That\u2019s how we feel about Huawei.\u201d Hastie is quoted as supporting frank conversation about data sovereignty with western allies, saying \"We save our toughest talk for our closest mates. I back my deputy chair.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Lucy Fisher, Defence Editor {{!}} Caroline Wheeler, The Sunday|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huawei-decision-may-threaten-trade-deal-with-us-says-mike-pence-vlg9d6ggs|title=Mike Pence and Tory MPs attack Boris Johnson over Huawei decision|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==== Enemies, allies and sovereignty ====\nIn May 2018, Hastie took the \"dramatic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/andrew-hastie-senate-estimates/9797718|title=ASIO boss says Hastie's allegations have had no impact on intelligence allies|last=Gribbin|first=political reporter Caitlyn|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> step of using parliamentary privilege to name a Chinese-Australian property developer as being a corrupt person acting in the interests of a foreign power, saying, \"It is now my duty to inform the House and the Australian people that CC-3 is Chau Chak Wing, the same man who co-conspired to bribe the president of the United Nations General Assembly, John Ashe, the same man with extensive contacts in the Chinese Communist Party, including the United Front.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=2018-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The information had been given to the MP during meetings in the United States earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=2018-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The move was criticised as \"causing trouble\" both to the government to Australia's relationship with China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Hastie himself believed he was compelled to speak as, \"My duty, first and foremost, is to the Australian people and the preservation of the ideals and democratic traditions of our Commonwealth.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/why-andrew-hastie-australias-uberpatriot-mp-risked-chinas-wrath-20180524-h10ie6|title=Why Andrew Hastie, Australia's uber-patriot MP, risked China's wrath|date=2018-05-24|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n[[File:AH and Gen Mattis.jpg|thumb|Hastie with General Jim Mattis outside the Pentagon on 4 May 2018]]\nWhile the incident gave another example of the parliamentarian's determination to protect Australian institutions from the influence of the Chinese Communist Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/political-donor-chau-chak-wing-behind-un-bribe-scandal-parliament-told-20180522-p4zgs5.html|title=Political donor Chau Chak Wing behind UN bribe scandal, Parliament told|last=Baker|first=Nick McKenzie, Richard|date=2018-05-22|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> his acting in consort with American defence forces and intelligence agencies such as the Department of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karp|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/24/andrew-hasties-use-of-us-intelligence-over-bribery-allegation-a-concern-dreyfus-says|title=Andrew Hastie's use of US intelligence over bribery allegation 'a concern', Dreyfus says|date=2018-05-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> also provided more proof of his commitment to the [[U.S.-Australia alliance]]. At the high level, Hastie believes that this alliance is essential to Australia maintaining its sovereignty saying, \u201cNational leaders must affirm and articulate the values that define Western democracies, especially as we seek to build a coalition of like-minded partners to resist authoritarian political warfare.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> He led a parliamentary delegation to the United States in early 2017 and afterwards indicated that, for him, the defence alliance holds personal importance<blockquote>\u201cWhen we met with House and Senate leaders, and members of the [US] House Intelligence Committee, those committee members really emphasised the importance of the relationship... I was sitting there in front of the Senate Intelligence and Security Committee and the committee minority leader is a senator from Virginia and I said to him, \u2018I wouldn't be sitting here if it wasn\u2019t for a medic from Virginia who saved my grandfather\u2019s life on the 31st of March 1945\u2019.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4466943/hastie-promoted-to-key-national-security-role/|title=Hastie promoted to key national security role|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2017-02-14|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Community ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP Age Care Community Visit.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie MP visiting Amana Living Meadow Springs Village, an Anglican age care community in Mandurah.]]Hastie's experiences in Afghanistan, especially in seeing how limited the military is in reshaping people's lives, seems to have given him an even higher view of community, culture and local institutions. In an interview about his wartime experiences, he said:<blockquote> For me, it proved that culture and geography (are) decisive in the formation of societies and political institutions. Building lasting, trusted institutions takes time, generations of stewardship and public virtue.<ref name=\"Whinnett\"/></blockquote>\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with son Jonathan at the 2018 ANZAC Day March in Mandurah WA taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|His son Jonathan holding his hand, Andrew Hastie marches with veterans on [[Anzac Day]] in Mandurah. ]]\n\n Looking at Australia, Hastie believes that it is local institutions that provide civic foundations of \"accountability, freedom and democracy.\"<ref name=\"First Speech\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> He argued in his first speech that the first of these institutions is the family, which \"is central to a healthy society\"<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> but also extends to sporting clubs, service clubs, churches and local businesses.<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> In one op-ed, Hastie went even further, suggesting that community groups, or \"pre-political institutions\" are finally more important than governments:<blockquote> \"More powerful than the political levers of government are grassroots volunteer movements and pre-political institutions... Pre-political institutions are the best place for securing our freedoms and so we should take encouragement that democratic governments cannot control them, and are sent packing when they attempt to do so.\"<ref name=\"theaustralian.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political class ignored the people and paid the price|date=November 23, 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== The power of community and PTSD ====\nHastie reflected on how his grandfather recovered from the trauma of [[World War II]] thanks, in part to the power of community, and laments that we may not have that power available to us now, \"Just thinking of my grandfather's own experience, he was shot up quite badly in the second world war where civil society was still very strong, community was still very strong, a lot of local clubs and organisations, I think he struggled with [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] but I think his PTSD was mitigated by those little platoons that we talk about, he was very close to his comrades from the second war, and I'm just not sure if we have in today's society that same sort of cushioning and community support as we had 70 years ago.\"<ref name=\"Grattan\"/>\n\n==== Community and environment ====\nWhile environmental concern is often seen as a progressive cause, Hastie sets the environment between two concerns - that, as per the [[Edmund Burke|Burkean]] contract - the good things inherited should be passed on to the next generation. And that the environment serves the community, which means they need to make the decisions about it. In a recent controversy about a proposed dredging of an estuary, Hastie said: <blockquote>\"I believe in the sovereignty of local communities to make decisions about how they conserve and develop their environment. The Bindjareb people, the First Australians in my constituency, have long been custodians of the waterways\u2014for many generations back to the present. The Murray Mandurah community also shares this responsibility, and together we are all stewards of the beautiful Peel-Harvey Estuary, a body of water larger than Sydney Harbour, teeming with marine life and brimming with natural beauty. We, therefore, through our local governments, have sovereignty over this natural asset and should have a say about how development takes place. We're not antiprogress, but we are rightly cautious about development, as we are the ones most affected by it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2019-09-11.151.1&s=speaker:10843#g151.2|title=Peel-Harvey Estuary: 11 Sep 2019: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AH with family (KN).jpg|thumb|Ruth and Andrew Hastie with their children in Mandurah, October 2018]]\nHastie met his wife Ruth in the summer of 2007 while he was studying at [[George Washington University]]. Hastie proposed to Ruth on the steps of the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The two were married in 2008 at [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]]. Their children were born in Perth in June 2015 and August 2017. The family of four now lives in the [[City of Mandurah]] in the [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] region of [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For God and country|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/sas-commander-liberal-party-rising-star-how-far-can-andrew-hastie-go/news-story/327a82373c4e90755402c1388506a502|accessdate=18 April 2018|agency=The Australian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Andrew|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/about_andrew|website=www.andrewhastie.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe credits his family for giving him a love for reading, especially \"biographies, Shakespeare, psalms\"<ref name=\"Development\"/> along with history. Favourite historians include [[Geoffrey Blainey]], [[H. W. Brands]], [[Niall Ferguson]], [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] and [[Ronald C. White]]. He also enjoys 20th century novelists such as [[Graham Greene]], [[Cormac McCarthy]] and [[P. G. Wodehouse]].\n\nFellow parliamentarians recognise Hastie as \u201ca man of deep faith\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2018-10-24.163.2&s=speaker:10843#g180.1|title=National Apology to Victims and...: 24 Oct 2018: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> which he shares with his parents and siblings. Whilst he is frequently ridiculed as being \u201cfundamentalist\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/mungo-maccallum/2018/28/2018/1527472468/hastie-judgement|title=Hastie judgement|last=kateg@themonthly.com.au1515708219|date=2018-05-28|website=The Monthly|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> he has been active across several reformed, evangelical and Protestant church communities with historic understandings of the Christian faith, including [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]] in Washington DC, Shenton Park [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican Church]] in the North of Perth<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/03/canning-byelection-andrew-hastie-deems-questions-on-family-and-religion-unacceptable|title=Canning byelection: Andrew Hastie deems questions on family and religion 'unacceptable'|date=2015-09-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and Crossroads Church in Canberra (an independent Evangelical Church) Hastie actually identifies with the Scottish Presbyterian faith in which he was raised<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> and his family church in Mandurah today is part of the [[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]. Having rejected Christian belief in his teens for several years, Hastie has spoken of how only a theistic understanding of the world makes any sense of the death and suffering he has personally witnessed, that if he were \"a closed universe atheist, how bleak and senseless those deaths would be\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Greg|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/inquirer/politicians-reveal-what-religion-means-to-them/news-story/ad54c5d1948393ae00cf20b9445372d1|title=In defence of Christianity|date=July 23, 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><br />\n\n==Honours and awards==\n<center>\n\n[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|100px]]\n\n[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|100px]]\n\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the AASM]] || [[Australian Active Service Medal]] || with clasp for [[Australian Active Service Medal#ICAT|ICAT]]\n|-\n|[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Afghanistan Medal for Australia]] || [[Afghanistan Medal (Australia)|Afghanistan Medal]] || Operation SLIPPER\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Australian Service Medal]] || [[Australian Service Medal]] || with clasp for CT/SR (Counter Terrorism / Special Recovery)<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://defence-honours-tribunal.gov.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SASR-Final-Report-Public-Release.pdf|title = INQUIRY INTO RECOGNITION OF AUSTRALIAN DEFENCE FORCE SERVICE FOR SPECIAL AIR SERVICE COUNTER TERRORIST AND SPECIAL RECOVERY DUTIES|date = 22 December 2009|accessdate = 20 September 2015|website = Defence Honours Tribunal|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the ADM]] || [[Australian Defence Medal]] ||\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|50px]] || [[NATO Medal#Non-Article 5 Medal|NATO Medal for the Non-Article 5 ISAF Operation in Afghanistan]] || with clasp ''ISAF''\n|-\n|[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|50px|Meritorious Unit Citation]] || [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] with [[Federation Star]] || Awarded to Task Force 66 in the [[2015 Australia Day Honours]]\n|-\n||| [[Infantry Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n||| [[Army Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805 Parliamentary biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Don Randall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Division of Canning|Canning]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Western Australia Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hastie, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Australian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian monarchists]]\n[[Category:Elliott School of International Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Canning]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Scots College]]\n[[Category:People from Wangaratta]]\n[[Category:Royal Military College, Duntroon graduates]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015 }}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = Andrew Hastie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n| image            = Andrew Hastie Orignal.jpg\n| caption          = Hastie in 2018\n| constituency_MP  = [[Division of Canning|Canning]]\n| parliament       = Australian\n| majority         = \n| predecessor      = [[Don Randall]]\n| successor        = \n| term_start       = 19 September 2015\n| term_end         = \n| office1          = Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]]\n| deputy1          = [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]]\n| term_start1      = 15 February 2017\n| term_end1        = \n| predecessor1     = [[Michael Sukkar]]\n| successor1       = \n| birthname        = Andrew William Hastie\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|9|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Wangaratta, Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Ruth Hastie\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Australia]]\n| relations        = \n| children         = 2\n| residence        = [[Mandurah, Western Australia]]\n| alma_mater       = [[University of New South Wales|UNSW]], [[Australian Defence Force Academy|ADFA]], [[Royal Military College, Duntroon|Duntroon]], [[George Washington University|GWU]]\n| occupation       = \n| profession       = [[Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n| signature        = \n| website          = {{url|www.andrewhastie.com.au}}\n| footnotes        = \n| allegiance       = Australia\n| branch           = [[Australian Army]]\n| serviceyears     = 2001\u20132015\n| rank             = [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]\n| unit             = [[2nd Cavalry Regiment (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]] (2007\u20132009)<br />[[Special Air Service Regiment]] (2010\u20132015)\n| battles          = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br/>[[Military intervention against ISIL]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrew William Hastie''' (born 30 September 1982) is an Australian politician who serves as Chair of the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] and as the Federal MP for [[Division of Canning|Canning]], [[Western Australia|WA]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]]. He was first elected in the [[2015 Canning by-election]] and re-elected in 2016 and 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|website=www.aph.gov.au|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> A controversial figure, his public statements for Australia to \"preserve our sovereignty\"<ref name=\"Hastie\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> in defiance of an \"expansionist\"<ref name=\"Grattan\">{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/politics-with-michelle-grattan-andrew-hastie-on-foreign-influence-security-and-veteran-mental-health-128545|title=Politics with Michelle Grattan: Andrew Hastie on foreign influence, security and veteran mental health|last=Grattan|first=Michelle|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> [[Communist Party of China]] have been condemned as \"totally intemperate\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ferguson|first=Richard|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/kerry-stokes-says-andrew-hastie-did-more-harm-than-good-with-china-remarks/news-story/bc218d8b7cbffd3f1cc3ec6cb6db8ee8|title=Kerry Stokes says Andrew Hastie did more harm than good with China remarks|date=9 February 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"inflammatory\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/politics/western-australia/wa-premier-slams-andrew-hastie-s-china-concerns-as-extreme-and-inflammatory-20190808-p52f7m.html|title=WA Premier slams Andrew Hastie's China concerns as 'extreme and inflammatory'|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2019-08-08|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref> by Australian corporate leaders, then praised as a matter of \"strong public interest\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/pm/strong-public-interest-in-chinese-influence-claims/9792976|title=\"Strong public interest\" in Chinese influence claims|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC Radio|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and \"necessary, and important\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2019/08/17/how-the-china-question-split-australian-politics/15659640008614|title=How the China question split Australian politics|last=Seccombe|first=Mike|date=2019-08-17|website=The Saturday Paper|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> by security analysts [[Clive Hamilton|Professor Clive Hamilton]] and Professor Rory Medcalf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/in-defence-of-andrew-hastie-20190811-p52fyw|title=In defence of Andrew Hastie|date=2019-08-11|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> His stance led to the [[Government of China]] refusing him and his colleague [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] from visiting China on a study tour, demanding that they \"repent\" from their views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/outspoken-liberal-politicians-must-repent-and-redress-says-china|title='Outspoken' Liberal politicians must 'repent and redress', says China|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nHastie's mother Sue was a primary school teacher, particularly to children with special needs. [[File:Andrew Hastie with his father Peter Hastie back yard Wangaratta Victoria circa 1983.jpg|alt=Andrew Hastie, age 1, with his father Peter, around 1983|thumb|Andrew Hastie with his father Peter, in the backyard of their home in Wangaratta, Victoria, circa 1983]] Her mother Rose \u2014 to whom, Hastie says in his first speech, he was \"very close\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Australian Parliament House|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\u2014 was a nurse throughout her life, caring for Hastie's grandfather, Reginald a war veteran, through to his death.\n\nSimilarly, his paternal grandfather served as an officer with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and was severely wounded by gunfire when covering the air-sea rescue of two downed Australian airmen during the [[Pacific War]] for which he was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|title=First Speech|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|website=www.andrewhastie.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> His son (Hastie's father) Peter has served as a pastor in church communities, early on in rural [[Wangaratta]], Victoria; and later in the inner urban suburb of [[Ashfield, New South Wales|Ashfield,]] where he launched a Mandarin speaking congregation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nWhen the family moved to the inner west of Sydney, Hastie began his primary education at Ashbury Public School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=May 4, 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> From year 5 he attended [[The Scots College]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2015|title=Old Boy News|url=https://www.tsc.nsw.edu.au/hubfs/Lion_and_Lang_Syne_Summer_2015.pdf|journal=The Lion & Lang Syne|volume=26|pages=49|via=}}</ref> in [[Sydney]], completing his [[Higher School Certificate (New South Wales)|Higher School Certificate]] in 2000. Intending to become a journalist, Hastie began a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in History, Politics and Philosophy at the Kensington Campus of [[University of New South Wales]] in 2001, and also joined the [[University of New South Wales Regiment]] as a part-time reservist. At a tutorial near the end of first year, following [[September 11 attacks|September 11 terror attacks]] Hastie says he listened to other students argue that the [[United States]] had \u201cdeserved\u201d the attack, which he says he found \u201cbizarre\",<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/australia/war-has-its-limits-hastie-tells-mps-ng-ya-130555|title=War has its limits, new MP Andrew Hastie tells Parliament|date=2015-10-14|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> the event would \"shape the next decade of my life.\"<ref name=\"Hastie\"/><blockquote>I was planning on being a foreign correspondent. 9/11 happened and the daughter of my year 2/3 teacher at Ashbury Public School, she died in one of the towers, I think she was 90 floors up. And so that event, apart from the obvious impact it had on Australia, it came very close to me and my life and I had a tradition of service in my family and thought, you know what, this is a big, historical shift, I want to be part of this.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=unforgiving60|website=unforgiving60|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Hastie with book.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Andrew Hastie at the rear of his ASLAV Type 1, holding a copy of ''Empire'' by Scottish historian [[Niall Ferguson]].]]\nHastie decided to join the [[Australian Army]] full-time, but completed his second year at the Kensington Campus in 2002 before transferring to the [[University of New South Wales]] at [[Australian Defence Force Academy]] in Canberra in 2003. He completed his bachelor's degree in 2004 before being invited to do an honours year in 2005, his final thesis examined [[Charles Bean]]'s official history of the [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]]. Hastie still regards himself as a student of history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourlocalexaminer.com.au/andrew-hastie-maiden-speech/|title=Hastie sworn in, vows to put Canning people first|last=Hastie|first=Hamish|date=2015-10-14|website=Your Local Examiner|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and recently wrote the forward to ''Destined for War''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.scribd.com/book/350699416/Destined-for-War-can-America-and-China-escape-Thucydides-Trap|title=Destined for War by Graham Allison and Andrew Hastie - Book - Read Online|language=en}}</ref> an historical survey of global conflicts, beginning with the [[Peloponnesian War]] by [[Graham T. Allison]].\n\nHastie went on to officer training at [[Royal Military College, Duntroon]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805|title=Mr Andrew Hastie MP|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In 2007, Hastie completed the [[George Washington University]] [[Elliott School of International Affairs]]'s U.S. Foreign Policy Summer Program in [[Washington, D.C.]]\n\n==Military service (2001\u20132015)==\nHastie initially intended to serve purely in the [[Australian Army Reserve]], participating in their officer training in 2001 and 2002 with the University of New South Wales Regiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=September 11 Australian Stories|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426162732/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2011/09/08/september-11-australian-stories|website=www.sbs.com.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> The events of [[9/11]] prompted him towards full-time army service beginning 2003. Having graduated from ADFA and Duntroon, he received his commission as a Lieutenant at the end of 2006 and began his chosen career in Royal Australian Armoured Corps in 2007. He first served in [[2nd Armoured Division (Australia)|2nd Cavalry Regiment]], beginning his command of a cavalry troop in 2008. The regiment is the second most senior regiment in the [[Royal Australian Armoured Corps]], which was attached to the 1st Brigade, based in Darwin, Northern Territory.<ref>{{cite web|title=2nd Cavalry Regiment|url=https://www.army.gov.au/our-people/units/forces-command/1st-brigade/2nd-cavalry-regiment|website=www.army.gov.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan, 2009-2010 ===\n[[File:Charmestan valley afghanistan.jpg|thumb|MRTF-2 Commanding Officer's Tactical Party, on the edge of the Charmestan Valley, Urozgan Province, Afghanistan.]]\n[[File:Hastie overlooking Chora Valley.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie overlooking the Chora Valley from his Type I ASLAV.]]\n\n Hastie first deployed to Afghanistan with the Mentoring and Reconstruction Task Force Two, a 750-strong Australian combined arms battle group. He commanded a troop of [[ASLAV|Australian Light Armoured Vehicle]]s on patrols in [[Uruzgan province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf |publisher=The Australian Army |title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009 |date=1 July 2010 |accessdate=2 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923174042/http://www.army.gov.au/Our-future/Publications/Australian-Army-Journal/Past-editions/~/media/Files/Our%20future/LWSC%20Publications/AAJ/2011Winter/02-CounterinsurgencyInUruz.pdf |archivedate=23 September 2015 }}</ref> Operations began at the very start of the fighting season in May 2009, concluding in February 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nautilus.org/publications/books/australian-forces-abroad/afghanistan/mentoring-task-force/|title=Mentoring Task Force|date=2011-12-19|website=Nautilus Institute for Security and Sustainability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> aiming \u201cto dominate the threat\u201d using \u201cclose combat to destroy the enemy with precision.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Counterinsurgency in Uruzgan 2009|last=Connolly|first=Peter|publisher=Land Warfare Studies Centre|year=2011|isbn=|location=Canberra|pages=}}</ref> For Hastie, the wider goal of Western forces was an attempt to reshape Afghanistan: <blockquote>Our job pretty much was the stick. The carrot was the mentoring piece, the aid that was delivered through DFAT, also there at the time and other NGOs. And we were the stick that kept the bad guys back.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=12 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>The responsibilities of Hastie's own troop were convoy escort and force overwatch - for which it was attacked by the enemy intermittently, mostly by [[improvised explosive device]]s. In interview, he explained, \"We had four strikes in my troop alone.\u201d<ref name=\"Development\">{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Special Air Service Regiment, 2010-2012 ===\n[[File:Insigne du Special Air Service Regiment (SASR).svg|thumb|Insignia of the Special Air Service Regiment (SASR)]]Hastie successfully applied for entry to the [[Special Air Service Regiment]]\u00a0Selection Course (known simply as \"Selection\"). The process is designed to identify soldiers with diverse backgrounds and strong character as they are able to \u201cgenerate unconventional answers to strategic and tactical problems\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cios.org/EJCPUBLIC/010/1/01013.html|title=Article from ejc/rec|website=www.cios.org|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> as needed for a Tier 1 [[Special forces]] unit. His cohort featured in the SBS documentary ''The Search for Warriors''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/video/11757123841/SAS-The-Search-For-Warriors-S1-Ep1|title=SAS - The Search For Warriors S1 Ep1|website=SBS PopAsia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> where Hastie has been identified as candidate 10. With the other candidates, Hastie was subjected to extreme exercises, a deliberate system in which, according to the Lieutenant Colonel who had oversight of Hastie's Selection, \u201cwe will break an individual down.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackfootstudios.com/forums/index.php?/forums/topic/5012-australian-sas-selection-documentary/|title=Australian SAS Selection Documentary|website=BlackFoot Studios|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Exercises included \u201cLucky Dip\u201d, five days working with teams to move heavy equipment by hand through the bush, with only one meal in that time; and a 150&nbsp;km five-day solo trek across mountainous terrain, which Hastie recalled in interview:<blockquote>\u201cI remember on Selection being up on one of the mountains in the Stirling ranges, being asked, \u201cWhy do you want to be here?\u201d I said, \u201cBecause last time I was in Afghanistan I was driving around getting blown up and I actually want to go after these guys.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=3 May 2019|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> </blockquote>Hastie's Selection experience concluded with a three-day extreme interrogation session, involving constant sleep deprivation and starvation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/documentary-reveals-gruelling-sas-selection-process/news-story/4488a528d9e0bffd2bc98c43cc2a9350|title=SAS: We will break an individual down|date=2010-12-06|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>  Men in the group lost between 10 and 15 kilograms from exertion and malnutrition. From Hastie's initial cohort of 131, only 26 completed the course.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/national/2015/08/21/can-pass-sas-test/|title=The most gruelling tests of the SAS|date=2015-08-21|website=The New Daily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> From there Hastie commenced the 18-month Reinforcement Cycle before receiving qualification with the Regiment, based at [[Campbell Barracks]]. He was given his \u201csandy beret\u201d in May 2012 and was assigned to 1 SAS Squadron. His first overseas deployment was in Port Moresby to support the [[Papua New Guinea Defence Force]] as they provide security and stability for the General Election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2012/s3523650.htm|title=Australia provides help for PNG elections|date=2012-06-12|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Commanding special forces troop in Afghanistan, 2013  ===\nIn January 2013, Hastie returned to Afghanistan as an SASR officer with Special Operations Task Group Rotation XIX. Hastie led his troop in operations against hostile [[Taliban]] leadership in southern Afghanistan, commanding B Troop. The wider mission was to provide force protection as the ADF mentored the nascent [[Afghan National Security Force]]. Hastie directed counter-leadership operations:<blockquote>This meant targeting and taking out the Taliban leadership, helping to support the building of institutions such as schools, and trying to carve out some space for the new Afghan Government to govern.<ref name=\"Whinnett\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>At points, operations were also protective. Hastie and his troops were a part the successful removal of enemy combatants who fired rockets at the Allied base and prevented a truck bomb from coming through the front gates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The Untold Story of SAS mission|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref> As part of Task Force 66 (Special Operations Task Groups IV-XX) Hastie's unit was awarded a [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] for \"outstanding service on operations against an unrelenting, cunning and ruthless enemy, in an unforgiving environment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/australia-day-honours-list-2015|title=Australia Day honours list 2015|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Deaths of Toor Jan and Odood ====\nIn February 2013, Hastie led a team of men to support a remote outpost of Afghan National Police. While there, he received communication intercepts indicating two Taliban fighters, seen at a distance of 1,200 metres, were planning a rocket attack on the post.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/special-features/in-depth/the-untold-story-of-andrew-hasties-tragic-sas-mission-in-afghanistan/news-story/4711aefcf3e78930daa27b9030d9617c|title=The untold story of Andrew Hastie's tragic SAS mission in Afghanistan|date=December 9, 2016|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Hastie had authority to neutralise the threat, communicated the coordinates for the combatants and called in a strike by a US Army Apache helicopter. However, the attack went badly wrong:<blockquote>I remember looking at the target, and then hearing the guns fire and then the rounds splashing 600m away and thinking, \u2018what the heck, that is not at all, that is not the target.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\"/></blockquote>Two boys, Toor Jan, age 7 and his brother Odood, who were collecting firewood had been mistakenly targeted for the two Taliban figures. An ADF inquiry later cleared the Australian forces of any breakdown in procedure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fdefence%2Fandrew-hastie-in-clear-on-second-afghan-incident%2Fnews-story%2Fb91a2ab20fa8ccfe4fb7f1a546b5e7cd&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=9daa57764cfab982111b15402df38b47-1576880157|title=Andrew Hastie in clear on second afghan incident|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> For Hastie, the death of the boys was both personally affecting and a turning point in his political outlook:<blockquote>I just felt sick. My stomach just dropped away.... It was arrogant to think we could build a mirror image of ourselves in foreign lands. [The boys\u2019 deaths] underscored the gap between our aims and reality. The two boys who perished were bystanders in this larger struggle. I was humbled and chastened by this experience. War is a miserable enterprise. I remember saying to my boss: \u2018I didn\u2019t come here to kill kids\u2019.<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\" /></blockquote>\n\n==== Inquiry into severed hands ====\nOne engagement with the Taliban became the subject of a major investigation. During combat operations on April 28 2013 which targeted a senior insurgent commander, several combatants were killed by a patrol under Hastie's command.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> On searching the dead men, one corporal severed the right hands of two \"Enemy Killed in Action\" using a scalpel. On attempting to do the same to a third EKIA the soldier was stopped by a sergeant who said, \u201cWhat the f*** are you doing?\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> On arriving at this part of battle environment, Hastie gave the order to cease the practice and the next day the incident was reported to the CO, triggering a major ADF inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> The inquiry heard that there had recently been training on how to collect biometric samples, particularly in managing the aftermath of a suicide bomb event,<ref>{{Cite book|title=No Front Line|last=Masters|first=Chris|publisher=Allen & Unwin|year=2017|isbn=9781760111144|location=Australia|pages=518}}</ref> Hastie later commented that \u201cthe guy giving instructions conflated site exploitation of a suicide bomber with that of biometric testing.\" The SASR corporal who severed the hands later conceded he had made an error of judgement in not first checking with his patrol commander.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> The inquiry made it clear that the practice, and the fact that some appeared to accept it at the time, \"demonstrated a drift in values, or at least a degree of desensitisation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-07-11/afghan-files-shed-light-on-notorious-severed-hands-case/8496654|title='What the f*** are you doing': Chaos over severed hands|last=Oakes|first=the National Reporting Team's Dan|last2=Clark|first2=Sam|date=2017-07-11|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Jordan and Afghanistan, 2014-2015 ===\nHastie deployed in late-2014 and 2015 to an intelligence role<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> in the Middle East-based role countering [[ISIL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-21/hastie-liberal-candidate-keogh-alp-canning-byelection/6713986|title=Andrew Hastie to run for Liberals, Matt Keogh for ALP in Canning by-election|date=20 August 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref> as an Operations Officer for Operation Gallant Phoenix,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unforgiving60.podbean.com/e/a-tale-of-two-andrews-%e2%80%93-two-federal-politicians-but-no-politics-andrew-hastie-mp-and-andrew-leigh-mp/|title=S1E15a- A Tale of Two Andrews \u2013 Two Federal Politicians / But No Politics! Andrew Hastie (MP) and Andrew Leigh (MP)|last=Development|first=PodBean|website=unforgiving60.podbean.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref> a classified defence operation based in Jordan. The operation is said to be collecting intelligence \"from commando raids in Syria and Iraq and funnelling it to law enforcement agencies in Europe and Southeast Asia to help stop future attacks.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Schmitt|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/24/us/politics/us-isis-fight.html|title=Its Territory May Be Gone, but the U.S. Fight Against ISIS Is Far From Over|date=2019-03-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|last2=Gibbons-Neff|first2=Thomas|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Cooper|first3=Helene|last4=Rubin|first4=Alissa J.}}</ref> Hastie resigned his commission from the ADF in August 2015 after announcing his candidature to run as the Member for Canning in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/andrew-hastie-liberal-byelection-candidate-led-troop-probed-for-chopping-hands-off-taliban-20150821-gj52lj.html|title=Andrew Hastie, Liberal byelection candidate, was in charge of troop probed for chopping hands off Taliban|date=22 August 2015|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=3 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n==Political career (2015\u2013present)==\n\n=== Election and first Turnbull Government ===\nThe seat of [[Division of Canning|Canning]] became vacant by the death in office of the Liberal member, [[Don Randall]], triggering the [[2015 Canning by-election]]. Hastie began a launched his campaign with strong support from [[Mathias Cormann]] and [[Julie Bishop]], however he was quickly inundated with media criticism about the \"severed hands\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2015/08/australia-election-dictate-pm-fate-150830103706951.html|title=Australia by-election could dictate PM's fate|last=Kurmelovs|first=Royce|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> incident and was further \"rattled\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=2015-09-11|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> by strong questioning of his family's religious beliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/creationism-rattles-cannings-newchum-politician-20150911-gjk0o8.html|title=Creationism rattles Canning's new-chum politician|last=Murphy|first=Damien|date=2015-09-11|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Within days Hastie would give a speech in which he strongly defended the soldiers under his command and his own military service:<blockquote>I have not lived my life behind a desk pushing paper and talking about the concepts of freedom and democracy. I have acted. I have put my life on the line for this country and for that freedom.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>On Saturday 19 September 2015, after a four-week campaign that centred on solving the [[methamphetamine]] epidemic, Hastie won 55.26% of votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote|two-party-preferred]] system, making him the 10th Federal Member for Canning, defeating Labor candidate [[Matt Keogh]]. He joined the government of [[Malcolm Turnbull]] who had himself become [[Prime Minister of Australia]] a week before the by-election. Hastie gave his first speech on 13 October 2015, which centred on his priorities for healthy democracy, stronger community institutions and for defending Australia's sovereignty, \"To safeguard our freedom I believe that the first duty of the Australian federal government is to secure our nation.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=ParlInfo - BUSINESS : Rearrangement|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In the first months, when headlines were dominated by the [[2015 Parramatta shooting|Parramatta shooting]] and the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris terror attack]] and the aftermath of the [[2014 Sydney hostage crisis|Sydney hostage crisis]], it seemed that Hastie's parliamentary career would be marked by his concern<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/asio-chief-called-just-two-coalition-mps-about-islam-debate-malcolm-turnbull-20151218-glr0js.html|title=ASIO chief called just two Coalition MPs about Islam debate: Malcolm Turnbull|last=Kenny|first=David Wroe and Mark|date=2015-12-18|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> about \"radical islamist ideology\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Alberici|first=Emma|title=Interview: Andrew Hastie, Liberal MP|date=2017-05-31|url=https://www.abc.net.au/lateline/interview:-andrew-hastie,-liberal-mp/8577672|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> arguing in interviews<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.2gb.com/podcast/alan-jones-andrew-hastie/|title=Alan Jones \u2013 Andrew Hastie|date=1448967022|website=2GB|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> and op eds that: <blockquote>I have read the Koran in its entirety. In my previous job with the Australian Defence Force, I studied Islamic State propaganda including many of its violent videos and images in an effort to understand their objectives, aims and rationale. I was disturbed by what I saw, but not cowed into inaction.... we should be free to question the roots of Islamic terrorism, especially the brand pushed by Islamic State. It is troubling that we have had young Australians sympathising with the theology and ideology of Islamic State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=AAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.adelaidenow.com.au%2Fnews%2Fopinion%2Fwe-should-be-free-to-question-the-roots-of-islamic-terrorism-especially-the-brand-pushed-by-islamic-state-writes-andrew-hastie%2Fnews-story%2F81bc06145842d58af1c980edb20d0b42&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=3290dea7434c4d3e6d98e6f90da327e0-1586142284|title=Adelaidenow.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Advertiser for exclusive stories|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Re-election and second Turnbull Government ===\nHastie stood again for the division of Canning for the [[2016 Australian federal election]], on Saturday 2 July. He won 56.79% of the votes under the [[Two-party-preferred vote]] against Labor opposition candidate Barry Winmar, moving his seat from being \"marginal\" to \"fairly safe\" according to the [[Australian Electoral Commission]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} He was appointed to the [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] [[File:Andrew Hastie MP, Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with Deputy Chair Anthony Byrne MP in February 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Anthony Byrne, a Labor MP and Deputy Chair of the Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security with its Chair, Andrew Hastie MP. ]]in September 2016, and invited to chair the committee from February 2017.<ref>http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F9de5f081-9ccf-4f72-a05a-02462c1f3a0c%2F0136%22 Retrieved 15 June 2017</ref> It's known the committee receives briefings from [[Inspector-General of Intelligence and Security (Australia)]], [[Australian Signals Directorate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/plans-to-boost-electronic-spy-agency-meet-with-extreme-caution-20190615-p51y1o.html|title=Plans to boost electronic spy agency meet with extreme caution|last=Ireland|first=David Wroe, Judith|date=2019-06-15|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> and [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itnews.com.au/news/four-hour-top-secret-briefing-used-to-press-encryption-law-need-516084|title=Four hour 'top secret' briefing used to press encryption law need|website=iTnews|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> As such, Hastie and fellow members of the [[bi-partisan]] committee are \"privy to a lot of information and intelligence briefings that other members of parliament aren't.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6070077627001|title='We can't deny there are problems with China's behaviour': Dutton|website=Sky News Australia|language=|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> Through his work with the PJCIS Hastie came to conclude that Australia is \"facing an unprecedented threat from espionage and foreign interference, and that current laws are not adequate to deal with this threat.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/foreign-interference-laws-needed-before-super-saturday-vote-christian-porter-says-20180607-h113o9|title=Foreign interference laws needed before super Saturday vote, Christian Porter says|date=2018-06-07|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> At this point the source of the foreign interference was unnamed. Following its deliberations, the committee reviewed and amended the [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018C00506 Espionage and Foreign Interference Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defence.gov.au/dsvs/industry/DISP-foreign-espionage.asp|title=Foreign Espionage & Interference Act 2018 : Industry Security Program : Department of Defence|last=|website=www.defence.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2018A00029 Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/about-us/our-portfolios/national-security/security-coordination/security-of-critical-infrastructure-act-2018|title=Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018|website=www.homeaffairs.gov.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n=== First Morrison Government ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie and daughter (KN).jpg|thumb|In Parliamentary offices, Andrew Hastie plays with his daughter. ]]\nIn August 2018, Malcolm Turnbull called for two [[2018 Liberal Party of Australia leadership spills|leadership spills]], in which Hastie is known to have supported the call for a new leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-24/the-liberal-mps-that-sparked-the-spill/10161660|title=The 43 Liberal MPs that brought down Malcolm Turnbull|date=2018-08-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> [[Scott Morrison]] was elected leader of the Liberal Party, becoming [[Prime Minister of Australia]]. Hastie maintained his chairmanship of the PJCIS as it took an increasingly serious tone on foreign threats. The committee carried the Assistance and Access Bill 2018 through to legislation enabling security agencies to access otherwise encrypted communications by people who intend harm to Australians. Prompted by the sale of the Port of [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] to interests connected to the Communist Party of China, the Committee made recommendations for the Security of Critical Infrastructure Act 2018 (Cth) (Act)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corrs.com.au/insights/critical-infrastructure-reporting-starts-now|title=Critical infrastructure: reporting starts now|website=Corrs Chambers Westgarth|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \u2014 placing a national security test to any foreign investment into energy or water assets and, notably, ports. The committee also contributed amendments to the Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme Act 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ag.gov.au/Integrity/foreign-influence-transparency-scheme/Pages/default.aspx|title=Foreign Influence Transparency Scheme|last=Department|first=Attorney-Generals's|website=www.ag.gov.au|language=en-au|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nIn his constituency work, Hastie surprised some by giving public support to striking [[Alcoa Australia]] workers, organised by the [[Australian Workers' Union]]. Hastie said, he supported the strikers because, \"energy production in Australia is too expensive and it is hurting industry, workers, seniors and families. We have to put Australians first. Otherwise, more jobs will go offshore to other countries. Our smelters and refineries will close down. Energy security is job security.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/opinion/andrew-hastie-utility-bills-are-crippling-workingclass-families/news-story/d2890e742284107f09917bfcbfd78a08|title=Utility bills are crippling working-class families|date=November 23, 2018|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=9 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Re-election and second Morrison Government ===\n[[File:AH and PM at Mandurah War Memorial (KN).jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Scott Morrison and Andrew Hastie MP stand by ANZAC wreaths at a memorial in Mandurah.]]\nIn the [[2019 Australian federal election]], held on May 18, Hastie ran for re-election and won 61.83% of the [[two-party-preferred vote]] against the Australian Labor Party's candidate Mellisa Teede. On entering the [[46th Parliament of Australia]] Hastie, in which [[Scott Morrison]] was returned as Prime Minister, Hastie become increasingly involved in lawmaking around matters of national security. He spoke in 45 debates in 2019, above average according to Open Australia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/mp/andrew_hastie/canning|title=Andrew Hastie MP, Canning (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> the bulk of them surrounding matters of security or sovereignty.  [[Parliamentary Joint Committee on Intelligence and Security]] pushed forward the Temporary Exclusion Orders Bill designed to prevent dual-national terrorists from returning to Australia. [[File:Andrew Hastie MP with flag gifted to him by SASR operators January 2020 photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie in his electoral office in Mandurah, with an Australian flag given to him by a friend in the ADF, it had once flown at a army forward operating base]]However, the Identity-matching Services Bill 2019 and the Australian Passports Amendment (Identity-matching Services) Bill 2019 were reviewed by the committee and sent back for redrafting.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/facial-recognition-bill-knocked-back-20191024-p533s6|title=Facial recognition bill knocked back|date=2019-10-23|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> By 2020, Hastie was able to review the suite of legislative changes security as being all of one piece, to strengthen Australia's position in the region and the world:<blockquote>What we\u2019ve done in Australia over the last three or four years, I call it our pivot... taking action to preserve our digital sovereignty by excluding high-risk vendors from our future 5G network, passing the Espionage and Foreign Interference Laws, stopping the extradition treaty to China, those things were part of the pivot and ultimately, they\u2019re expressions of our sovereignty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\u00a0 </blockquote>\n\n==== \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\" ====\n[[File:Joint media release Hastie Paterson November 15 2019.jpg|alt=A media release from Andrew Hastie MP and Senator James Paterson.|thumb|Hastie and James Paterson confirm they have been blocked from visiting China following their public comments about the [[Communist Party of China]]]]\nIn August 2019 Hastie wrote an [[Op-ed]] column, \"We Must See China with Clear Eyes\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> for [[The Sydney Morning Herald|''The Sydney Morning Herald'']] and [[The Age|''The Age'']] newspapers<ref name=\"Hastie\"/>, where he admitted that Communist China \u2014 rather than [[Islamic terrorism]], which he worked to defeat in his military career \u2014 would be the real security concern of the 21st Century. Moreover, a rising, revisionist, expansionist China would frame \"almost every strategic and economic question facing Australia in the coming decades.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-08-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>  What brought more attention was his strong criticism of Western democracies and their mistaken belief \"that economic liberalisation would naturally lead to democratisation in China\" much as the French had believed the [[Maginot Line]] would guard them against the German advance in 1940. Hastie wrote, \"Like the French, Australia has failed to see how mobile our authoritarian neighbour has become.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/we-must-see-china-the-opportunities-and-the-threats-with-clear-eyes-20190807-p52eon.html|title=We must see China - the opportunities and the threats - with clear eyes|last1=Hastie|first1=Andrew|date=8 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The piece caused \"a firestorm\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> with the [[Embassy of China, Canberra|Chinese Embassy in Australia]] denouncing the remarks as reflecting a \"[[Cold war (general term)|Cold War]] mentality\",<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Liberal MP Andrew Hastie condemned by China after comparing Beijing's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last1=Laschon|first1=Eliza|date=8 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> while Western Australian Premier [[Mark McGowan]], whose state is heavily reliant on China for trade,<ref name=\"abcaunazi\">{{cite news|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-09/wa-particularly-vulnerable-in-a-china-us-trade-war/11395926|title=Western Australia's huge reliance on China leaves it particularly vulnerable in a trade war|last1=O'Flaherty|first1=Alisha|date=10 August 2019|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> accusing Hastie of \"threatening WA jobs with extreme and inflammatory language.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> An academic at UWA opined that the Western Australian government's contemporaneous relationship with China may not be sustainable in the future, saying \"But there may come a time where this relationship is not possible to be run purely on commercial lines, and I have to say most of the reason for that is the changing behaviour of the Chinese Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"abcaunazi\" /> Conversely, Hastie received support from his colleagues [[Dave Sharma]]<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-wins-support-for-his-china-warning-from-former-diplomat-sharma-20190810-p52fup.html|title=Hastie wins support for his China warning from former diplomat Sharma|last1=Wright|first1=Shane|date=10 August 2019|work=[[The Age]]|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> and [[Peter Dutton]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/no-point-pretending-there-s-nothing-to-see-here-peter-dutton-warns-on-china-20190809-p52fgz.html|title='No point pretending there's nothing to see here': Peter Dutton warns on China|last1=Shields|first1=Bevan|date=9 August 2019|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> Hastie had been invited on a study trip with several colleagues to China with the independent think tank China Matters. However the Chinese embassy announced \u201cthat at this time Mr Hastie and Senator Paterson are not welcome\" unless they \"genuinely repent and redress their mistakes.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/nov/15/china-denies-entry-to-liberal-mps-andrew-hastie-and-james-paterson|title=China denies entry to Liberal MPs Andrew Hastie and James Paterson|last=editor|first=Katharine Murphy Political|date=2019-11-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This snub had the effect of making [[Communist Party of China]] attempts to control the behaviour and speech of people in sovereign nations an even bigger concern. Hastie's warnings about Chinese abuses of human rights and interference with sovereign nations appeared to be vindicated when newspapers released 400 pages of Chinese documents<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/16/world/asia/china-xinjiang-documents.html|title='Absolutely No Mercy': Leaked Files Expose How China Organized Mass Detentions of Muslims|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|date=2019-11-16|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-18|last2=Buckley|first2=Chris|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> on the workings of internment camps in [[Xinjiang]], shortly followed by the apparent defection of a young Chinese spy with information in connection with a Chinese Australian, Nick Zhao<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-25/chinese-spy-parliament-foreign-interference-in-hong-kong-taiwan/11735176|title=A man is dead. Another fears being killed. Here's a breakdown of the claims about Chinese espionage|last=Conifer|first=Dan|date=2019-11-25|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> who was funded by Chinese interests to run for parliament, and was later found dead in a hotel room. By raising concerns about foreign interference, the opinion piece has been seen as a \"threshold\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/hastie-s-awakening-to-xi-s-bid-for-total-control-of-china-and-beyond-20190809-p52for.html|title=Hastie's awakening to Xi's bid for total control of China - and beyond|last=Hartcher|first=Peter|date=2019-08-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref>, with other commentators predicting that Hastie's concerns \"will dominate the political agenda\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whinnett|first=Ellen|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/ellen-whinnett-china-crisis-looms-large-in-canberra/news-story/66c19d19acafcbaa2a914fabe17b23d5|title=China crisis looms large in Canberra|date=December 4, 2019|work=Herald Sun|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, having been discussed in the pages of global newspapers such as ''[[Haaretz]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.haaretz.com/world-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|last=Melman|first=Yossi|date=December 6, 2019|website=haaretz.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref>  [[The Times|''The Times'']]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/beijing-denies-australian-mps-right-to-visit-china-bldtfvl2j|title=Beijing denies Australian MPs right to visit China|last=Times|first=Bernard Lagan, Sydney {{!}} The|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/28/world/australia/china-spying-wang-liqiang-nick-zhao.html|title=Suddenly, the Chinese Threat to Australia Seems Very Real|last=Cave|first=Damien|date=2019-11-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-18|last2=Tarabay|first2=Jamie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nHastie has been described as a \"conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/ruthless-hardline-and-focused-the-mp-who-stunned-parliament-20180525-p4zhgy.html|title='Ruthless, hardline and focused': The MP who stunned Parliament|last=Wright|first=Tony|date=2018-05-25|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>, a \"social conservative\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/08/canning-byelection-the-complete-and-completely-unofficial-guide-to-the-candidates|title=Canning byelection: the complete (and completely unofficial) guide to the candidates|date=2015-09-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and, at least by the official Chinese government media as \"an arch-conservative\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/21/c_137406904.htm|title=News Analysis: Aussie gov't set for period of upheaval following leadership challenge to PM - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>. Critics see his foreign policy outlook as being \"jingoistic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1161600.shtml|title=Australia need not follow US script on its relationship with China - Global Times|website=www.globaltimes.cn|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> and the MP himself as \"a notorious hawk.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/08/andrew-hasties-nazi-germany-warning-on-china-labelled-extreme-and-unwelcome|title=China denounces Liberal MP Andrew Hastie's Nazi Germany analogy|date=2019-08-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Hastie himself has said, \"I am not a libertarian, but I am a Liberal, which is to say that I am committed to freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/blogs/andrew-bolt/andrew-hastie-shames-the-free-speech-quislings/news-story/1f81333ae068f76e98ca8b311effcc1d|title=Andrew Hastie Shames the Free Speech Quislings|last=Bolt|first=Andrew|date=March 3, 2017|website=Herald Sun|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 30 2020}}</ref> This would appear to be confirmed by his decision to join the [[Atlantic Council]] \u2014 a [[Classical liberalism|Classical liberal]] bi-partisan think tank formed for \"defending democratic values.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/cbd-melbourne-hockey-ready-to-ride-post-virus-bondi-wave-20200325-p54dw1.html|title=CBD Melbourne: Hockey ready to ride post-virus Bondi wave|last=Loussikian|first=Samantha Hutchinson, Kylar|date=2020-03-25|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The invitation<ref name=\":5\" /> came via US Congressman [[Mike Gallagher (American politician)|Mike Gallagher]], a conservative [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and [[Tom Tugendhat]], a British MP who describes himself as a \"community conservative.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smf.co.uk/tom-tugendhat-speech-2018/|title=Tom Tugendhat MP's speech for the SMF|date=2018-11-08|website=Social Market Foundation|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> [[File:Soldiers cross a foot bridge in the Mirabad Valley.jpg|thumb|A footbridge in the Mirabad Valley, in [[Urozgan Province]], built by [[Australian Defence Force|ADF]] engineers, being patrolled by a member of the [[Afghan National Army]], followed by an Australian soldier from the [[Mentoring Task Force One|Mentoring Task Force]] in February 2010. ]] His outlook, unsurprisingly, has been shaped by his experience of war:<blockquote>I take my time in Afghanistan, especially in my first deployment, particularly my time with [[Mentoring Task Force One|MRTF2]] with the [[1st Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment|1RAR]] battle group, as being very formative for me, doing [[Nation Building - Afghanistan|Nation Building]] and realising the limitations of government to change people and their culture. We built bridges, we built a bazaar where we expected people to trade, we built schools and hospitals, we built all sorts of things, but fundamentally, we didn\u2019t change the way the Afghan people lived. Respecting people\u2019s sovereignty, and people\u2019s freedom to live as they choose is something that I learned over there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref></blockquote>[[File:Hastie giving crayons to children op takht.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant Hastie distributing crayons to Afghan children in Oruzghan]]This experience seems to have made Hastie sceptical of [[Neoliberalism]], saying, \"I am now far more circumspect about the ability of military power to change people and societies, and far more aware of how resilient culture can be.\"<ref name=\"thewest.com.au\" /> By the same measure, Hastie is diffident towards [[Neoconservatism]], especially in its [[Laissez-faire]] tendencies, which he finds unacceptable because, \"despite the benefits of globalisation, there are always losers in the transfer of labour and capital offshore. Loss of identity through vocational irrelevance is a real anxiety in communities that prize skilled labour.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political Class Ignored the People and Paid the Price|date=November 23, 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Hastie's high view of  sovereignty and his desire to protect local people and their industries from global forces<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/26/andrew-hasties-contribution-to-our-china-effort-curious-and-curiouser|title=Andrew Hastie's contribution to our China effort? Curious and curiouser {{!}} Katharine Murphy|last=Murphy|first=Katharine|date=2018-05-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> would places him in the tradition of [[National liberalism]]. Recently Ben Pronk and Tim Curtis (both former SAS officers, Pronk had been Hastie's commanding officer) asked Hastie for his vision for Australia. His off the cuff answer was: <blockquote>I hope to see a country where families are strong. Where we've incentivised families through the policies that we've legislated. I hope to see a strong defence force so that we can weather the challenges that will inevitably come. If you take history as a guide we will face inevitable security challenges. I hope that we are aware of our history, that we haven't cut the mooring that is our civilisation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unforgiving60.com/|title=A Tale of Two Andrews|last=|first=|date=|website=Unforgiving 60|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref></blockquote>This statement contains three threads that are seen in almost all of Hastie's writing and remarks. First, a passion \"to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Greg|first=Brown|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/rivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy/news-story/455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811|title=Rivals unite for the sake of democracy|date=July 13, 2020|work=The Australian|access-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. Second, a believe that \"Sovereignty, where compromised, must be recovered and protected.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Third, that community or local institutions \"should define the character and activity of our nation from the ground up.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0200;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/e5ff85d2-b96e-4e0e-8227-2131e40beaf7/0049%22|title=ParlInfo - ADJOURNMENT : 45th Parliament|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Democracy ===\nOne [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]] profile on Hastie found that \"the heart of his worldview is the belief that everyone is equal and has dignity\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382?pfmredir=sm&sf75079731=1&smid=Page:+ABC+News-Facebook_Organic&WT.tsrc=Facebook_Organic|title=Keeping the faith: Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|website=mobile.abc.net.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and from here his convictions about democracy emanate. The belief in the inherent value of the individual means the individual must be free when it comes to \"thought, worship, speech, association and choice\" as Hastie said in his first speech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b1239e0c-7fca-43e4-aac5-25ac64e2bc96/0128%22|title=First Speech|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=13 October 2015|website=Parliament of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> These freedoms allow our communities to naturally form and \"are the fullest expression of self-government.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie recently collaborated with the [[Australian Labor Party]]'s [[Kimberley Kitching]] to form the \"Parliamentary Friends of Democracy.\" It comes out of a concern that democratic institutions are \"under increasing pressure around the globe.\" They believe, \"Australian parliamentarians have a duty to rise above party to defend the rule of law, democracy and the constituent freedoms that make Australia a special place to live.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a&dest=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theaustralian.com.au%2Fnation%2Fpolitics%2Frivals-unite-for-the-sake-of-democracy%2Fnews-story%2F455c76fe549eda7c318a6a496985b811&memtype=anonymous&mode=premium&nk=e77fa5e4fbb81da52eba770ee8c0a8a7-1576685699|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|website=www.theaustralian.com.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> This view expands on concerns that Hastie has expressed elsewhere, that \"our greatest vulnerability lies not in our infrastructure, but in our thinking. That intellectual failure makes us institutionally weak. If we don't understand the challenge ahead for our civil society, in our parliaments, in our universities, in our private enterprises, in our charities \u2014 our little platoons \u2014 then choices will be made for us. Our sovereignty, our freedoms, will be diminished.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-08-08/chinese-officials-slam-andrew-hastie-nazi-beijing-china-comments/11395980|title=Embassy condemns MP Hastie for comparing China's rise to threat from Nazi Germany|last=Laschon|first=political reporter Eliza|date=2019-08-08|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> In February 2020 it was announced that Hastie had been invited to serve on a panel of western leaders who are concerned for the state of global democracy, the Commission on Advancing a Free World, in association with [[Atlantic Council|The Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/news/press-releases/free-world-commission-of-legislators-from-leading-democracies-launched-at-munich-security-conference/|title=Free World Commission of legislators from leading democracies launched at Munich Security Conference|date=2020-02-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> Their ''Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/declaration/|title=Declaration of Principles for Freedom, Prosperity, and Peace|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> articulates seven statements for protecting democracy across the world, beginning with \"the right of all people to live in free and just societies, where fundamental rights are protected under the rule of law.\"\n\n==== Freedom of thought - on marriage ====\nHastie saw the 2016 [[Same-sex marriage in Australia|Same-sex marriage debate in Australia]] as a conscience issue.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/marriage-is-peoples-institution-so-they-should-decide-its-future/news-story/a6ace55c388f0f5e3c7484f8738aefe6|title=Marriage is people's institution, so they should decide its future|date=September 20, 2016|work=|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  He supported the postal survey because he believed that the institution of marriage, since it existed before the parliament, was an institution that \"belongs to the people\" so it was right for the people themselves to vote on it.<ref name=\":4\" /> When the \"yes vote\" was strongly returned, Hastie ensured passage of the bill, but could not vote for it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-11-15/wa-politicians-to-ignore-same-sex-marriage-result/9154656|title=Prominent No campaigner to abstain from same-sex marriage vote|date=2017-11-15|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He explained, \"We went to the election with it, I was on television saying I would abstain, I've been in dialogue with constituents for the last 18 months and whenever I've talked to them about the issue, I've said I would abstain. My intention is to abstain because to vote yes would go against my conscience, but I want to uphold both the vote in Canning and the national result and abstention is the best way to do that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/5058727/hastie-to-abstain-on-yes-vote/|title=Hastie to abstain on 'yes' vote|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2017-11-15|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Most of Hastie's statements through the public debate centred not on marriage, but on how to have the debate. When right wing commentators such as Larry Pickering used homophobic language towards [[LGBT]] persons, Hastie immediately condemned the statement, expressing his \"dismay\" at the degrading language, and pleaded for \"higher personal and civic standards\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/pickering-comments-despicable-hastie|title=Pickering comments despicable: Hastie|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of conscience - on military abuses ====\nRecent reports by Chris Masters and others of prisoner abuse, and even killings, by the Australian [[Special Air Service Regiment]] in Afghanistan have seen Hastie come forward as a strong advocate for transparency, though it may hurt the prestige of his former unit. He has \"emerged as a champion of the Brereton Inquiry.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/he-thought-i-was-going-to-shoot-him-how-david-s-little-voice-saved-him-in-war-20190913-p52qy6.html|title='He thought I was going to shoot him': How David's 'little voice' saved him in war|last=Masters|first=Nick McKenzie, Chris|date=2019-09-20|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> He strongly supports whistleblowers when it comes to abuse, telling ABC Radio the truth tellers should be respected: \"I don't want to go into any specific allegations, but they should be taken seriously and, as I said, we want a free media reporting on all issues.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/secretive-and-elite-sas-soldiers-grilled-about-alleged-war-crimes-20180608-p4zkau.html|title=Secretive and elite SAS soldiers grilled about alleged war crimes|last=Wroe|first=Nick McKenzie, David|date=2018-06-08|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of expression ====\nIn one of Hastie's first electoral campaigns, he had a large outdoor poster vandalised. Rather than condemn the culprit, he wrote a Facebook message, \"Will Mandurah's Van Gogh please come forward<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/3985723/hasties-spray-mp-responds-to-graffiti-attack/|title=Hastie's spray: MP responds to graffiti attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2016-06-22|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> then had a local graffiti artist add even more colour to the piece. However, when a campaign bus was torched, Hastie drew a firm line, calling them, \"cowards using Taliban tactics in the dead of night\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watoday.com.au/federal-election-2019/andrew-hastie-s-campaign-bus-survives-dead-of-night-arson-attack-20190420-p51fr4.html|title=Andrew Hastie's campaign bus survives 'dead of night' arson attack|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2019-04-19|website=WAtoday|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie encourages debate and dissension, especially in classroom settings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4488661/students-get-political-during-hastie-visit/|title=Students get political during Hastie visit|last=Cockerill|first=Jess|date=2017-02-23|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Freedom of press ====\nHastie is currently having difficulty balancing freedoms when it comes to the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/today/paddy-manning/2019/23/2019/1563861108/joint-pain|title=Joint pain|last=paddym@schwartzmedia.com.au1516749970|date=2019-07-23|website=The Monthly|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He has actively stood up for journalists at the ABC and [[Sydney morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]], using Parliamentary privilege to name Chau Chak Wing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> as a man who co-conspired to bribe a UN official, a man who took the media outlets to court for defamation as they had published the accusations. Hastie explained his actions by saying \"...democracy works only if we have a free press that can publish information that serves the public interest.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-23/turnbull-did-not-know-hastie-would-make-chau-chak-wing-claims/9790476|title=Liberal MP says he did his duty in speaking up about political donor|last=Yaxley|first=political reporters Louise|last2=Gribbin|first2=Caitlyn|date=2018-05-23|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18|last3=Conifer|first3=Dan}}</ref> However, current laws have allowed for the Australian Federal Police to raid journalists from the ABC and News Corp Australia for reasons of security.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-07-15/abc-raids-australian-federal-police-press-freedom/11309810|title=AFP wanted fingerprints of journalists behind ABC special forces investigation|last=Lyons|first=the ABC's head of investigative journalism John|date=2019-07-15|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> This places a tension between freedom and sovereignty.\n\n==== Freedom of religion ====\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Huyghur delegates and Sen James Paterson 30 November 2019 photographed by D Birch.jpg|thumb|Delegates from Australia's Uyghur community, Sadam and Almas, meeting with Andrew Hastie MP (on left) and Senator James Paterson (right) at Parliament House, Canberra, in November 2019.]]\nWhile an observant Christian<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Hastie holds to the view that if the law allows him to practice his faith, it must allow all to express their faith, or lack of it. That means, in Australia, that while he personally finds the burka \"repugnant\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> as it \"defaces the personhood of women\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> he would be very reluctant to have the state controlling it, as it's an expression of religious belief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-05-02/keeping-the-faith-andrew-hastie/8477382|title=Andrew Hastie on poetry, political courage, and not banning the burka|last=Alexandra Beech|date=2017-05-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Hastie advocates strongly for freedom of religion as a basic human right across the globe, including the right of [[Uyghurs]] to practice their faith in China's Xingjian Province, saying \"it's our duty to stand up for them, and argue the point, and ask for their freedom.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=2019-11-17|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> After [[The New York Times]] published the [[Xinjiang papers]] Hastie expressed deep empathy for those with personal ties to Uighurs facing \"systemic persecution and internment\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/liberal-mp-and-outspoken-china-critic-vows-uighur-loved-ones-will-not-be-forgotten|title=Liberal MP and outspoken China critic vows Uighur \u2018loved ones\u2019 will not be forgotten|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  The documents showed how China views their the muslim people of that region as being \"infected, as they say, with unhealthy thoughts\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-17/andrew-hastie-james-paterson-refuse-to-repent-china-criticism/11712160|title=Hastie and Paterson defiant in the face of China's calls for repentance|last=Dalzell|first=political reporter Stephanie|last2=Editor|first2=Political|date=2019-11-17|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-10|last3=Probyn|first3=rew}}</ref> forcing millions into the communist government's [[Xinjiang re-education camps|Xinjiang re-education program]]. Hastie urged Uyghur people in Australia, and in China, not to give up hope.<ref name=\":7\" /> \n\n=== Sovereignty ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with Mayor Rhys Williams at March 2020 Citizenship Ceremony in Mandurah photo taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|The Mayor of Mandurah, Rhys Williams, with Andrew Hastie MP, hosting an Australian Citizenship ceremony in March 2020]]\nHastie argues that Australia's representatives must be the ones making decisions that affect Australia's future, and so \"upholding our political system is the first thing that we must do because that at least preserves our political leadership and their ability to make decisions, un-influence by greater powers.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.defenceconnect.com.au/key-enablers/5792-insight-australia-s-relationship-with-china-andrew-hastie-mp|title=INSIGHT: Australia\u2019s relationship with China \u2013 Andrew Hastie MP|last=Levy|first=Tasha|last2=Levy|first2=Tasha|date=2020-03-19|website=www.defenceconnect.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> As such he strongly resists foreign influence on the working of the Australian economy, culture or political system. \"My bottom line is Australian sovereignty \u2013 I want to protect our way of life, our freedom of action and our political institutions. That's my job as a member of the Commonwealth Parliament. I make no apologies for it.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-a-dead-spy-chinese-hackers-and-the-australian-commando-warning-israel-1.8223349|title=A Dead Spy, Chinese Hackers and the Australian Commando Warning Israel|date=2019-12-06|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Economic sovereignty ====\nInterestingly, Hastie locates the energy debates as sovereignty issue, and in 2018 said, \"I have a problem legislating the Paris target because it undermines Australia's 'economic sovereignty'\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kelly|first=Joe|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/andrew-hastie-confirms-we-cannot-support-neg-in-current-form/news-story/48af53948ad288198550fdb68617f947|title=Andrew Hastie confirms he cannot support NEG in current form|date=August 16, 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which meant he could not support the [[National Energy Guarantee]]. The next month he made a speech in the Federation Chamber, saying, \"Australian industry and Australian workers must come first. When it comes to energy, we must put the Australian people before Paris.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;db=CHAMBER;id=chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0350;query=Id:%22chamber/hansardr/b8101fb1-edde-4753-a50e-1709934db485/0329%22|title=ParlInfo - Federation Chamber : PRIVATE MEMBERS' BUSINESS : Alcoa|website=parlinfo.aph.gov.au|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==== Sovereignty and political warfare ====\nThis has been the main legislative focus for Hastie in recent times. In an interview with the Israeli newspaper ''Haaretz'', Hastie explained that, \"Democratic countries must take domestic measures to protect against these threats. Australia has led the way in this regard. Authoritarian states use all instruments of state power to pursue their strategic objectives. Seemingly innocent activities like diplomacy, foreign-investment flows into strategic industries and infrastructure acquisitions like the purchase of ports are not so innocuous. Democracies who don't pay attention to these activities \u2013 and take measures to guard against them \u2013 risk becoming tethered to hyper-modern authoritarian states and losing their sovereignty in the process.\"<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/>\n\n==== Digital sovereignty ====\nHastie frames questions to do with the provision of information networks as a matter of sovereignty, which must be defended. Given that companies such as Huawei would be legally required to pass on information carried on their networks to the Chinese government,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/05/huawei-would-have-to-give-data-to-china-government-if-asked-experts.html|title=Huawei says it would never hand data to China's government. Experts say it wouldn't have a choice|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=2019-03-05|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> Hastie was a strong supporter of the Turnbull Government's decision to prevent that company from providing 5G services in Australia. Along with other parliamentarians from the Liberal Party, including [[Tim Wilson (Australian politician)|Tim Wilson]] and [[James Paterson (Australian politician)|James Paterson]] and [[Australian Labor Party|Labor's]] [[Kimberley Kitching]] and [[Anthony Byrne (politician)|Anthony Byrne]], he has been active in applying pressure to Australia's partners in the [[Five Eyes]] security alliance to do the same. In a public statement he explained how important that security arrangement is, \"In a time of growing strategic uncertainty, Australia values that membership more than ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/four-australian-mps-urge-britain-to-ban-huawei-20200124-p53u9x.html|title=Four Australian MPs urge Britain to ban Huawei|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=2020-01-23|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> In private settings, it is known that he has supported Byrne, the Deputy Chair of the committee Hastie leads, who used forceful language with the UK leadership, asking \u201cHow would you feel if the Russians laid down infrastructure in your own networks? That\u2019s how we feel about Huawei.\u201d Hastie is quoted as supporting frank conversation about data sovereignty with western allies, saying \"We save our toughest talk for our closest mates. I back my deputy chair.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Times|first=Lucy Fisher, Defence Editor {{!}} Caroline Wheeler, The Sunday|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/huawei-decision-may-threaten-trade-deal-with-us-says-mike-pence-vlg9d6ggs|title=Mike Pence and Tory MPs attack Boris Johnson over Huawei decision|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==== Enemies, allies and sovereignty ====\nIn May 2018, Hastie took the \"dramatic\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/andrew-hastie-senate-estimates/9797718|title=ASIO boss says Hastie's allegations have had no impact on intelligence allies|last=Gribbin|first=political reporter Caitlyn|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> step of using parliamentary privilege to name a Chinese-Australian property developer as being a corrupt person acting in the interests of a foreign power, saying, \"It is now my duty to inform the House and the Australian people that CC-3 is Chau Chak Wing, the same man who co-conspired to bribe the president of the United Nations General Assembly, John Ashe, the same man with extensive contacts in the Chinese Communist Party, including the United Front.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=2018-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The information had been given to the MP during meetings in the United States earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/world/australia/bribery-un-china-chau-chak-wing.html|title=In Australia, Fears of Chinese Meddling Rise on U.N. Bribery Case Revelation|date=2018-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Williams|first2=Jacqueline|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The move was criticised as \"causing trouble\" both to the government to Australia's relationship with China.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Hastie himself believed he was compelled to speak as, \"My duty, first and foremost, is to the Australian people and the preservation of the ideals and democratic traditions of our Commonwealth.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/politics/why-andrew-hastie-australias-uberpatriot-mp-risked-chinas-wrath-20180524-h10ie6|title=Why Andrew Hastie, Australia's uber-patriot MP, risked China's wrath|date=2018-05-24|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n[[File:AH and Gen Mattis.jpg|thumb|Hastie with General Jim Mattis outside the Pentagon on 4 May 2018]]\nWhile the incident gave another example of the parliamentarian's determination to protect Australian institutions from the influence of the Chinese Communist Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/political-donor-chau-chak-wing-behind-un-bribe-scandal-parliament-told-20180522-p4zgs5.html|title=Political donor Chau Chak Wing behind UN bribe scandal, Parliament told|last=Baker|first=Nick McKenzie, Richard|date=2018-05-22|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> his acting in consort with American defence forces and intelligence agencies such as the Department of Justice<ref>{{Cite news|last=Karp|first=Paul|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/may/24/andrew-hasties-use-of-us-intelligence-over-bribery-allegation-a-concern-dreyfus-says|title=Andrew Hastie's use of US intelligence over bribery allegation 'a concern', Dreyfus says|date=2018-05-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> also provided more proof of his commitment to the [[U.S.-Australia alliance]]. At the high level, Hastie believes that this alliance is essential to Australia maintaining its sovereignty saying, \u201cNational leaders must affirm and articulate the values that define Western democracies, especially as we seek to build a coalition of like-minded partners to resist authoritarian political warfare.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/challenge-to-democracy-to-counter-russia-china-20191204-p53gzj.html|title=Challenge to democracy to counter Russia, China|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|date=2019-12-09|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> He led a parliamentary delegation to the United States in early 2017 and afterwards indicated that, for him, the defence alliance holds personal importance<blockquote>\u201cWhen we met with House and Senate leaders, and members of the [US] House Intelligence Committee, those committee members really emphasised the importance of the relationship... I was sitting there in front of the Senate Intelligence and Security Committee and the committee minority leader is a senator from Virginia and I said to him, \u2018I wouldn't be sitting here if it wasn\u2019t for a medic from Virginia who saved my grandfather\u2019s life on the 31st of March 1945\u2019.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/4466943/hastie-promoted-to-key-national-security-role/|title=Hastie promoted to key national security role|last=Hondros|first=Nathan|date=2017-02-14|website=Mandurah Mail|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Community ===\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP Age Care Community Visit.jpg|thumb|Andrew Hastie MP visiting Amana Living Meadow Springs Village, an Anglican age care community in Mandurah.]]Hastie's experiences in Afghanistan, especially in seeing how limited the military is in reshaping people's lives, seems to have given him an even higher view of community, culture and local institutions. In an interview about his wartime experiences, he said:<blockquote> For me, it proved that culture and geography (are) decisive in the formation of societies and political institutions. Building lasting, trusted institutions takes time, generations of stewardship and public virtue.<ref name=\"Whinnett\"/></blockquote>\n[[File:Andrew Hastie MP with son Jonathan at the 2018 ANZAC Day March in Mandurah WA taken by D Birch.jpg|thumb|His son Jonathan holding his hand, Andrew Hastie marches with veterans on [[Anzac Day]] in Mandurah. ]]\n\n Looking at Australia, Hastie believes that it is local institutions that provide civic foundations of \"accountability, freedom and democracy.\"<ref name=\"First Speech\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/first_speech|title=First Speech|website=Andrew Hastie MP|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> He argued in his first speech that the first of these institutions is the family, which \"is central to a healthy society\"<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> but also extends to sporting clubs, service clubs, churches and local businesses.<ref name=\"First Speech\"/> In one op-ed, Hastie went even further, suggesting that community groups, or \"pre-political institutions\" are finally more important than governments:<blockquote> \"More powerful than the political levers of government are grassroots volunteer movements and pre-political institutions... Pre-political institutions are the best place for securing our freedoms and so we should take encouragement that democratic governments cannot control them, and are sent packing when they attempt to do so.\"<ref name=\"theaustralian.com.au\">{{Cite news|last=Hastie|first=Andrew|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/opinion/political-class-ignored-the-people-and-paid-the-price/news-story/f1d35ad7c29f76daf08768182b316d55|title=Political class ignored the people and paid the price|date=November 23, 2016|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==== The power of community and PTSD ====\nHastie reflected on how his grandfather recovered from the trauma of [[World War II]] thanks, in part to the power of community, and laments that we may not have that power available to us now, \"Just thinking of my grandfather's own experience, he was shot up quite badly in the second world war where civil society was still very strong, community was still very strong, a lot of local clubs and organisations, I think he struggled with [[Posttraumatic stress disorder|PTSD]] but I think his PTSD was mitigated by those little platoons that we talk about, he was very close to his comrades from the second war, and I'm just not sure if we have in today's society that same sort of cushioning and community support as we had 70 years ago.\"<ref name=\"Grattan\"/>\n\n==== Community and environment ====\nWhile environmental concern is often seen as a progressive cause, Hastie sets the environment between two concerns - that, as per the [[Edmund Burke|Burkean]] contract - the good things inherited should be passed on to the next generation. And that the environment serves the community, which means they need to make the decisions about it. In a recent controversy about a proposed dredging of an estuary, Hastie said: <blockquote>\"I believe in the sovereignty of local communities to make decisions about how they conserve and develop their environment. The Bindjareb people, the First Australians in my constituency, have long been custodians of the waterways\u2014for many generations back to the present. The Murray Mandurah community also shares this responsibility, and together we are all stewards of the beautiful Peel-Harvey Estuary, a body of water larger than Sydney Harbour, teeming with marine life and brimming with natural beauty. We, therefore, through our local governments, have sovereignty over this natural asset and should have a say about how development takes place. We're not antiprogress, but we are rightly cautious about development, as we are the ones most affected by it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2019-09-11.151.1&s=speaker:10843#g151.2|title=Peel-Harvey Estuary: 11 Sep 2019: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AH with family (KN).jpg|thumb|Ruth and Andrew Hastie with their children in Mandurah, October 2018]]\nHastie met his wife Ruth in the summer of 2007 while he was studying at [[George Washington University]]. Hastie proposed to Ruth on the steps of the [[Sydney Opera House]]. The two were married in 2008 at [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]]. Their children were born in Perth in June 2015 and August 2017. The family of four now lives in the [[City of Mandurah]] in the [[Peel (Western Australia)|Peel]] region of [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For God and country|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/sas-commander-liberal-party-rising-star-how-far-can-andrew-hastie-go/news-story/327a82373c4e90755402c1388506a502|accessdate=18 April 2018|agency=The Australian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Andrew|url=https://www.andrewhastie.com.au/about_andrew|website=www.andrewhastie.com|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe credits his family for giving him a love for reading, especially \"biographies, Shakespeare, psalms\"<ref name=\"Development\"/> along with history. Favourite historians include [[Geoffrey Blainey]], [[H. W. Brands]], [[Niall Ferguson]], [[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]] and [[Ronald C. White]]. He also enjoys 20th century novelists such as [[Graham Greene]], [[Cormac McCarthy]] and [[P. G. Wodehouse]].\n\nFellow parliamentarians recognise Hastie as \u201ca man of deep faith\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.openaustralia.org.au/debates/?id=2018-10-24.163.2&s=speaker:10843#g180.1|title=National Apology to Victims and...: 24 Oct 2018: House debates (OpenAustralia.org)|website=www.openaustralia.org.au|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> which he shares with his parents and siblings. Whilst he is frequently ridiculed as being \u201cfundamentalist\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/blog/mungo-maccallum/2018/28/2018/1527472468/hastie-judgement|title=Hastie judgement|last=kateg@themonthly.com.au1515708219|date=2018-05-28|website=The Monthly|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> he has been active across several reformed, evangelical and Protestant church communities with historic understandings of the Christian faith, including [[Capitol Hill Baptist Church]] in Washington DC, Shenton Park [[Anglican Church of Australia|Anglican Church]] in the North of Perth<ref>{{Cite news|last=Wahlquist|first=Calla|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/sep/03/canning-byelection-andrew-hastie-deems-questions-on-family-and-religion-unacceptable|title=Canning byelection: Andrew Hastie deems questions on family and religion 'unacceptable'|date=2015-09-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and Crossroads Church in Canberra (an independent Evangelical Church) Hastie actually identifies with the Scottish Presbyterian faith in which he was raised<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-24/analysis-andrew-hastie-chau-chak-wing-complex-situation/9795766|title=Here's why Andrew Hastie named Chau Chak Wing in Parliament|last=Editor|first=Political|last2=Probyn|first2=rew|date=2018-05-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> and his family church in Mandurah today is part of the [[Presbyterian Church of Australia]]. Having rejected Christian belief in his teens for several years, Hastie has spoken of how only a theistic understanding of the world makes any sense of the death and suffering he has personally witnessed, that if he were \"a closed universe atheist, how bleak and senseless those deaths would be\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sheridan|first=Greg|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/inquirer/politicians-reveal-what-religion-means-to-them/news-story/ad54c5d1948393ae00cf20b9445372d1|title=In defence of Christianity|date=July 23, 2018|work=The Australian|access-date=February 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><br />\n\n==Honours and awards==\n<center>\n\n[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n\n[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|100px]]\n[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|100px]]\n\n[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|100px]]\n\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Active Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the AASM]] || [[Australian Active Service Medal]] || with clasp for [[Australian Active Service Medal#ICAT|ICAT]]\n|-\n|[[File:Afghanistan Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Afghanistan Medal for Australia]] || [[Afghanistan Medal (Australia)|Afghanistan Medal]] || Operation SLIPPER\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Service Medal ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the Australian Service Medal]] || [[Australian Service Medal]] || with clasp for CT/SR (Counter Terrorism / Special Recovery)<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://defence-honours-tribunal.gov.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SASR-Final-Report-Public-Release.pdf|title = INQUIRY INTO RECOGNITION OF AUSTRALIAN DEFENCE FORCE SERVICE FOR SPECIAL AIR SERVICE COUNTER TERRORIST AND SPECIAL RECOVERY DUTIES|date = 22 December 2009|accessdate = 20 September 2015|website = Defence Honours Tribunal|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Australian Defence Medal (Australia) ribbon.png|50px|Ribbon of the ADM]] || [[Australian Defence Medal]] ||\n|-\n|[[File:NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar v2.svg|50px]] || [[NATO Medal#Non-Article 5 Medal|NATO Medal for the Non-Article 5 ISAF Operation in Afghanistan]] || with clasp ''ISAF''\n|-\n|[[File:AUS Meritorious Unit Citation with Federation Star.png|50px|Meritorious Unit Citation]] || [[Meritorious Unit Citation]] with [[Federation Star]] || Awarded to Task Force 66 in the [[2015 Australia Day Honours]]\n|-\n||| [[Infantry Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n||| [[Army Combat Badge]] ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aph.gov.au/Senators_and_Members/Parliamentarian?MPID=260805 Parliamentary biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Don Randall]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Division of Canning|Canning]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Western Australia Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hastie, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Australian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian monarchists]]\n[[Category:Elliott School of International Affairs alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Canning]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Scots College]]\n[[Category:People from Wangaratta]]\n[[Category:Royal Military College, Duntroon graduates]]\n[[Category:University of New South Wales alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Erasmus Sydney", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommanding special forces troop in Afghanistan, 2013:relevant image added and name of target entered", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Hastie_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "List of public art in Conwy", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Wales Conwy locator map.svg|thumb|Map of Wales with Conwy highlighted]]\nThis is a '''list of public art in [[Conwy County Borough]]''', Wales. Conwy County Borough (''Welsh: Bwrdeistref Sirol Conwy'') is a [[Local government in Wales|unitary authority area]] in [[North Wales]] and includes the town of [[Conwy]]. This list applies only to works of [[public art]] on permanent display in an outdoor public space and does not, for example, include artworks in museums.\n\n==Abergele==\n{{Public art header|show_architect=no|show_material=yes|show_dimensions=yes|show_owner=no|show_wikidata=yes}}\n{{Public art row\n| image =\n| commonscat = \n| subject = War memorial\n| location = St Michael's Churchyard, [[Abergele]] \n| date = \n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = \n| type = Celtic cross \n| material = \n| dimensions = \n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = <ref>{{cite web |author=|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/31098 |title=War Memorials Register: Abergele \u2013 WW1 and WW2 Cross |date= |accessdate=12 March 2020|work=[[Imperial War Museum]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=|url= https://historypoints.org/index.php?page=abergele-war-memorial|title= Abergele war memorial|date=|accessdate= 12 March 2020|work=historypoints.org}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Public art row\n| image = Carreg Heddwch (&quot;Peace Stone&quot;) - geograph.org.uk - 1082884.jpg\n| commonscat = \n| subject = Peace Stone\n| location = Pensarn Beach, [[Abergele]] \n| date = 1995\n| show_artist= yes\n| artist = \n| type = Boulder \n| material = Stone\n| dimensions = \n| designation = \n| coordinates=\n| show_wikidata= yes\n| wikidata = \n| notes = Erected to mark the anniversary of the end of World War II\n}}\n{{Public art footer}}\n\n==Capel Curig==\n{{Public art header|show_