ger playing a flute |Otto E. Krueger, conductor]]\n\nThe '''Detroit News Orchestra''' was the world's first [[radio orchestra]], first broadcasting in 1922. It was composed of already-distinguished members of the [[Detroit Symphony Orchestra]], broadcasting from [[radio station]] [[WWJ (AM)|WWJ]] in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]<ref name=\"WWJ\">{{cite web |url=https://detroit.cbslocal.com/2010/06/24/wwj-firsts-timeline/ |title=\"WWJ Firsts\" Timeline |date=June 24, 2010 |publisher=[[WWJ-TV|WWJ - Channel CBS Detroit]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Kiska|2009|pages=2, 4, 105}}  The orchestra's broadcasts could be received across most of North America and even as far away as Hawaii.{{sfn|Kiska|2009|pages=2, 4, 105}}<ref name=OrchestraHeardHawaii/>\n\n== Background ==\nThe 16 members of the Detroit News Orchestra were drawn from the city's Detroit Symphony Orchestra, having previously achieved distinction as accomplished soloists. The orchestra broadcast on radio station [[WWJ (AM)|WWJ]], first debuting on May&nbsp;28, 1922.<ref name=\"WWJ\"/>{{sfn|Gavrilovich|McGraw|2006|page=62}} The broadcasts were sponsored by [[Detroit Bank & Trust Company|The Detroit Bank]] and could be received across half of North America.{{sfn|Detroit News|1922|page=12}} The Detroit News Orchestra was the first symphonic ensemble in the world organized specifically to play on radio.<ref name=\"WWJ\"/>{{sfn|Sies|2008|page=785}}{{sfn|Kane|Anzovin|Podell|1997|page=30}}\n\nThe Orchestra, sometimes referred to as the \"little symphony,\"<ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web |url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Stations/IDX/Station-Books-IDX/WWJ-The-Detroit-News-1922-OCR-Page-0023.pdf |title=The Detroit News Orchestra - American Radio History |page=22 |format=PDF |accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> played at the WWJ Detroit News radio studio from Monday through Friday at 7:00&nbsp;P.M., as well as at 2:00&nbsp;P.M. on Sundays.<ref name=BroadcastDays>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= First Radio Orchestra |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46691861/ |newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]] |page= 9  |location=Madison, Wisconsin|date= 23 July 1922|via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref> On occasion they also performed recitals for churches, schools, and other non-profit organization as a public relations outreach to their listeners.{{sfn|Fourth Estate|1922|page=26}} WWJ claims to be America's first [[Commercial broadcasting|commercial radio station]]{{sfn|Godfrey|Leigh|1998|page=426}} and was also the first radio station to broadcast regular [[radio news]].<ref name=\"WWJ\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailydetroit.com/2016/09/28/10-impressive-detroit-firsts/ |date=September 28, 2016\n|first1=Ardelia |last1=Lee |title=10 Impressive Detroit Firsts |publisher=[[Daily Detroit]] |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Listeners in Hawaii ==\nOn November&nbsp;23, 1922, at thirty minutes past midnight, the Detroit News Orchestra played the waltz [[Three O'Clock in the Morning|\"Three O'Clock in the Morning]]\" in studio in the [[The Detroit News|Detroit News]] building. The transmission was received clearly at 6:30&nbsp;P.M. local time in the [[Hawaiian Islands]] by A. F. Costa, the postmaster at [[Wailuku, Hawaii]]. Several people listened to the program in its entirety at the Wailuku post office, over 4,400 miles (7,100&nbsp;km) from Detroit. The notes of the music transmitted from the Detroit News radio station in Michigan took about one fiftieth of a second to arrive in Hawaii.<ref name=OrchestraHeardHawaii>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Distance Records Broken When Hawaii Picks Up Detroit News |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46742850/  |newspaper= [[The Paducah Sun-Democrat]] |page= 5  |location=Paducah, Kentucky|date= 25 January 1923 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{open access}} }}</ref>\n\n== Ensemble ==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 700\n | image1 = Detroit News symphonic ensembel 1922.jpg\n | alt1 = Detroit News Orchestra\n | caption1 = <center>Detroit News Orchestra players\n | image2 = WWJ range.jpg\n | alt2 = Map of station WWJ broadcast range\n | caption2 = <center>WWJ broadcast range\n\n | footer = \n}}\n{{clear}}\nList of personnel of the [[musical ensemble]].{{sfn|Detroit News|1922|page=21}}  \n* [[Otto E Krueger]] \u2013 [[conductor]]{{efn-ua|He was a well known member of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra, and also was conductor of the [[Federal Music Project|Works Projects Administration Orchestra]].{{sfn|Detroit News|1922|page=21}} {{sfn|Clemens|2008|page=67}}}}\n* [[Maurice Warner]] \u2013 [[violinist]] and [[Concertmeister]]{{efn-ua|\"Concertmeister; member of [[New York Symphony Orchestra]] on European tour, and soloist throughout United States and Canada; first violin,\nDetroit Symphony Orchestra\"<ref name=\"Radio\"/>}}\n* [[Herman Goldstein (violinist)|Herman Goldstein]] \u2013 violinist  \n* [[LeRoy Hancock]] \u2013 violinist \n* [[Armand Hebert]] \u2013 violinist \n* [[Valbert P. Coffey]] \u2013  [[pianist]] \n* [[Frederick Broeder]] \u2013 [[cellist]] \n* [[Eugene W Braunsdorf]] \u2013 [[Bass violin|bass]] soloist  \n* [[Thomas J Byrne]] \u2013 [[oboe]] soloist  \n* [[R. M. Arey]] \u2013 [[clarinet]]ist   \n* [[Vincenzo Pezzi]] \u2013 [[bassoon]]ist \n* [[Albert Stagliamo]] \u2013 [[horn]] player  \n* [[Edward Clarke (trumpeter)|Edward Clarke]] \u2013 [[trumpeter]]\n* [[Floyd O Hara]] \u2013 trumpeter \n* [[Max Smith (trombonist )|Max Smith]] \u2013 [[trombonist]]\n* [[Arthur Cooper (percussionist)|Arthur Cooper]] \u2013 [[xylophone]] player{{sfn|Fuller|1997|page=422}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1922 in radio]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Commons category|Detroit News Orchestra}} \n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwQ8sfBoDOwC&pg=PA67 |title=The Works Progress Administration in Detroit |first1=Elizabeth |last1=Clemens |location=Charleston, South Carolina|isbn=9780738551814 |type=Paperback |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |date=March 31, 2008 |series=Images of America |page=67 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Detroit News|first= |title= WWJ\u2014The Detroit News, The History of Radiophone Broadcasting  | url= https://www.google.com/books/edition/WWJ_The_Detroit_News/h3xIAAAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22Detroit+News+Orchestra%22&printsec=frontcover |date=1922|location=Detroit, Michigan|publisher=[[The Evening News Association]] |newspaper=[[Detroit News]] |quote=}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Fourth Estate |first=  |title=Fourth Estate  | url= |date=1922|publisher=[[HarperCollins|Fourth Estate Publishing Company]] |quote=  }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Fuller |first=George Newman |title=[[Michigan History]] |volume=44  | url= |date=1997|publisher= Michigan History Division of the [[Michigan Secretary of State|Department of State]] |quote=  }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Gavrilovich|first=Peter, Editor |first2=Bill, Editor |last2=McGraw|title= The Detroit Almanac: 300 Years of Life in the Motor City  | url= https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=rBoOAQAAMAAJ&dq=Gavrilovich%2C+Peter+%282006%29.+The+Detroit+Almanac.+Detroit+Free+Press.+%22Detroit+News+Orchestra%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Detroit+News+Orchestra%22 |date=2006|location=Detroit, Michigan|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]] \n|edition=2, reprint |isbn=0937247480 |id=ISBN 9780937247488}}\n*{{cite book |title=Historical Dictionary of American Radio |last1=Godfrey |first1=Donald G.|first2=Frederic |last2=Leigh |page=426 |location=Westport, Connecticut |date=January 1, 1998|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |isbn=9780313296369 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last2= Anzovin |first2= Steven |first1=Joseph Nathan |last1=Kane |first3=Janet |last3=Podell  |edition=5th, revised |title=Famous First Facts: A Record of First Happenings, Discoveries, and Inventions in American History |series=Famous First Facts |isbn=0824209303 |id=ISBN 9780824209308  | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=GpEYAAAAIAAJ&dq=Anzovin,+Steven+(1997).+Famous+First+Facts,+fifth+edition.&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6tPC5oJ3oAhVUVs0KHUDmA8EQ6AEwAHoECAEQAg |date=1997|location=New York|publisher=The [[H. W. Wilson Company]] |quote= }}\n*{{cite book |pages=2, 4, 105 |title=A Newscast for the Masses: The History of Detroit Television News |first1=Tim |last1=Kiska |date=February 24, 2009 |isbn=9780814333020 |location=Detroit, Michigan |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last= Sies |first= Luther F. |title= Encyclopedia of American Radio, 1920\u20131960 |volume=2  | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=AWY5AQAAIAAJ&q=%22The+Detroit+News+Orchestra,+conducted+by+Otto+E.+Krueger,+was+organized+by+WWJ+(Detroit,+MI).%22&dq=%22The+Detroit+News+Orchestra,+conducted+by+Otto+E.+Krueger,+was+organized+by+WWJ+(Detroit,+MI).%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjXsKOZxJroAhVQeKwKHTUMD7cQ6AEwA3oECAIQAg |date=2008|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |location=Jefferson, North Carolina |edition=2 revised |id=ISBN 0786429429 |isbn=9780786429424 |quote= }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Culture of Detroit]]\n[[Category:Orchestras based in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "7&6=thirteen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detroit_News_Orchestra"}
{"title_page": "2003 24 Hours of Le Mans", "text_new": "{{short description|71st Grand Prix of Endurance}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Le Mans Races\n| Previous = 2002\n| Current = 2003\n| Next = 2004\n}}\n[[File:2003 Bentley Speed 8.jpg|thumb|250px|The race-winning {{Abbr|No.|Car number}} 7 [[Bentley Speed 8]], driven at the 2009 [[Goodwood Festival of Speed]].]]\nThe '''71st 24 Hours of Le Mans''' ({{lang-fr|71<sup>e</sup> 24 Heures du Mans|link=no}}) was an [[Endurance racing (motorsport)|automobile endurance race]] held for [[Le Mans Prototype]] and [[Grand tourer|Grand Touring]] cars from 14 to 15 June 2003 at the [[Circuit de la Sarthe]] at [[Le Mans, France]] before approximately 220,000 people. It was the 71st edition of the 24 Hour race, as organised by the automotive group, the [[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]] (ACO) since [[1923 24 Hours of Le Mans|1923]]. Unlike other events, it was not a part of any endurance motor racing championship. A test day was held seven weeks prior to the race on 4 May.\n\nA [[Bentley Speed 8]] shared by Dane [[Tom Kristensen (racing driver)|Tom Kristensen]], Italian [[Rinaldo Capello]] and Englishman [[Guy Smith (racing driver)|Guy Smith]] started from the [[pole position]] after Kristensen set the fastest overall lap time in the second qualifying session. The team won the race, two laps ahead of the sister Bentley of [[Mark Blundell]], [[David Brabham]] and [[Johnny Herbert]] in second place. It was Capello and Smith's first Le Mans victory and Kristensen's fifth. This was the sixth overall victory for Bentley, and their first since the [[1930 24 Hours of Le Mans|1930 edition]]. The overall podium was completed by [[Champion Racing]]'s [[Audi R8 (LMP)|Audi R8]] of [[JJ Lehto]], [[Emanuele Pirro]] and [[Stefan Johansson]], which won the Le Mans Prototype 900 (LMP900) category from [[Team Goh|Audi Sport Japan Team Goh]]'s entry driven by [[Seiji Ara]], [[Jan Magnussen]] and [[Marco Werner]].\n\nA No\u00ebl del Bello Racing [[Reynard Motorsport|Reynard]] 2KQ-LM driven by [[Jean-Luc Maury-Laribi\u00e8re]], Christophe Pillon and [[Didier Andr\u00e9]] won the Le Mans Prototype 675 (LMP675) class, 32 laps ahead of the second-placed RN Motorsport [[DBA4 03S]]-[[Gibson Technology|Zytek]] car of [[John Nielsen (racing driver)|John Nielsen]], [[Casper Elgaard]] and [[Hayanari Shimoda]]. The [[Prodrive|Veloqx Prodrive Racing]] team took the victory in the Le Mans Grand Touring Sport (LMGTS) class with drivers [[Jamie Davies]], [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Enge]], [[Peter Kox]] in a [[Ferrari 550|Ferrari 550-GTS Maranello]], securing Ferrari its first GT win since the [[1981 24 Hours of Le Mans|1981 race]]. [[Pratt & Miller|Corvette Racing]] completed the category podium positions a further ten laps behind in second and third with the No. 50 and No. 53 [[Chevrolet Corvette C5-R|C5-R]]<nowiki/>s. [[Porsche in motorsport|Porsche]] took the first six positions in the Le Mans Grand Touring (LMGT) category with an [[Alex Job Racing]] [[Porsche 911 GT3|911-GT3 RS]] of [[Sascha Maassen]], [[Emmanuel Collard]] and [[Lucas Luhr]] winning on the team's debut appearance at Le Mans.\n\n==Background and regulation changes==\n\nThe 2003 [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] was the 71st edition of the race and took place at the {{Convert|8.482|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Circuit de la Sarthe]] from 14 to 15 June.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11986922.audi-and-bentley-gear-up-for-monumental-le-mans-battle-famous-endurance-test-is-still-worlds-greatest-race/|title=Audi and Bentley gear up for monumental Le Mans battle Famous endurance test is still world's greatest race|last=McGill|first=Jim|date=14 June 2003|work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|access-date=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617070022/https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11986922.audi-and-bentley-gear-up-for-monumental-le-mans-battle-famous-endurance-test-is-still-worlds-greatest-race/|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The automotive journalist [[Charles Faroux]] proposed the race to Georges Durand, the president of the [[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]] (ACO), and the industrialist Emile Coquile for a test of vehicle reliability and fuel-efficiency, which was first held in [[1923 24 Hours of Le Mans|1923]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lemans.org/en/news/commemoration-of-the-90th-anniversary-of-the-le-mans-24-hours/9734|title=Commemoration of the 90th anniversary of the Le Mans 24 Hours|date=1 February 2013|publisher=[[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602163444/https://www.lemans.org/en/news/commemoration-of-the-90th-anniversary-of-the-le-mans-24-hours/9734|archive-date=2 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"RTLMHistory\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/news/a13113/le-mans-how-it-began/|title=Le Mans \u2014 How It Began|date=16 May 2007|website=[[Road & Track]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911022850/http://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/news/a13113/le-mans-how-it-began/|archive-date=11 September 2015|url-status=live|access-date=2 June 2019}}</ref> The 24 Hours of Le Mans is considered one of the world's most prestigious motor races and is part of the [[Triple Crown of Motorsport]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/luxury/travel/le-mans-24-hours-attend-style/|title=An insider's guide to the Le Mans 24hours: how to experience the ultimate endurance race in style|last=Hargreaves|first=Eilidh|date=13 May 2019|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=2 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530203845/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/luxury/travel/le-mans-24-hours-attend-style/|archive-date=30 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2002 24 Hours of Le Mans|2002 race]], the ACO reduced the overall amount of horsepower for the Le Mans Grand Touring Prototype (LMGTP), Le Mans Prototype 900 (LMP900), Le Mans Prototype 675 (LMP675), Le Mans Grand Touring Sports (LMGTS) and LMGT (Le Mans Grand Touring) categories by 10 per cent. It allowed carbon fibre chassis to be introduced in the LMGTS class and permitted original [[Automatic transmission|automatic]] and [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic gearboxes]] to be retained in a homologated road vehicle entered in the LMGTS and LMGT categories. [[Restrictor plate|Air restrictors]] were installed on every engine and [[Boost gauge|boost pressures]] were altered in an attempt to create a parity of performance within all four categories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mulsannescorner.com/ACOrglement2003annexea.pdf|title=Competitor Information: 2003 Regulations: Appendix A|date=3 October 2002|publisher=[[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030315135624/http://www.mulsannescorner.com/ACOrglement2003annexea.pdf|archive-date=15 March 2003|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> Drivers were told at a public meeting that they were barred from putting two wheels of a car over the white line denoting the boundaries of the circuit and onto the [[Curb|kerbing]]; otherwise, they would incur a stop-and-go penalty that would increase in severity if the transgression was repeated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans146.htm|title=Le Mans \u2013 White Lines (Kerbs) & Things|last=Legangneux|first=David|date=4 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617101420/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans146.htm|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Entries==\nThe ACO received 72 applications (31 for the Prototype classes and 41 for the Grand Touring categories) by the deadline for entries on 20 February 2003. It granted 50 invitations to the race and entries were divided between the LMP900, LMGTP, LMP675, LMGTS and LMGT classes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.speedtv.com/articles/auto/roadracing/5373/|title=Le Mans Accepts 72 Entries for 24 Hours|date=4 March 2003|publisher=[[Speed (TV channel)|Speed]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030331132917/http://www.speedtv.com/articles/auto/roadracing/5373/|archive-date=31 March 2003|url-status=dead|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Automatic entries===\nSix automatic entry invitations were earned by teams of two cars that won their class in the 2002 24 Hours of Le Mans or in the [[2002 American Le Mans Series]] (ALMS) season-closing round, the [[2002 Petit Le Mans|Petit Le Mans]] at [[Road Atlanta]], designated a qualifying race by the ACO as part of an agreement with the ALMS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/alms/news/131945/1/le-mans-in-2003-beckons-for-petit-winners|title=Le Mans in 2003 beckons for Petit winners|last=Wilkins|first=Robert|date=17 October 2002|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617175358/https://www.crash.net/alms/news/131945/1/le-mans-in-2003-beckons-for-petit-winners|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=dead|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> As entries were designated for teams, the squads were not allowed to change their cars from the previous year to the next. They were permitted to change category provided there was no change in the make of car and the ACO consented to the switch.<ref name=\"2003Regs\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lemans.org/sport/pdf/2003_24H_REGULATIONS_GB.pdf|title=24 Heures du Mans 2003: Supplementary Regulations|date=18 December 2002|publisher=Automobile Club de l'Ouest|pages=6\u20137 & 11\u201312|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030315065630/http://www.lemans.org/sport/pdf/2003_24H_REGULATIONS_GB.pdf|archive-date=15 March 2003|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> The teams who received an automatic entry based on victory in their class at the 2002 24 Hours of Le Mans were [[Joest Racing|Audi Sport Team Joest]] in both of the LMP categories, [[Pratt & Miller|Corvette Racing]] for the LMGTS class and [[The Racer's Group]] in the LMGT category. Audi Sport North America and Corvette also earned berths for securing victories in their respective classes at the Petit Le Mans and [[Alex Job Racing]] in the LMGT category.<ref name=2003Regs/> However, Audi chose not to accept its automatic invitations after the manufacturer announced the withdrawal of its factory operations and forwent its defense of the overall victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/21307|title=Audi boss confirms Le Mans pull-out|date=22 November 2002|website=[[Autosport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617202528/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/21307|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Entry list===\nOn 25 March 2003, the selection committee of the ACO announced the full 50-car entry list for Le Mans, plus six reserves. An equal amount of Prototype and GT cars composed the field, representing 22 different makes of car (14 in the GT classes and 8 in the Prototype categories).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autoweek.com/article/car-news/fifty-selected-cars-announced-le-mans|title=Fifty selected cars announced for Le Mans|date=25 March 2003|website=[[Autoweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617073838/https://autoweek.com/article/car-news/fifty-selected-cars-announced-le-mans|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> After a protest was raised by [[Larbre Comp\u00e9tition]] owner [[Jack Leconte]] and alpine skier [[Luc Alphand]] over their respective teams being allocated one entry,<ref name=ACOEntriesPresident>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=64413&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|title=A propos de la s\u00e9lection pour les 24 Heures : 3 questions \u00e0 Michel Cosson: \" On a pris les cinquante meilleurs \"|last=Virfeu|first=Jean-Claude|date=1 April 2003|work=[[Ouest-France]]|access-date=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050710115137/http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=64413&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|archive-date=10 July 2005|url-status=dead|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans050.htm|title=Following the LM Entry Saga|date=2 April 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617182926/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans050.htm|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref> Michel Cosson, the president of the ACO, said that entries selected appeared to be of high quality and the automotive group wanted the field to be heterogeneousness. He stated it was not the right way to select entries for the race but disliked those who sought to spoil the excitement of the event.<ref name=ACOEntriesPresident/>\n\n===Bio-ethanol car===\nTeam Nasamax, an operation based in [[Sittingbourne]], England, entered the first [[Renewable fuels|renewable-fuelled]] sports prototype racing car at the Le Mans event to increase awareness of renewable fuels.<ref name=NasamaxCar /><ref name=CrashNasamax>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140187/1/green-fuel-to-challenge-for-pole-at-le-mans|title='Green fuel' to challenge for pole at Le Mans|date=5 February 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618082820/https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140187/1/green-fuel-to-challenge-for-pole-at-le-mans|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> The car, called the Reynard 01Q, ran a {{Convert|2.65|l||abbr=on}} [[Cosworth]] [[V8 engine|V8]] [[Turbocharger|turbocharged engine]] on [[Ethanol fuel|bio-ethanol fuel]],<ref name=NasamaxCar/> which does not release carbon dioxide into the atmosphere because it is produced from crops.<ref name=CrashNasamax/> The car's fuel systems and inlet air system were modified to allow for the efficient combustion of fuel. An alternative [[exhaust system]] was built and the housing and vanes on the turbocharger were altered.<ref name=NasamaxCar>{{Cite web|url=https://www.just-auto.com/analysis/bio-ethanol-at-le-mans-raising-the-profile-of-renewable-fuels_id87084.aspx|title=Bio-ethanol at Le Mans \u2013 raising the profile of \u2018renewable\u2019 fuels|last=Wagstaff|first=Ian|date=26 June 2003|publisher=Just-Auto.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617192224/https://www.just-auto.com/analysis/bio-ethanol-at-le-mans-raising-the-profile-of-renewable-fuels_id87084.aspx|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Testing==\nA mandatory pre-Le Mans testing day split into two daytime sessions of four hours each was held at the circuit on 4 May, involving all 50 entries as well as all six reserve cars.<ref name=\"2003Regs\" /> The weather was clear and dry.<ref name=Crash4MayTest>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140233/1/prodrive-set-the-gts-class-pace|title=Prodrive set the GTS class pace|last=Wilkins|first=Robert|date=5 May 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618082825/https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140233/1/prodrive-set-the-gts-class-pace|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Bentley was fastest with a lap of 3 minutes and 34.820 seconds set by [[Tom Kristensen (racing driver)|Tom Kristensen]] in the {{Abbr|No.|Car number}} 7 [[Bentley Speed 8|Speed 8]] in the final minutes of testing. [[Jan Magnussen]] was the fastest of the privateer [[Audi R8 (LMP)|Audi R8s]] for [[Team Goh]] in second place and the No. 7 Bentley was third. The Audi Sport UK and the [[Champion Racing]] entries completed the top five overall cars.<ref name=MCOM4MayTest>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentleys-audis-lead-the-way-in-preliminaries/121801/|title=Bentleys, Audis lead the way in preliminaries|date=4 May 2003|publisher=[[motorsport.com]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618082821/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentleys-audis-lead-the-way-in-preliminaries/121801/|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Late in testing, [[Frank Biela]] lost control on a patch of oil laid by a [[Pagani Zonda]] at the Porsche Curves, crashing into a barrier at {{Convert|120|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and damaging the right-rear corner of the Audi Sport UK car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/22858|title=Biela unhurt in major accident|date=6 May 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618082821/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/22858|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=DSCTestRoundUp>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans107.htm|title=Le Mans Test Day Round Up|date=5 May 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617113738/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/news/lemans/2003lemans/lemans107.htm|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> The No. 26 RN Motorsport [[DBA4 03S]]-[[Gibson Technology|Zytek]] car led in LMP675 with a 3 minutes and 47.708 seconds lap, followed by the No. 29 No\u00ebl del Bello Racing Reynard 2KQ-LM and the No. 27 [[Intersport Racing]] [[MG-Lola EX257]]<nowiki/>vehicles.<ref name=MCOM4MayTest/> [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Enge]]'s No. 88 [[Prodrive]] [[Ferrari 550|Ferrari 550-GTS Maranello]] recorded the fastest lap in LMGTS at 3 minutes and 57.180 seconds, the sister No. 80 car of [[Kelvin Burt]] placed second and [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Policand]] completed a top-three sweep of Ferraris in the class in the No. 72 Luc Alphand Aventures entry.<ref name=Crash4MayTest/><ref name=DSCTestRoundUp/> [[J\u00f6rg Bergmeister]]'s No. 81 The Racer's Group [[Porsche 911 GT3]]-RS led the LMGT category at 4 minutes and 8.636 seconds and the No. 93 [[Alex Job Racing]] car of [[Sascha Maassen]] was second.<ref name=MCOM4MayTest/>\n\n==Qualifying==\nEight hours of qualifying divided into four two-hour sessions were available to all the entrants on 11 and 12 June. During the sessions, all entrants were required to set a time within 110 per cent of the fastest lap established by the fastest vehicle in each of the four categories to qualify for the race.<ref name=\"2003Regs\" /> The weather was overcast and humid,<ref name=AutosportQ1>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23335|title=Qualifying 1: Bentleys dominate|date=11 June 2003|website=Autosport|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/K7tbJ|archivedate=18 June 2019|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> and teams focused on [[Racing setup|car setup]].<ref name=MCOMQ1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-fast-for-first-qualifying-part-one/126445/|title=Bentley fast for first qualifying, part one|date=12 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Bentley led early on with a flying lap from [[Mark Blundell]]'s No. 8 car, followed by Kristensen and [[Johnny Herbert]], who bettered his effort. Ultimately, Blundell went to the top with a lap of 3 minutes and 35.321 seconds. Kristensen's No. 7 vehicle was a quarter of a second slower in second and [[Jan Magnussen]] was the fastest Audi [[Privateer (motorsport)|privateer]] in third.<ref name=DSCWedQualiLMP>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/wednesday_900675.htm|title=Wednesday Qualifying Report \u2013 Prototypes|date=11 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618135233/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/wednesday_900675.htm|archive-date=18 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> [[Jan Lammers]]' No. 15 [[Racing for Holland]] Dome S101 improved on each of his timed laps to finish fourth,<ref name=AutosportQ1/> and [[JJ Lehto]] of Champion Racing rounded out the top five.<ref name=DSCWedQualiLMP/> [[John Nielsen (racing driver)|John Nielsen]] carried RN Motorsport's DBA4 03S-Zytek car to provisional pole position in LMP675 with a time of 3 minutes and 45.243 seconds, eight seconds ahead of the Intersport and [[Durango (racing team)|Automotive Durango SRL]] teams.<ref name=DSCWedQualiLMP/> A lap of 3 minutes and 55.613 seconds set with five minutes to go put [[Oliver Gavin]]'s No. 50 [[Chevrolet Corvette C5-R]] at the top of the LMGTS category and he demoted Enge's Prodrive Ferrari to second. [[Johnny O'Connell]]'s No. 53 car was third after a lap recorded in the final ten minutes. Alex Job Racing's Porsche of Maassen topped the timing charts in LMGT, almost three seconds faster than [[Timo Bernhard]]'s The Racer's Group car and another seven-tenths ahead of [[Marc Lieb]]'s No. 87 Orbit entry.<ref name=DSCWedQualiGT>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/wednesday_gtgts.htm|title=Wednesday Qualifying Report - GTS & GT|date=11 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605125143/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/wednesday_gtgts.htm|archive-date=5 June 2019|url-status=dead|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Separate spins from Chris McMurry, [[Kevin Buckler]], [[Peter Kox]] and [[Andrew Bagnall]] did not disrupt the session.<ref name=\"MCOMQ1\"/>\n\nWednesday night's qualifying session was held with lower asphalt temperatures and teams performed scheduled simulation runs to see how their cars would behave on heavy fuel loads and worn tyres under darkness in its final 75 minutes.<ref name=MCOMQuali2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/kristensen-turns-two-quick-laps-to-take-provisional-pole/126446/|title=Kristensen turns two quick laps to take provisional pole|date=12 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|url-status=live|access-date=18 June 2003}}</ref> A lack of slower traffic and better [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]] allowed Kristensen to displace Blundell as the fastest overall and twice improve the overall fastest lap to 3 minutes and 32.843 seconds, followed by [[David Brabham]]'s sister No. 8 Bentley in second and Biela's No. 10 Audi third. [[Emanuele Pirro]] put the No. 6 Audi fourth as Lammers fell to fifth.<ref name=MCOMQuali2/> [[Marco Werner]]'s Team Goh Audi ran into a [[Run-off area|gravel trap]]; he continued driving.<ref name=DSCWedQualiLMP/> In LMP675, Nielsen improved the RN Motorsport Zytek car's lap by a second to 3 minutes and 44.343 and increased its advantage over the Intersport team to almost ten seconds.<ref name=MCOMQuali2/><ref name=AutosportQ2>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23337|title=Qualifying 2: Bentleys on top again|date=11 June 2003|website=Autosport|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/JdP58|archivedate=18 June 2019|access-date=18 June 2019}}</ref> 75 minutes into the session, the Team Bucknum Racing Pilbeam-JPX MP91 car had an engine fault at Indianapolis corner and laid oil on the track. [[Motorsport marshal|Marshals]] took 20 minutes to dry the spilled oil and qualifying resumed.<ref name=DSCWedQualiLMP/><ref name=MCOMQuali2/> Enge's Prodrive Ferrari led from the start in the LMGTS class. He improved on Corvette Racing's lap from the first session to a 3 minutes and 53.278 seconds. Maassen in the Alex Job Racing Porsche remained at the top of the LMGT category after a session-long battle with Bernhard.<ref name=DSCWedQualiGT/><ref name=AutosportQ2/> Bagnall lost control of the Seikel Motorsport Porsche and got beached in a gravel trap.<ref name=MCOMQuali2/> David Warnock's PK Sport car sustained [[Tie rod|track rod]] damage in a collision with a Prototype in the Dunlop [[Chicane]].<ref name=DSCWedQualiGT/>\n\nThursday's first qualifying session was stopped after seven minutes because of an accident.<ref name=\"MCOMQ3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-remains-fastest-on-second-qualifying-part-one/126537/|title=Bentley remains fastest on second qualifying, part one|date=13 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|url-status=live|accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref> [[Jamie Campbell-Walter]] spun a [[Lister Storm LMP]] car after hitting a bump on the exit of the Dunlop Esses.<ref name=ListerWD>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68224|title=It was my fault says Campbell-Walter|date=13 June 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030915024448/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68224|archive-date=15 September 2003|url-status=dead|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> He crashed backwards against a left-hand side barrier at the Dunlop Curve at {{Convert|146|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"MCOMQ3\" /><ref name=DSCThuQualiLMP>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Thursday Qualifying Report \u2013 900 & 675|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/thursday_900675.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=12 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618193748/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/thursday_900675.htm|archivedate=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The impact was measured at {{Convert|14|g0||abbr=on}},<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiLMP\" /> and marshals and safety teams spent ten minutes extricating Campbell-Walter from the car. They removing a section of carbon fibre bodywork trapping his legs and then put him into an ambulance.<ref name=ListerWD/><ref name=\"DSCThuQualiLMP\" /> The Lister Storm LMP car was later withdrawn due to a lack of spare parts.<ref name=ListerWD/> Later, [[Ian Khan]]'s [[Thierry Perrier]] Porsche engine failed and laid oil on the circuit at the Dunlop Chicane. Robin Liddell was caught out, hit the oil and spun into a gravel trap. At the same time, Roland Bervill\u00e9 spun, hit a barrier with his front-right hand corner and broke the [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]] on the T2M Motorsport car, temporarily stopping the session.<ref name=\"MCOMQ3\" /><ref name=\"DSCThuQualiGT\">{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Thursday Qualifying Report \u2013 GTS & GT|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/thursday_gtgts.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=12 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618193748/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/thursday_gtgts.htm|archivedate=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Herbert's No. 8 Bentley led the session with a lap of 3 minutes and 35.126 seconds. It remained in second position on the provisional grid. Magnussen used lower air temperatures to improve the Team Goh Audi's lap and pass Lammers for third at the close of the session. Lehto bettered the Champion Racing's entry to maintain fourth.<ref name=\"MCOMQ3\" /> Although the RN Motorsport Zytek car did not better its lap, it remained on provisional pole in LMP675, while the Intersport Lola vehicle improved by more than five seconds to remain in second in class.<ref name=\"MCOMQ3\" /> Enge's lap from the second session kept him at the top of LMGTS as [[Darren Turner]] in the sister Prodrive Ferrari moved ahead of the No. 50 Corvette for second. Alex Job Racing continued to lead the LMGT class due to its lap from the previous day.<ref name=\"AutosportQ3\">{{cite web|title=Qualifying 3: No change at the top|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23356|work=Autosport|date=12 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.is/8PMj4|archivedate=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe final session was used to test cars under race conditions and saw more incidents. [[Thomas Erdos]] in the Graham Nash Motorsport [[Saleen S7|Saleen S7-R]] stopped on his out-lap in a gravel trap at the Dunlop Chicane, requiring recovery from trackside marshals. Gavin Pickering's Rachel Welter WR-Peugeot car stopped at the exit of the pit lane with bodywork flailing from it.<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiGT\" /><ref name=\"MCOMQ4\">{{cite web|title=Bentleys on front row for 24 Hours of Le Mans|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentleys-on-front-row-for-24-hours-of-le-mans/126547/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=14 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Kristensen allowed his co-drivers [[Rinaldo Capello]] and [[Guy Smith (racing driver)|Guy Smith]] to become familiar with the No. 7 Bentley,<ref name=\"EurosportThuQualifying\">{{cite web|last=Thomas|first=Barry|title=Bentley Secure Front Row|url=http://eurosport.com/home/pages/V3/L0/S76/E5522/sport_Lng0_Spo76_Evt5522_Sto444685.shtml|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|date=13 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030708222404/http://eurosport.com/home/pages/V3/L0/S76/E5522/sport_Lng0_Spo76_Evt5522_Sto444685.shtml|archivedate=8 July 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> which led the session and secured the pole position through Kristensen's lap from the second qualifying session.<ref name=\"AutosportQ4\">{{cite web|title=Final qualifying: Kristensen holds pole|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23358|work=Autosport|date=12 June 2003|accessdate=18 June 2019|archiveurl=https://archive.is/0keXN|archivedate=18 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Herbert improved the sister No. 8 Bentley's lap on his second attempt by one-tenth of a second; it remained in second overall due to slower traffic delaying it.<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiLMP\" /><ref name=\"EurosportThuQualifying\" /> Audi were unable to challenge though Biela's Audi Sport UK entry improved its fastest lap to take third and Magnussen qualified the Team Goh car fifth; they were separated by Lammers' Racing for Holland Dome car. Intersport's MG-Lola vehicle bettered its lap but it was not fast enough to displace the RN Motorsport Zytek car, which was impaired by a broken throttle linkage, from the top of the LMP675 category and was two seconds slower.<ref name=\"AutosportQ4\" /> The GT categories remained mostly the same with the second session lap of Enge's No. 88 Prodrive Ferrari in LMGTS class again not being improved upon as his teammate Turner moved to within four-tenths of a second.<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiGT\" /> Porsche took the first three positions in the LMGT category,<ref name=\"AutosportQ4\" /> with [[Lucas Luhr]]'s Alex Job Racing car resetting the category lap record to a 4 minutes and 6.984 seconds and Bernhard's The Racer's Group entry was four-hundredths of a seconds behind in second.<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiGT\" />\n\n===Qualifying results===\n[[Pole position]] winners in each class are indicated in '''bold''' and by a {{Double-dagger}} The fastest time set by each entry is denoted in gray.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Class\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Team\n! scope=\"col\" | Car\n! scope=\"col\" | {{nowrap|Day 1}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{nowrap|Day 2}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Gap|Gap to the fastest driver}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |'''1'''\n|'''LMGTP'''\n|align=center|'''7'''\n|[[Apex Motorsport|'''Team Bentley''']]\n|'''[[Bentley Speed 8]]'''\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|'''3:32.843'''\n|align=center|'''3:33.158'''\n|'''\u2014'''{{Double-dagger}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n|LMGTP\n|align=center| 8\n|[[Apex Motorsport|Team Bentley]]\n|[[Bentley Speed 8]]\n|align=center|3:35.222\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|3:35.098\n|<nowiki>+2.255</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |'''3'''\n|'''LMP900'''\n|align=center|'''10'''\n|'''[[Audi]] Sport UK'''\n|[[Audi R8 (LMP)|'''Audi R8''']]\n|