e=\"row\" | 41\n|LMGT\n|align=center| 95\n|[[Risi Competizione]]\n|[[Ferrari 360 Modena]] GT\n|align=center|4:18.268\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:15.342\n|<nowiki>+42.499</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 42\n|LMGT\n|align=center|83\n|[[Seikel Motorsport]]\n|[[Porsche 911 GT3]]-RS\n|align=center|4:18.592\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:16.792\n|<nowiki>+43.949</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 43\n|LMGT\n|align=center|92\n| Dewalt Racesports Salisbury\n|[[TVR Tuscan Speed 6|TVR Tuscan]] T400R\n|align=center|4:19.378\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:16.872\n|<nowiki>+44.029</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 44\n| LMGT\n|align=center| 70\n|[[JMB Racing]]\n|[[Ferrari 360 Modena]] GT\n|align=center|4:18.161\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:17.138\n|<nowiki>+44.295</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 45\n|LMGT\n|align=center|75\n|[[Thierry Perrier]]\n|[[Porsche 911 GT3]]-RS\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:18.579\n|align=center|17:59.928\n|<nowiki>+45.736</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 46\n|LMGT\n|align=center| 85\n| ST Team Orange [[Spyker Cars|Spyker]]\n|[[Spyker C8]] Double-12R\n|align=center| 4:21.473\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:18.887\n|<nowiki>+46.044</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 47\n|LMGT\n|align=center|99\n| XL Racing\n|[[Ferrari 550 Maranello]]\n|align=center|4:21.459\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:20.245\n|<nowiki>+47.402</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 48\n|LMGT\n|align=center| 91\n|Dewalt Racesport Salisbury\n|[[TVR Tuscan Speed 6|TVR Tuscan]] T400R\n|align=center|4:23.425\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:20.288\n|<nowiki>+47.445</nowiki>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 49\n|LMGT\n|align=center|84\n|T2M Motorsport\n|[[Porsche 911 GT3]]-RS\n|align=center style=background:#ddd;|4:26.499\n|align=center|22:10.735\n|<nowiki>+53.656</nowiki>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" |{{center|{{small|''Source:<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Mans 24 Hours (Qualifying Results)|url=http://www.racingsportscars.com/results/qualifying/Le_Mans-2003-06-15.html|publisher=Racing Sports Cars|accessdate=19 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161001020857/http://www.racingsportscars.com/results/qualifying/Le_Mans-2003-06-15.html|archivedate=1 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>''}}}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|}\n\n'''Notes:'''\n*{{note|1|1}} \u2014 The No. 20 [[Lister Storm LMP]] was withdrawn due to accident damage in the third qualifying session.<ref name=\"DSCThuQualiLMP\" />\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nThe drivers took to the track at 09:00 [[Central European Summer Time]] ([[UTC+02:00]]) for a 45-minute warm-up session in overcast and cool weather.<ref name=\"2003Regs\" /><ref name=\"AutosportWarmUp\">{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23389|title=Warm-up: Blundell fastest|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623082023/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23389|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref> Bentley continued to be fastest overall as Blundell's No. 8 car recorded a lap of 3 minutes and 35.319 seconds. He was 2.615 seconds faster than the No. 7 Bentley in second place. The Audi Sport UK R8 was third, Champion Racing was fourth and the Racing for Holland Home car rounded out the top five. RN Motorsport's Zytek car continued to lead in LMP675, as the No. 50 Corvette led the LMGTS field and The Racer's Group Porsche led in LMGT.<ref name=AutosportWarmUp/> Shortly after the session commenced, [[Romain Dumas]]' Team Nasamax Reynard had an ignition problem caused by a heat leak at the right of the engine's [[cylinder bank]], significantly damaging its engine compartment and required a significant change of car components.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/satwarmup.htm|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Race Morning Warmup|date=14 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605125337/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/satwarmup.htm|archive-date=5 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68413|title=Heat leak hits Team Nasamax|date=14 June 2003|publisher=Crash|access-date=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050124213234/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68413|archive-date=24 January 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\n\n===Start===\nThunderstorms were forecast, and despite an earlier heavy rain shower, the weather at the start of the race was clear. The air temperature approached {{Convert|28|C|F|abbr=on}}.<ref name=AutosportStart>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23398|title=The race is go!|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620080548/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23398|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Approximately 220,000 people attended the event.<ref name=\"RacingReferenceResults\" /> The two Bentley Speed 8s underwent checks to their [[ride height]]s,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68317|title=Le Mans 2003 is go!!|date=14 June 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030915024702/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68317|archive-date=15 September 2003|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Ray Mallock rectified a faulty [[Transmission (mechanics)|gearbox]] that leaked oil in the No. 64 [[Saleen S7|Saleen S7-R]], and Kondo Racing replaced the No. 9 Dome S101's [[V8 engine]] after a water leak.<ref name=DSCH1to3>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans1_3.htm|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 1 \u2013 3|date=14 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620051601/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans1_3.htm|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> The [[Flag of France|French tricolour]] was waved by the founder of the ALMS [[Don Panoz]] at 16:00 [[Central European Summer Time]] to signal the start of the race,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.italiaspeed.com/news_2003_sportscars/news_089_lemans_acemco_result.html|title=80th Le Mans 24 Hours: Engine Failure Ends AMECO's Charge Into GT Class Lead at Le Mans|date=16 June 2003|publisher=ItaliaSpeed.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031007040830/http://www.italiaspeed.com/news_2003_sportscars/news_089_lemans_acemco_result.html|archive-date=7 October 2003|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> led by the starting pole sitter Capello's No. 7 Bentley.<ref name=AutosportStart/> 49 cars planned to take the start following the withdrawal of the Lister Storm LMP,<ref>{{cite web|title=80\u00b0 \u00e9dition: 49 voitures au d\u00e9part|url=http://www.spiritof.com.fr:80/spirit%20of/spirit3/LM/lm2003/audepart.htm|publisher=Spirit Of|language=French|date=13 June 2003|accessdate=25 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030625192413/http://www.spiritof.com.fr/spirit%20of/spirit3/LM/lm2003/audepart.htm|archivedate=25 June 2003|url-status=dead}},</ref> but the No. 25 Gerard Welter WR LMP02 was in the [[Pit stop|pit lane]] with a mechanical fault.<ref name=DSCH1to3/> Capello maintained the lead and Lammers' Racing for Holland car passed Magnussen's Team Goh Audi for third.<ref name=AutosportStart/> At the end of the first lap, Gavin brought the No. 50 Corvette into the pit lane with a throttle linkage problem that lost the car 26 minutes and dropped it to last overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68331|title=Early hiccup for defending GTS champs|date=14 June 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050124213130/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68331|archive-date=24 January 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Lammers fell from second to sixth when the three privateer Audis passed him as Bentley quickly pulled away from the rest of the field. Herbert briefly took the lead from Capello before making the No. 8 Bentley's first pit stop of the event on lap 10. Meanwhile, Intersport's Lola-MG vehicle moved to the front of LMP675 after the RN Motorsport Zytek developed car trouble and Alex Job Racing led the LMGT category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23398|title=Hour 1: Bentley leads the way|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620080548/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23398|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first hour of the race ended with the first crash as the No. 91 [[TVR Tuscan Speed Six|TVR Tuscan T400R]] of Richard Stanton was hit from behind by a Gerard Walter WR LMP02 car in the Porsche Curves, sending him into the outside concrete barrier at the exit to the complex.<ref name=TVRCrash>{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68336|title=TVR challenged halved inside one hour?|date=14 June 2003|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050124213133/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68336|archive-date=24 January 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> The impact broke the Tuscan's right-rear [[Suspension (vehicle)|suspension]], stranding Stanton at the complex of turns.<ref name=TVRCrash/> The car was retired after repairs made to its [[Differential (mechanical device)|differential]] by Stanton to make it drive-able for a return to the pit lane proved unsuccessful.<ref name=\"DSCH1to3\" /> Not long after, Capello locked the No. 7 Bentley's brakes going into the right-hand Mulsanne Corner and he slowed to stop the car from spinning into a gravel trap. He held off Herbert in a large amount of slower traffic until Herbert passed him to retake the lead on the 23rd lap. Kristensen relieved Capello in the No. 7 Bentley and retook the overall lead from Lehto's Audi R8 three laps later. Brabham's sister No. 8 car was called into the pit lane to have a loose door frame fixed in a ten-second stop. [[Casper Elgaard]] had been the fastest driver in LMP675 at the time, returning the RN Motorsport Zytek to the lead of the class.<ref name=MCOMH2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/no-8-bentley-survives-but-biela-comes-up-empty/126729/|title=No. 8 Bentley survives, but Biela comes up empty|date=15 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620151125/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/no-8-bentley-survives-but-biela-comes-up-empty/126729/|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Audi Sport UK instructed Birla to enter the pit lane on lap 28. He was prevented from doing so by a Panoz prototype vehicle to his right and was required to complete an additional lap.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lemans.org/en/news/frank-biela-out-of-gas/12954|title=Frank Biela: out of gas...|last=Hergault|first=Julien|last2=Light|first2=Tony|date=30 October 2013|publisher=Automobile Club de l'Ouest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105225329/https://www.lemans.org/en/news/frank-biela-out-of-gas/12954|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> The R8 slowed with a lack of fuel through Mulsanne Corner and it was retired at the side of the track after Biela's attempt to weave and keep the car running on its [[Starter (engine)|starter]] failed.<ref name=MCOMH2/>\n\nIn the third hour, Kristensen almost made contact with [[Jean-Marc Gounon]]'s [[Courage Comp\u00e9tition]] Judd exiting the pit lane.<ref name=CloseCallBentley>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-has-close-call-but-maintains-lead/126740/|title=Bentley has close call but maintains lead|date=15 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620194113/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-has-close-call-but-maintains-lead/126740/|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> [[Beppe Gabbiani]]'s Racing for Holland car hit Kelly Collins' No. 50 Corvette at Arnage corner and both cars spun.<ref name=\"DSCH1to3\" /> Brabham's No. 8 Bentley passed Werner's Team Goh Audi R8 for second at the Dunlop Curve though Werner used slower traffic to retake the position. Brabham returned to second when Werner entered the pit lane as the RN Motorsport Zytek car lost the lead of the LMP675 class to No\u00ebl del Bello Racing's Reynard car of [[Didier Andr\u00e9]] as its [[Alternator (automotive)|alternator]] was changed.<ref name=\"CloseCallBentley\" /> [[Safety car]]s were deployed after 3 hours and 40 minutes to slow the race because oil was laid by an unknown car between the Mulsanne and Indianapolis turns.<ref name=\"DSCH4to6\">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans4_6.htm|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 4 \u2013 6|date=14 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620084741/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans4_6.htm|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=dead|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> This prompted several cars to make pit stops and brought much of the field closer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23405|title=Hour 4: Oil on the track|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620194116/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23405|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> In the main LMP categories, the safety cars separated the field, leaving the Bentleys more than 2 minutes and 17 seconds of each other, 50 seconds ahead of Werner's Team Goh Audi and another 50 seconds in front of [[Stefan Johansson]]'s Champion Racing car.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/oil-spill-at-mulsanne-brings-out-safety-cars/126749/|title=Oil spill at Mulsanne brings out safety cars|date=15 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190620194116/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/oil-spill-at-mulsanne-brings-out-safety-cars/126749/|archive-date=20 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> The lead of LMGT changed as [[Emmanuel Collard]]'s Alex Job Racing Porsche was forced into the pit lane with a malfunctioning gearshift, allowing Buckler's The Racer's Group vehicle to take the category lead until Bernhard made an unscheduled pit stop to replace a heavily slipping [[clutch]].<ref name=DSCH4to6/> The No. 88 Prodrive Ferrari of [[Jamie Davies]] came to the pit lane for a two-minute stop to rectify a water leak, ceding the lead to the sister No. 80 car of [[Kelvin Burt]].<ref name=DSCH4to6/>\n\n===Night===\nAs night fell, the lead of the LMP675 category switched from the No. 29 No\u00ebl del Bello Racing's Reynard vehicle to the Intersport Racing MG-Lola car,<ref name=\"DSCH4to6\" /> which later had an anxious moment when driver [[Duncan Dayton]] spun at the PlayStation chicane. He managed to retain the lead in the class.<ref name=MCOMH7>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-leads-the-way-into-darkness/126788/|title=Bentley leads the way into darkness|date=15 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621091612/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-leads-the-way-into-darkness/126788/|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> Soon after, [[Tom Coronel]]'s St Team Orange Spyker C8 Double-12R stopped at the entry to the pit lane with a clutch failure. He exited the car to push it beyond a white line denoting where his pit crew could provide assistance. Coronel was then told by a trackside marshal that he was not permitted to push the car any further and it dropped out of reach of completing the laps necessary for classification.<ref name=\"DSCH4to6\" /> At the front of the field, the gap between Smith and Capello's No. 7 Bentley and Blundell and Herbert's sister No. 8 car was 33 seconds. Third position was the Champion Racing Audi R8 of Pirro and [[Seiji Ara]]'s Team Goh entry was fourth.<ref name=MCOMH7/> The LMGTS category was a close battle between the Prodrive pair of Kox and [[Anthony Davidson]],<ref name=DSCH7to9>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans7_9.htm|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 7 \u2013 9|date=14 June 2003|publisher=DailySportsCar|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621090022/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans7_9.htm|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=dead|access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> as both cars set next to identical lap times during the seventh hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23421|title=Hour 7: Green and red in the dark|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621192016/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23421|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> [[Ron Fellows]]' No. 53 Corvette equalled their pace until the Ferraris responded by increasing their speed.<ref name=DSCH7to9/> In the eighth hour, Davidson spun into a gravel trap at the PlayStation chicane.<ref name=MCOMH8>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/pit-confusion-adds-to-herbert-s-woes-still-trails-capello/126809/|title=Pit confusion adds to Herbert's woes, still trails Capello|date=15 June 2003|publisher=motorsport.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621192013/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/pit-confusion-adds-to-herbert-s-woes-still-trails-capello/126809/|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> The resulting pit stop to change the No. 80 Prodrive Ferrari's tyres and a precautionary check lost Davidson two laps and third place in LMGTS to Fellows.<ref name=\"DSCH7to9\" /><ref name=MCOMH8/><ref name=AutosportH8>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23421|title=Hour 8: dropping like flies|date=14 June 2003|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621192016/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23421|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live|access-date=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nEighth place overall became a multi-car battle between [[David Saelens]]' Panoz, the Courage Comp\u00e9tition of Gounon and [[Christophe Tinseau]]'s Riley & Scott Mk III C-Ford; all three drivers were within 20 seconds of each other. Tinseau bowed out of the battle after a routine pit stop, leaving Saelens and Gounon 18 seconds apart.<ref name=MCOMH8/> On lap 116, Herbert's No. 8 Bentley made a pit stop; a miscommunication between the mechanic holding a [[Jack (device)|jack]] and a rear tyre fitter lost him ten seconds.<ref name=MCOMH8/><ref name=AutosportH8/> 19 laps later, Lammers' Racing for Holland car lowered a 15-second gap through its faster pace to pass [[Olivier Beretta]]'s Riley & Scott Ford in the final third of the lap for fifth overall.<ref name=MCOMH9>{{cite web|title=Jan Lammers flies into fifth, Bentleys still lead|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/jan-lammers-flies-into-fifth-bentleys-still-lead/126821/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=21 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621205314/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/jan-lammers-flies-into-fifth-bentleys-still-lead/126821/|archive-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> Soon after, Beretta picked up a puncture from hitting debris on the dirty side of the [[Mulsanne Straight]] at {{convert|190|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and slowed en route to the pit lane.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beretta dodges a bullet|url=https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140328/1/beretta-dodges-a-bullet|publisher=Crash|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=21 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621205323/https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140328/1/beretta-dodges-a-bullet|archive-date=21 June 2019}}</ref> The second-place car in the LMGTS category, the No. 50 Corvette of Fellows, was hindered by a suspected [[Serpentine belt|alternator belt]] failure and entered the pit lane. Mechanics found it was a broken [[pulley]] operating the vehicle's [[Oil pump (internal combustion engine)|oil pump]]. They replaced the support and the [[Automotive battery|battery]], enabling Fellows to rejoin the circuit fourth in class.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Le Mans Nine-Hour Report: Corvette On The Move|url=http://corvetteracing.com/race_news/racenews_set.htm|publisher=Corvette Racing|date=14 June 2003|accessdate=21 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030820112850/http://corvetteracing.com/race_news/racenews_set.htm|archivedate=20 August 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Kristensen's No. 7 Bentley had a 1-minute and 40-second pit stop to have minor damage at the front of the car repaired; he retained the overall lead over Brabham's sister No. 8 car. Luhr's No. 83 Alex Job Racing Porsche succumbed to raised oil and water temperatures caused by a sharp rock penerating its radiator. It spent 24 minutes and five laps having its radiator replaced and Luhr ceded the LMGT class lead to Kazuyuki Nishizawa's No. 77 Team Taisan Advan car.<ref name=MCOMH10>{{cite web|title=Audis attack, falter in the wee hours|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/audis-attack-falter-in-the-wee-hours/126838/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=21 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621205310/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/audis-attack-falter-in-the-wee-hours/126838/|archive-date=21 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AJRLoseGTLead\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68430|title=AJR strikes problems|date=15 June 2003|publisher=Crash|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050124211107/http://www.crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68430|archive-date=24 January 2005|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nMagnussen spun at the Ford chicane and damaged the front suspension on Team Goh's Audi R8.<ref name=DSCH10to12>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 10 \u2013 12|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans10_12.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621200931/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans10_12.htm|archivedate=21 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> He drove the car to the pit lane and mechanics took 8 minutes and 53 seconds to make repairs. The car rejoined in fourth place with Werner driving.<ref name=MCOMH10/> No\u00ebl del Bello Racing had an anxious moment when driver [[Jean-Luc Maury-Laribi\u00e8re]] spun into a gravel trap at the Dunlop Curves. He recovered with assistance from trackside marshals without losing the LMP675 class lead. [[Soheil Ayari]]'s No. 18 Courage vehicle overtook [[Scott Maxwell]]'s No. 12 Panoz LMP01 Evo car for ninth overall and pulled away.<ref name=MCOMH11to12>{{cite web|title=Kristensen, Smith hang on to lead at midway point|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/kristensen-smith-hang-on-to-lead-at-midway-point/126873/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093646/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/kristensen-smith-hang-on-to-lead-at-midway-point/126873/|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> All three of the top cars in LMGT were within a lap of each other, led by [[Johnny Mowlem]]'s No. 94 [[Risi Competizione]] Ferrari after Team Taisan Advan made a pit stop to replace the driver's-side door. Mowlem held it until his car's engine failed on the Mulsanne Straight and ceded the lead of the class to Lieb's Orbit Porsche.<ref name=DSCH10to12/> Werner's Team Goh Audi R8 twice drove into its garage for repairs to its [[engine control unit]] and lost 10 minutes and 14 seconds. Werner rejoined 3 minutes and 20 seconds in front of [[Andy Wallace (racing driver)|Andy Wallace]]'s No. 15 Racing for Holland car.<ref name=MCOMH11to12/><ref>{{cite web|title=Hour 12: Battles everywhere but the front|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23426|work=Autosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093644/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23426|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> As the race approached its halfway point, the No. 7 Bentley of Smith lapped two to five seconds faster than Blundell's No. 8 car and increased the vehicle's overall lead to 1 minute and 20 seconds.<ref name=MCOMH11to12/>\n\n===Morning to early afternoon===\nIn the 12th hour, the second-placed car in LMGTS, Davidson's No. 80 Prodrive Ferrari had a right-front wheel bearing fault at {{convert|175|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and was sent into a barrier at the end of the Mulsanne Straight.<ref>{{cite web|title=2003 24 Heures du Le Mans|url=http://www.superstreetonline.com/event-coverage/motorsports/0309ec-2003-lemans|work=[[European Car (magazine)|European Car]]|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622083148/http://www.superstreetonline.com/event-coverage/motorsports/0309ec-2003-lemans|archivedate=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He extricated himself from the car and was tended to by trackside marshals. Davidson was transported by ambulance to the infield medical centre for circuit doctors to examine him.<ref name=\":0\" /> They found he had sustained bruising and a head concussion from hitting his head against a door; he was taken to Centre Hospitalier Le Mans for a brain scan.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Davidson bruised but otherwise okay|url=https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140330/1/davidson-bruised-but-otherwise-okay|publisher=Crash|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093646/https://www.crash.net/le-mans/news/140330/1/davidson-bruised-but-otherwise-okay|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/bentley-power-to-first-24-hour-victory-in-seven-decades-109016.html|title=Bentley power to first 24-hour victory in seven decades|last=Allsop|first=Derick|date=16 June 2003|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=22 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622203701/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/bentley-power-to-first-24-hour-victory-in-seven-decades-109016.html|archive-date=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The Ferrari's retirement elevated the No. 50 Corvette C5-R of Gavin to second in LMGTS. Prodrive asked Kox in the No. 88 Ferrari to enter the pit lane for a precautionary brake check. Not long after, a low voltage indicator warning and no radio communication to the No. 8 Bentley's pit stall prompted Blundell to make a pit stop for a replacement battery, losing the car two laps to the sister No. 7 entry. The lead of LMGT continued to be closely fought with the No. 93 Alex Job Racing Porsche heading the field until a front splitter problem forced it into the pit lane for four minutes, giving the position to Lieb's Orbit vehicle. Because of the mechanical attrition affecting the Porsche 996s in the LMGT category, only two Porsches remained in contention for a victory and Ferrari could not challenge the marque.<ref name=DSCH13to15>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 13 \u2013 15|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans13_15.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622081838/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans13_15.htm|archivedate=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Front suspension problems for the No. 12 Panoz car and an engine failure that curtailed the No. 4 Riley & Scott Mk III C's race promoted the No. 88 Prodrive Ferrari to tenth overall.<ref name=DSCH13to15/><ref>{{cite web|title=Hour 16: It's easy being green|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23431|work=Autosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622093646/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23431|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhr and Maashen's No. 93 Alex Job Racing Porsche was able to fight with Lieb and later [[Leo Hindery]]'s No. 87 Orbit car and eventually retake the lead of the LMGT category it had lost when it entered the pit lane for car repairs.<ref name=DSCH16to18>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 16 \u2013 18|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans16_18.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605125349/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans16_18.htm|archivedate=5 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> An hour and 20 minutes later, Lammers picked up a left-rear puncture, losing control of the No. 15 Racing For Holland car when he braked.<ref name=DSCH16to18/> He spun several times backwards into a gravel trap at Indianapolis corner and damaged one of the car's rear wheels. The car was pushed back onto the circuit by track marshals and Lammers drove to the pit lane to repair the damage. At the same time, [[Gunnar Jeannette]]'s No. 11 Panoz LMP01 Evo car locked up and made light contact with the tyre barrier at Arnage corner.<ref name=MCOMBentleyMO>{{cite web|title=Bentley motors on|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-motors-on/126908/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131151/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentley-motors-on/126908/|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hour 17: Lammers spins but survives|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23433|work=Autosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131158/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23433|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> Further up the field, Brabham made an unscheduled pit stop in the No. 8 Bentley to undergo a second battery replacement. The change took 3 minutes and 32 seconds and the car returned to the race in second overall. Not long after Collins' No. 50 Corvette bowed out of the battle for the LMGTS lead to have its transmission bearing replaced and it was completed in 15 minutes. Lehto's Champion Racing R8 could not take advantage of the No. 8 Bentley's mechanical impairments and lost one additional lap after a spin.<ref name=DSCH16to18/><ref name=MCOMBentleyMO/> At the start of the 18th hour, Saelens in the No. 12 Panoz car lost [[Grip (auto racing)|grip]] through Mulsanne corner and made left-front contact with a tyre barrier at high speed. Saelens was unhurt; the damage to the car forced its retirement.<ref name=MCOMSCHighNoon>{{cite web|title=Safety cars back out before high noon|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/safety-cars-back-out-before-high-noon/126919/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131152/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/safety-cars-back-out-before-high-noon/126919/|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe No. 93 Alex Job Racing Porsche of Maassen entered the garage with loss of voltage that was rectified by a six-minute change of the alternator. Maassen returned to the track still in the lead of the LMGT category.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Alex Job Racing \u2013 Petersen Motorsports/White Lightining Racing: Fifth Report (8:30 a.m. \u2013 1:30 p.m.)|url=http://www.alexjobracing.com/03_lemans/0615c.htm|publisher=Alex Job Racing|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030626124508/http://www.alexjobracing.com/03_lemans/0615c.htm|archivedate=26 June 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Soon after, Wallace's No. 15 Racing for Holland Dome had a flat battery that dropped the car from fifth to eighth overall.<ref name=DSCH19to21>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 19 \u2013 21|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans19_21.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622102945/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans19_21.htm|archivedate=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Gabbiani's sister No. 16 car had its front-left tyre delaminate and carbon fibre debris was launched from the car's front-left corner. Safety cars were required for the second time as the track needed cleaning and prompted several cars to make pit stops. Beretta's No. 11 Panoz car was the main beneficiary from the safety car period and he passed [[Jonathan Cochet]]'s No. 13 Courage C60 vehicle on the Mulsanne Straight for fifth overall.<ref name=MCOMSCHighNoon/> Towards the end of the 20th hour, the LMP675 class leading No\u00ebl del Bello Reynard slowed with a misfiring engine but the car's 35-lap advantage kept it in the category lead.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hour 20: Drama at high noon|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23437|work=Autosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131157/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23437|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> The No. 15 Racing for Holland car of John Bosch returned to seventh<ref name=DSCH19to21/> when Ayari's No. 18 Courage C60 began leaking fluids at the car's rear and entered the pit lane for a 22-minute repair.<ref name=MCOMH21to22>{{cite web|title=Bentleys, Audis hold station into the final two hours|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentleys-audis-hold-station-into-the-final-two-hours/126933/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131156/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/bentleys-audis-hold-station-into-the-final-two-hours/126933/|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> With the first four positions stable, attention focused on the battle for fifth place between the No. 11 Panoz LMP01 Evo and the No. 13 Courage C60 cars.<ref name=AutosportH21>{{cite web|title=Hour 21: Bentley closes on win|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23443|work=Autosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622131151/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/23443|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> The No. 99 XL Racing Ferrari of Ga\u00ebl Lasoudier had an rear engine bay fire at the PlayStation Chicane, causing the deployment of the safety cars for the third time in the race.<ref name=MCOMH21to22/>\n\n===Finish===\nAs the safety car period ended, [[Max Papis]] in the No. 11 Panoz LMP01 Evo car caught and passed [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]]'s No. 13 Courage C60 vehicle at Tetre Rouge corner. Fellows overtook his Corvette Racing teammate Collins in the final third of the lap for second in LMGTS. Collins retook the position from Fellows two laps later until they made pit stops for fuel, tyres and a change of driver. O'Connell relieved Fellows and returned to second by having a faster stop than [[Andy Pilgrim]]. The No. 17 Pescarolo Courage 60 car of [[Jean-Christophe Boullion]]'s had a flash fire when fuel ignited during a pit stop. An intervention from the team's mechanics to extinguish the fire allowed him to continue driving.<ref name=MCOMH21to22/> The Champion Racing Audi of Johansson stalled during a pit stop for tyres, fuel and a driver switch with co-driver Pirro. The fault was rectified by replacing the car's battery at the right-hand corner of its cockpit. It rejoined the track still in third place and ahead of Ara's Team Goh Audi.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final hour begins at Le Mans|url=https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/final-hour-begins-at-le-mans/126938/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622184253/https://www.motorsport.com/lemans/news/final-hour-begins-at-le-mans/126938/|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> Lammers' No. 15 Racing for Holland Dome car in seventh caught and overtook Gounon's No. 13 Courage Comp\u00e9tition C60 vehicle on the race's final lap to claim sixth overall for his team. In the meantime, [[Tristan Gommendy]] crashed at the Indianapolis corner. He drove the No. 16 Racing for Holland car into the pit lane to retire.<ref name=DSCH22to24>{{cite web|title=The 71st Le Mans 24 Hours: Hours 22 - 24|url=http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans22_24.htm|publisher=DailySportsCar|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605125423/http://archive.dailysportscar.com/subscribers/lemans/2003/qual_race/71lemans22_24.htm|archivedate=5 June 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nUnhindered in the final hours of the race, Smith took the [[Racing flags#Chequered flag|chequered flag]] for the No. 8 Bentley, two laps ahead of the No. 7 Bentley of Brabham.<ref name=DSCH22to24/> Audi, in their first defeat at Le Mans since the [[2000 24 Hours of Le Mans|2000 edition]], were a further three laps behind in third to win the LMP900 class with Champion Racing's R8 and Team Goh took fourth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Privateer Audi proud of podium|url=http://crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68636|publisher=Crash|date=16 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040127163353/http://crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68636|archivedate=27 January 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=The 2003 season in review|url=https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/the-2003-season-in-review-8705|publisher=Audi Media Center|date=27 November 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622184256/https://www.audi-mediacenter.com/en/press-releases/the-2003-season-in-review-8705|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> It was Smith and Capello's first Le Mans victory and Kristensen's fifth.<ref name=EurosportBentleyWin>{{cite web|title=Historic 1-2 for Bentley|url=http://www.eurosport.com/home/pages/V3/L0/S76/E5522/sport_Lng0_Spo76_Evt5522_Sto445506.shtml|publisher=Eurosport|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030617213140/http://www.eurosport.com/home/pages/V3/L0/S76/E5522/sport_Lng0_Spo76_Evt5522_Sto445506.shtml|archivedate=17 June 2003|url-status=dead}}</ref> Kristensen became the first driver in history to win the 24 Hours of Le Mans four times in a row.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also equalled [[Derek Bell (racing driver)|Derek Bell]]'s record of five victories and was one behind [[Jacky Ickx]]'s all-time record of six wins.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Bentley's historic Le Mans win|url=https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/bentleys-historic-le-mans-win/|work=Car Magazine|date=16 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622151535/https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/bentleys-historic-le-mans-win/https://web.archive.org/web/20190622151535/https://www.carmag.co.za/news-blog/bentleys-historic-le-mans-win/|archivedate=22 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was Bentley's sixth overall Le Mans victory and its first since the [[1930 24 Hours of Le Mans|1930 race]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bentley claim Le Mans crown|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/2986658.stm|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040704063222/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/2986658.stm|archive-date=4 July 2004}}</ref> Prodrive held their ten-lap lead in the LMGTS category,<ref>{{cite web|title=First Ferrari GT victory at Le Mans since 1974 \u2013 looking forward to UK FIA GT Race on 29 June|url=https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/first-ferrari-gt-victory-le-mans-1974-looking-forward-uk-fia-gt-race-29-june|work=Classic Driver|date=18 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622184251/https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/first-ferrari-gt-victory-le-mans-1974-looking-forward-uk-fia-gt-race-29-june|archive-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> earning Enge, Kox and Davies their first class victories and the first for Ferrari in a GT class since the [[1981 24 Hours of Le Mans|1981 edition]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=76835&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|title=LM GTS: Ferrari redore son prestigieux blason|last=Panighini|first=Phillipe|date=16 June 2003|work=Ouest-France|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050710044551/http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=76835&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|archive-date=10 July 2005|url-status=dead|language=French}}</ref> Corvette Racing completed the class podium with the No. 50 ahead of the No. 53.<ref name=RacingReferenceResults/> Porsche took the first six places in the LMGT class with Alex Job Racing taking the category win on the team's first visit to Le Mans. Orbit Racing and Thierry Perrier were the final two category podium finishers in second and third.<ref>{{cite web|title=Porsche rivals combine for Le Mans win|url=http://crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68548|publisher=Crash|date=15 June 2003|accessdate=22 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040127205518/http://crash.net/uk/en/news_view.asp?cid=28&nid=68548|archivedate=27 January 2004|url-status=dead}}</ref> No\u00ebl del Bello Racing, unchallenged since the night, were victorious in the LMP675 class,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=76836&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|title=LMP 675. \u2013 Nouvelle victoire de la Reynard-Lehmann: No\u00ebl Del Bello double la mise|last=Virfeu|first=Boris|date=16 June 2003|work=Ouest-France|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050710115408/http://www.ouest-france.fr/Dossiers/24heures2003_autoactu.asp?IdArt=76836&IdThe=&IdCla=3794&NomCla=Les+24+heures+du+Mans+auto&PageCour=1&PageTot=2|archive-date=10 July 2005|url-status=dead|language=French}}</ref> 31 laps ahead of the RN Motorsport Zytek and 84 laps in front of Rachel Welter's WR LMP01.<ref name=RacingReferenceResults>{{cite web|title=2003 24 Hours of Le Mans|url=https://www.racing-reference.info/race/2003-05/X|publisher=Racing-Reference|accessdate=22 June 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606022853/https://www.racing-reference.info/race/2003-05/X|archive-date=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Race classification==\nThe minimum number of laps for classification (70% of the overall winning car's race distance) was 264 laps. Class winners are denoted with '''bold''' and {{double-dagger}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Class\n! rowspan=\"2\" |{{Abb